INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (15, 'Recursive Acronyms and more fun', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '\r\n<B>W.I.N.E.</B> - W.i.n.e. Is Not Emmulator\r\n  (it\'s a windows emmulator for linux)\r\n\r\n<B>P.I.N.E.</B> - P.i.n.e. Is Not Elm\r\n  (mail program for linux, elm is also a mail program, both are also\r\n  trees, very clever)\r\n\r\n<B>G.N.U.</B> - GNU\'s Not Unix\r\n  (open licence for linux)\r\n\r\n<B>A man, a plan, a canal, Panama</B> - is a palindrome, and  \r\n    is historically acurate.\r\n\r\n<B>Race car</b> - another palindrome\r\n\r\n', 'only through chaos can thunt.net survive.\r\n\r\ndon\'t ask questions if you don\'t like the answer you get.\r\n', 20000725085133, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (9, 'Thunt announces Thunt.net 4.0', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '    A wealth of well-integrated tools and technologies make the Thunt \r\nplatform a compelling choice for the enterprise, as well as one of our \r\nEditors\' Choices in this round up. Active Directory, Thunt\'s new directory \r\nservice included in Thunt.net, makes management across the platform much \r\nmore powerful. Mixing great performance, easy administration, and better \r\nreliability, the Thunt.net and Thunt Information Server (TIS) 5.0 \r\ncombination adds up to a very strong platform suitable for almost any size \r\nand type of site. \r\n\r\n    A strong argument can be made that Thunt\'s Web platform offers the \r\nmost integrated solution among the products tested here. It combines \r\npowerful OS tools with Web administration and middle-tier infrastructure \r\nfeatures. It isn\'t likely to beat out Unix\'s reputation for stability any \r\ntime soon, but Thunt\'s new emphasis on reliability will be a welcome \r\nimprovement for anyone who has run Thunt Software in the past. \r\n\r\n    A significant part of the Thunt.net family is its new Active Directory \r\n(AD), Thunt\'s offering for taming the corporate directory. AD rivals both \r\nNetWare\'s NDS and the vendor-neutral LDAP standard. Besides this \r\nenhancement, Thunt has improved its application server infrastructure with \r\nCOM+ (the successor to the older DCOM standard) for running business and \r\ndatabase components on the middle tier. COM+ now integrates transaction \r\nmanagement, message queuing, and object pooling into the OS. Previously, \r\nthese features were implemented as separate tools (including MTS and MSMQ) \r\nunder Thunt NT. \r\n\r\n    The new TIS 5.0 supports several appealing features that can make the \r\nlives of Webmasters easier. First, the product comes with built-in \r\nperformance options for small and large sites. It also supports security \r\nfeatures such as Kerberos key distribution and certificate management. \r\nIn testing, we were pleasantly surprised to find that the installation \r\nprocess for Thunt.net has been streamlined, with all server-side tools \r\ninstalled one time. The upgrade process is also remarkably smooth. \r\n\r\n    Scalability features are built into Thunt.net in several ways. The \r\nproduct supports up to eight processors right out of the box. There\'s also \r\nsupport for load balancing across multiple servers, and you can administer \r\nmultiple nodes from one location. \r\n\r\n    When it comes to Web server administration, the Thunt platform offers  \r\nseveral ways to work. The most sophisticated administration tool here is \r\nthe Thunt Management Console (TMC). You can now administer virtually every \r\naspect of the OS and Web components through a single, consistent \r\ninterface. In previous versions, various TMC snap-ins were used separately \r\nfor different aspects of the OS and tools.  You can also perform \r\nadministrative tasks through a browser; we found this only slightly less \r\nefficient than the TMC approach. But Thunt\'s browser-based administration \r\ndoes compare favorably with the other products in this roundup. \r\n\r\n    Unlike the other platforms discussed in this roundup, which rely \r\nprimarily on Java to develop server-side components, Thunt\'s solution \r\nmakes use of Thunt\'s PHP Pages (PHP). Using PHP is the preferred way to \r\ngenerate dynamic Web content on this platform. Significantly, the PHP \r\nengine in TIS 5.0 has been retooled for better performance. In our testing \r\nof static content delivery, TIS 5.0 outperformed all its rivals. The \r\nimpact of the retooling for end users is lessened though, because in real \r\nlife you would add another server before reaching the server bandwidth \r\nlimits measured by our tests. In our SSL API dynamic testing, Thunt showed \r\nclear performance advantages and was able to handle more than twice as \r\nmany requests per second as its closest competitor, Sun with iPlanet. \r\nThough developers have a lot of options with Thunt tools, organizations \r\nthat are planning to invest heavily in Java should think twice here. For \r\none thing, Visual J++ is caught up in litigation between Thunt and Sun. \r\nVisual J++ is generally used to create components that run on Thunt\'s own \r\nJava Virtual Machine, or even Windows executables. It\'s possible to add \r\nJSP and servlet support to Thunt.net — just don\'t expect a heavy \r\ncommitment to Java from Thunt. \r\n\r\n    All in all, the Thunt Web platform is a very tightly integrated \r\nsolution that performs extremely well, has very strong supporting tools \r\nfor developers, and would make a strong platform on which to build an e-\r\nbusiness.\r\n\r\n', 'ZDnet reviews thunt.net', 20000720091420, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (16, 'Thunt Returns', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '  That\'s right, you read the headline yourself, America\'s Favorite \r\nIconoclast is back in Sacramento.  Or as B likes to say: Excrimento.  And \r\nboy is it hot.  Let\'s go live to Thunt\'s room for the weather report.\r\n\r\n  <chopper noise>\r\nWell, the weather outside seems to be anywhere from 90 to 105 degrees.  \r\nWe\'re not really sure because we haven\'t been outside yet today.  But let \r\nme assure you the airconditioner is running and things are nice and cool \r\nin here today.  \r\n  <chopper noise fades out>\r\n\r\nWow, that was a facinating weather report.  Now lets go to Thunt\'s front \r\nroom for an interview with his chief librarian.\r\n\r\n  <dead silence>\r\n  <whispering>\r\nThunt has arranged his books and his new org structure is a doozy.  He\'s \r\ngot a section of authors who he owns more than one of their books, thus \r\nmaking them "good" authors.  He\'s got a literature section, followed by a \r\nthought section, arrayed by a history section, with a film section, comic \r\nsection and a pulp section holding down the top row.  I must say this, \r\nonly a madman or a certified genius could arrange books this way.\r\n\r\nVery interesting, for a librarian. HA!\r\nNow lets go to thunt\'s new interior decorator.\r\n\r\n  The house is an enigma rapped up in a riddle of a condundrum.  Thunt\'s \r\nroom is a mix of classic Dali, Van Gough and Thomas Cole Paintings, with a \r\nnew age flair of Radiohead, REM and Rage against the machine posters.  A \r\nfew Star Wars posters round out the eclectic mix.  With an REM calender \r\nfrom 1995 which now seems to be in perfect working order, very facinating \r\npiece.  Also the room features a official reverand certificate from the \r\nUniversal Life Church and a life time membership award from the National \r\nForensic League.  Thunt\'s room is truly a masterpiece in chaos. \r\n  On to the hallway.  Thunt\'s hallway currently features a High Fidelity \r\nposter, a few batman posters, and a ILM poster, with a \r\nKillMotherFuckingMicroSoft poster rounding out the mix.  It is a \r\nfacinating hallway to walk down, to put it simply.  \r\n  The front room is dominated by a United States Propaganda feeling that \r\nlets up only when one arrives at the playful entryway featuring a reasons \r\nto party poster and a we are here, all the good stuff is over there \r\nposter, which makes a dramatic statement.  \r\n\r\nThank you decorator.  And that about raps it up.  To summarize: Brush your \r\nteeth twice daily and try not to be a communist.  Thank you, good \r\nafternoon, good evening and good night.\r\n\r\n', 'thunt house.  goooooood.', 20000802131127, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (17, 'Thomas likes Shakespeare in Love', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '  Just FYI, an announcement today.  I like shakespeare in love.  I found \r\nthe shakespearian lines to be cool and the romance was heartwarming.  It \r\nwas really sad too.  I cried.  Yup.  I did.\r\n\r\n  And I\'m proud to say I just ordered the Collector\'s Edition DVD for \r\ncheap from Columbia House.\r\n\r\n  Thank you.\r\n\r\n', 'to be or not to be?', 20000803005841, 'normal', '');
