INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (32, '<B>Thomas Hunt</B>: <i>The Definative Interview</i>', 'Thunt.net', '', '\r\nIt is our very special privilege today to interview the founder of \r\nThunt.net, and a frequent author on Thunt.net, Thomas Hunt.  Thomas is a \r\nself styled iconoclast, star of stage and screen, he has most recently \r\nappeared alongside Michael Keaton in the Broadway version of "<B>The \r\nPaper</B>", he played the loveable tramp in Martin Scorsesse’s "<B>Really, \r\nReally, Really</B>" and is currently writing a short play about Watergate \r\ntentatively titled "<B>Sucks Big</B>, <B>Dick</B>".\r\n\r\n<B>Thunt.net: </B>Thank you for being with us today Mr. Hunt, we \r\nunderstand that your time is valuable, not to be wasted by pointless \r\nmeetings on marketing, backwards ass discussions of that so called cyber-\r\njournalism and other such pointless drivel that so many people try to \r\nforce upon those who have the courage to rise above the rest.\r\n\r\n<B>Mr. Hunt: </B>It’s a pleasure to be here, to tell you the truth I’m a \r\nbig fan of the show.\r\n\r\n<B>Thunt.net: </B>We get that so often, but when coming from a true \r\nhumanitarian like you, it really means a lot.  Now let’s get down to \r\nbusiness.  I understand that yesterday you wrote an article about Andrew \r\nHoratio Duong and I have heard that it is raising quite a stir.\r\n\r\n<B>Mr. Hunt: </B>That’s right.  I just wanted to take a moment to tell the \r\nworld what I really think about Mr. Duong.  He is a true compassionate \r\nhuman being who is years ahead of his time.  He’s bound to only be \r\nappreciated after he is long dead and I think that is really lame.  I know \r\na lot of people, and Mr. Duong, he’s just, the kind of guy who without \r\nbatting an eyelash would use the word "poon-tang" in mixed company.  Men \r\nwith that kind of balls only come along once, maybe twice a generation.  \r\nAmerica should learn to treasure this type of man, and Mr. Andrew Horatio \r\nDuong is certainly that type of man.\r\n\r\n<B>Thunt.net: </B>You seem to be a natural leader, a sort of God among \r\nmen.  In your time you’ve probably seen many inept leaders, what \r\nattributes should a leader avoid?\r\n\r\n<B>Mr. Hunt: </B>That’s a really good question.  The most important thing \r\nthat a leader should have is the respect of her associates.  If they laugh \r\nat her, even once, it completely undermines her authority.  I recall once \r\nthat I was leading an expedition to be the first man to climb Mr. Everest \r\nand I read some disparaging comments about me on one of my partner’s \r\nwebsites.  I had that man defenestrated.  As a leader you have to teach \r\nyour underlings right away that you won’t put up with any of their shit.  \r\nI mean, \r\none day they are laughing at you, the next day Brutus and Cassius and \r\neight other senators are stabbing you respectively with huge fucking \r\nknives.  And I mean, that is no good, I don’t care who you are.\r\n\r\n<B>Thunt.net: </B>That’s very true, do you have any other advice for \r\nleaders?\r\n\r\n<B>Mr. Hunt: </B>Sometimes it may seem as though your subordinates know \r\nmore than you do.  This is never true.  Regardless of how much training \r\nthey may have.  Nothing can take the place of good leadership.  I once had \r\na man tell me how to make web pages.  He thought he knew what he was doing \r\nbecause he had worked at Intel and he taught a course in HTML design at \r\nMIT.  Well, I showed that indignant bastard a lesson.  I ripped out his \r\nfucking heart with a spoon and showed to him before he died so he could \r\nsee how black it really was.  Then I realized he had made a good point and \r\nI \r\nfixed the problem myself.  I was really glad he was able to contribute to \r\nMY project.\r\n\r\n<B>Thunt.net: </B>I have heard many people refer to the current leadership \r\nof the Hornet as a Nouveau Gerald Ford Administration.  Some vicious right-\r\nwingers \r\nhave even went as far as to refer to them as Nazis.  What’s your opinion \r\non these \r\nstatements?\r\n\r\n<B>Mr. Hunt: </B>I have no comment at this time.\r\n\r\n<B>Thunt.net: </B>I’ve heard many people label you as a naysayer, a broken \r\ndown has-been, a man who is obsessed with the past and someone who just \r\nwon’t stop bitching about the shitty condition of the State Hornet, is \r\nthis true?\r\n\r\n<B>Mr. Hunt: </B>Well, this is an issue I have wanted to address for quite \r\nsome time.  As you well know, Mr. Sommers and I have disagreed on many \r\nissues in the past.  Namely the word "feces", the letter "A" and whether \r\nor not you should look both ways when crossing the street.  But with him \r\nout of the way, I think there are some great people working at that \r\nshitbag rag paper:\r\n\r\n<UL>\r\n<LI><B>Endeen</B>: A great guy.  A true managing <B>editor in</b> the \r\n<b>chief</b> sense of the word.  Think of the Compromise of 1877, I weep \r\nfor the future. <br>\r\n<br>\r\n<LI><B>Wagar</B>: The man really knows his news.  If something happens on \r\ncampus, he’s the one who will be there.  And you know he will put his \r\nfucking ass on the line to get that integral story.  Sometimes they lock \r\nhim out of the office and try to stop him from doing work, but nothing can \r\nhold back this behemoth of modern journalism.  I’ve read a lot of stories \r\nabout Lunch Ladies, but his was the best.<br>\r\n<br>\r\n<LI><B>Duong</B>: Too much has been said, but the man is not just a hero, \r\nbut my hero.  I thank the almighty God everyday of my life when I think of \r\nthat beautiful snowflake that he placed on this Earth.<br>\r\n<br>\r\n<LI><B>Tony</B>: Few people can be referred to by just their first name, \r\nMadonna, Marilyn, Marvin the Martian, but Tony is that kind of man.  I \r\nnever really liked Features and I never really will, but it’s good to see \r\na true renaissance man in charge of the section.<br>\r\n<br>\r\n<LI><B>Andrea</B>: In 1928 she joined a religious order and took the name \r\nTeresa. The order immediately sent her to India. A few years later, she \r\nbegan teaching in Calcutta, and in 1948 the Catholic Church granted her \r\npermission to leave her convent and work among the city\'s poor people. She \r\nbecame an Indian citizen that same year. In 1950, she founded a religious \r\norder in Calcutta called the Missionaries of Charity. The order provides \r\nfood for the needy and operates hospitals, schools, orphanages, youth \r\ncenters, and shelters for lepers and the dying poor. It now has branches \r\nin 50 Indian cities and 30 other countries.<br>\r\n<br>\r\n<LI><B>Katherine</B>: Even though she has Justin White as a friend, I \r\nwon’t hold that against her. <br>\r\n<br>\r\n<LI><B>Russ</B>: Russ grew up in the rough-and-tumble environment \r\nsurrounding his father’s Lombard and Camden Street saloons. By age seven \r\nhe had become incorrigible and beyond the influence of parental control. \r\nFrustrated, the Edmondson’s sent their son to St. Mary’s Industrial \r\nSchool, an institution for orphans and delinquent boys strictly run by the \r\nCatholic order of Xaverian Brothers, who were noted for their no-nonsense \r\ndisciplinary tactics. It was there that the youngster learned the \r\nintricacies of baseball, and of life, mostly under the tutelage of \r\nBrothers Gilbert and Matthias.\r\n</UL>\r\n\r\n<B>Thunt.net: </B>What has been the reaction of the Editor in Chief of the \r\nState Hornet, a woman who some call History’s Greatest Monster?\r\n\r\n<B>Mr. Hunt: </B>She’s been really great about it.  She called me up on \r\nthe phone they other day and was so incredibly cordial I thought that she \r\nhad been trained by Emily Post, herself.  She commented on the ironic \r\nqualities of the article as well as it’s narcissistic qualities.  To her \r\nit was more of a Nietzchistic expression of post-Kierergardian myth with a \r\nsmattering of Freud and Marx rather than an outpouring of Jeffersonian \r\ndemocratism.  She was really great about the whole thing.  She even \r\noffered to take me out to dinner and seemed to be interested in me \r\nsexually.  \r\n\r\n<B>Thunt.net: </B>So the threats we have heard of Lawyers and another bad \r\nmovie like "A Civil Action" are completely false?\r\n\r\n<B>Mr. Hunt: </B>Yes, completely false.  Nothing could be further from the \r\ntruth.  I mean I have no interest in suing the Hornet.   To tell you the \r\ntruth, they have nothing that I want.  I mean I’ve always wanted to throw \r\nan Imac off a ten story building but that’s one of those things that is \r\nbound to happen to any young man in today’s day and age.  It’s an \r\ninevitability really, I don’t really concern myself with it much.\r\n\r\n<B>Thunt.net: </B>Did you ever see Nadine underage, drunk off her ass, at \r\nthe Limelight?\r\n\r\n<B>Mr. Hunt: </B>I have no recollection of that fact, Senator.\r\n\r\n<B>Thunt.net: </B>Have you ever read the book Harry Potter and the \r\nGauntlet of Fire?\r\n\r\n<B>Mr. Hunt: </B>No, I did not have sexual relations with that woman.\r\n\r\n<B>Thunt.net: </B>I’m talking about the book, with Harry Potter, with the \r\nmagic and dragons, you know?\r\n\r\n<B>Mr. Hunt: </B>No, I did not have sexual relations with that woman.  \r\nPlease stop asking me this question.\r\n\r\n<B>Thunt.net: </B>What woman? Have you gone insane, I am not asking a \r\nquestion about a woman, but merely a whimsical children’s book.\r\n\r\n<B>Mr. Hunt: </B>No, I did not have sexual relations with that woman.  \r\nThis interview is over.  I can’t stand you.  You disgust me.  You dirty \r\nmuck-raking, yellow-journalist.  You’re an unfit mother.  They should give \r\nout more free condoms to stop people like you from procreating in drunken \r\nsorority sponsored orgies.  Step into my office, because you’re fucking \r\nfired you backstabbing whore!  You wouldn’t know a competent person if \r\nthey fell on you like that fucking house in that movie.  You couldn’t find \r\nyour ass with two hands and a map.  You smell like an elephant’s behind \r\nand your mother reeks of elderberries.  You had me at Hello.  \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<I>no one can touch you in your bathing suit area.</I>\r\n\r\nThis article is dedicated to the memory of Matt Brown.  How come when one \r\nman kills another man in the heat of battle it’s called heroism, but if he \r\nkills him for eating the last otter pop, it’s called murder? ', '   really long. About the hornet. They\'re funny.', 20000906004516, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (37, 'Ask Thunt', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '\r\nWell, with my newfound fame and fortune I’ve discovered that people have \r\nbegun to treat me as some sort of Christ-figure who they expect to solve \r\nall of their problems for them.  I hate to deprive anyone of my glorious \r\nadvice, so without any further ado I give you “Ask Thunt” or as I like to \r\ncall it, “Dear Abby with Attitude”.\r\n\r\nDear Thunt,\r\n\r\n   Someone is making fun of me at work.  It really hurts my feelings \r\nbecause ever since I was a little girl Daddy always bought me everything \r\nthat I wanted.  Even though I’m the boss at my work I feel like my \r\nauthority is being threatened by this Shakespearian miscreant.  I don’t \r\nknow who to trust anymore.  It seems as if he has struck at the very core \r\nof my inner circle and they are feeding him information to better craft \r\nhis masterful jokes.  Just the other day I was contemplating breast \r\nenhancement surgery with my closest friends and the very next day everyone \r\nin the break room was gawking at a poster on the wall.  It was a picture \r\nof me, but someone had removed my body and replaced it with the body of a \r\nnude female model.  I believe it was Pamela Anderson Lee post-Baywatch and \r\nbefore she had her reduction surgery.  I turned bright red and quickly \r\nripped the poster off of the wall and ran to my office with tears in my \r\neyes.  Of course later I couldn’t stop staring at the beautiful breasts in \r\nthe picture and I had a really good time if you know what I mean.  Even \r\nso, I fear that I’m not respected by my co-workers.   We had a routine \r\nstaff meeting yesterday and everyone was laughing at me.  I felt like my \r\nfavorite actor Ernest in the movie Ernest Scared Stupid.  Usually I’m \r\nhappy when I think about my favorite actor, a man who was robbed of \r\nAcademy gold so many times by that dirt bag Robert De Niro.  Anyway, I’m a \r\ncompletely laughing-stock.  I can’t even sleep around without being caught \r\nanymore.  I need help.  So far I’ve been trying to forget my troubles by \r\nborrowing money from the petty cash at work to buy dime bags of cocaine, \r\nbut I know that drug addiction is not the answer.  I just want to get back \r\nto the way things were in college.  When I was the “little princess” of \r\nthe sorority and I spent every evening drinking cheap alcohol until I \r\npassed out and was raped by the football team.  Those were the days.  How \r\ncan I get back to that?\r\n\r\n	Sincerely, \r\n            Crying in Colorado\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n   Well, <I>Crying</I>.  I think that it’s time you showed that asshole \r\nwho’s boss.  I mean, from what you tell me you are the boss at your work \r\nand you shouldn’t have to take any shit at all.  I mean not from anybody.  \r\nWhy do they call Superman Superman?  It’s not just because he’s banging \r\nLois Lane.  It’s because he doesn’t take any shit.  When Lex Luthor tried \r\nto kill him with Kryptonite that one time, he didn’t let that bastard get \r\naway with it.  He locked him in an easily escapable jail for good.  And \r\nthat is what I suggest with this troublemaker at your work.  I suggest you \r\nwrite him a letter.  A strong, harsh, mean-spirited letter and let him \r\nknow what your true feelings are.  Tell that bastard off.  Maybe you are a \r\nbad boss.  Maybe you do treat your underlings like scum sucking bottom \r\nfeeders.  Maybe you did start the Chicago Fire.  Perhaps it was your fault \r\nthat communism conquered China and Mao Tse-tsung killed off oh so many of \r\nhis people.  But these are still not reasons for you to take anyone’s \r\nshit.  Tell that bastard off, because if you allow your fellow employees \r\nto laugh at you, you are no longer the boss, you are just a little bitch.  \r\n\r\nDear Thunt, \r\n\r\n   I don’t know how to do my job.  I’m supposed to be running this big \r\nwebsite for this newspaper and I just don’t know how.  I try my best but \r\nnothing seems to work right.  And yesterday, my boss told me that I am \r\nincompetent screw-head and then she cussed me out in front of the rest of \r\nthe newspaper staff.  Now I’m completely shunned by all my fellow co-\r\nworkers because they think I’m a idiot.   What should I do?\r\n\r\n	From,\r\n           Loser in Louisville\r\n \r\n   Well, I don’t know how to help incompetent people.  If you don’t know \r\nhow to do your job perhaps you should perform some tests on your new zero \r\ngravity machine without a net.  Perhaps you could get a job testing \r\nejector seats on helicopters.  I know that the Army is always looking for \r\na few good corpses, so that’s right up your alley.  If your boss told you \r\nthat you were an incompetent screw-up, she’s probably right.  You should \r\njust take it and shut the fuck up like the little cocksucker you are.\r\n\r\n\r\nDear Thunt,\r\n\r\n   I need help.  I’m not a computer wiz.  To tell you the truth I don’t \r\nknow the difference between my toaster and my vibrator, I mean Microsoft \r\nand Macintosh.  But my friend gave me a job and it involves computer \r\nskills.  I try my best to convince my co-workers that I know what I’m \r\ndoing, but I’m a sorority girl.  The only thing I’ve learned in college is \r\nthat Victoria’s Secret has the best push-up bras and drinking vodka \r\ndirectly from the bottle is the best way to spend a Wednesday night.  \r\nPlease help me!\r\n\r\n	Love,\r\n           Brunette in Boston\r\n\r\n   Well, I’ve had to do a lot of soul searching to solve your problem \r\n<I>Brunette in Boston</I>.  And what I’ve come up while peering deep into \r\nmy crystal ball is that you should wear less clothing at work.  Try to \r\nshow these computer dorks that you work with that you are more than just a \r\npretty face.  Show them that you’ve got tits and an ass too.  There’s only \r\none thing that people respect in the computer industry and that is not \r\nintelligence.  It’s the willingness to suck up to anyone that can get you \r\na better job.  And you know what I mean when I say suck up.  So hop to it!\r\n\r\nThis has been “Ask Thunt”.  If you have any problems with your love life, \r\nyour job or enormous setbacks on your snowbound campaign to conquer \r\nRussia, please email Thunt at <a \r\nhref="mailto:thunt@thunt.net">thunt@thunt.net</a>.\r\n\r\nBecause it’s not like he cares but at least you’ll get some of the \r\nattention that you so desperately need, you silly little bitch.\r\n  \r\n\r\n\r\n', '3 losers state their complaints and Thunt gives them advice, Thunt-style.\r\n', 20000907215300, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (45, 'Thunt launches ThuntPhotos.com', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Ever wanted to see a collection of black and white photos shot, developed \r\nand printed by Thomas Hunt?  Well now you get your chance! Just click on \r\nover to <a href="http://www.thuntphotos.com">ThuntPhotos.com</a> and see \r\nall of Thomas Hunt\'s breathtaking B&W work.\r\n\r\nWhat are the critics saying about ThuntPhotos.com:\r\n\r\n"A stunning new foray into the realm of photography.  Thunt certainly has \r\nan eye."  - Kodak\r\n\r\n"It makes my work seem like nature photography" - Ansel Adams\r\n\r\n"A new voyage into the dark world of black and white.  It seems a bit \r\nrocky at first but Thunt certainly makes it work" - Roger Ebert\r\n\r\n"It tastes more like real butter" - Unknown\r\n\r\n"Ideal for backgrounds, Thunt\'s photos bring about a true feeling of \r\ndespair when viewing them" - Unknown\r\n\r\n"I think, therefore I am" - Descartes\r\n\r\n"When the going gets tough, the tough go gonzo" - Hunter S. Thompson\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'ThuntPhotos.com - Excellent B&W photography by Thomas Hunt', 20000912081339, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (46, 'Conspiracy Theory', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '</pre>\r\n<a href="http://www.thunt.net/images/comics/comic02.jpg">\r\n<img src="http://www.thunt.net/images/comics/comic02.jpg" border="0" alt="Whorenet Comics">\r\n</a>\r\n<pre class="normal">', 'You\'re not paranoid if they\'re really following you.', 20000912163009, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (47, 'arthur conan doyle rolling in his grave.', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '</pre>\r\n<a href="http://www.thunt.net/images/comics/comic03.jpg">\r\n<img src="http://www.thunt.net/images/comics/comic03.jpg" border="0" alt="Whorenet Comics">\r\n</a>\r\n<pre class="normal">', 'Whornet comics continues!', 20000913151444, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (44, 'Hornet Therapy Session', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '</pre>\r\n<a href="http://www.thunt.net/images/comics/hornet_therapy.jpg" alt="Whorenet Comics">\r\n<img src="http://www.thunt.net/images/comics/hornet_therapy.jpg" \r\nborder="0"></a>\r\n<pre class="normal">\r\n\r\nillustrated by Thomas Hunt and his trusty laser mouse\r\nwritten by Matt Brown & Thomas Hunt\r\n\r\nAnd in case you were curious:<br><ul>\r\nMain Entry:	<b>sat·ire</b>\r\nPronunciation:	<tt>\'sa-"tIr</tt>\r\nFunction:	<i>noun</i>\r\nEtymology:	Middle French or Latin; Middle French, from Latin \r\n<i>satura, satira, </i>perhaps from (<i>lanx</i>) <i>satura </i>dish of \r\nmixed ingredients, from feminine of <i>satur </i>well-fed; akin to Latin \r\n<i>satis </i>enough</a>\r\nDate:	1501\r\n<b>1</b> <b>:</b> a literary work holding up human vices and follies to \r\nridicule or scorn<br><b>2</b> <b>:</b> trenchant wit, irony, or sarcasm \r\nused to expose and discredit vice or folly\r\n\r\n<b>Hustler Magazine, Inc. v. Falwell, 485 U.S. 46, 108 S.Ct. 876, 99 \r\nL.Ed.2d. 41 (1988) </b>\r\n\r\nHustler Magazine published a parody of a liquor advertisement in which \r\nRev. Jerry Falwell described his “first time” as a drunken encounter with \r\nhis mother in an outhouse. A <b>unanimous</b> Supreme Court held that a \r\npublic figure had to show New York Times actual malice in order to recover \r\nfor intentional infliction of emotional distress as a result of a parody \r\nin a magazine. The Court held that political cartoons and satire such as \r\nthis parody “have played a prominent role in public and political debate.” \r\nAnd although the outrageous caricature in this case “is at best a distant \r\ncousin of political cartoons,” the Court could see no standard to \r\ndistinguish among types of parodies that would not harm public discourse, \r\nwhich would be poorer without such satire.</ul>', 'a comic strip.satire', 20000911170745, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (62, 'Sir Ryan Endeen, III, my hero', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'I would like to take a <b>postition</b> today.\r\n\r\nI would like to glorify and magnify the stellar accomplishments of the \r\nworld’s protector Ryan Endeen in his flabbergasting article “Fee increase \r\nmay curb parking nightmares”. This article represents the absolute \r\npinnacle of investigative reporting.  Never before have I seen such \r\npunctuation like the period he used in line 5.  You just do not see \r\ngrammar like that in modern news reporting.  Seeing periods like this \r\nbrings me back to the grand old days of Edward R. Morrow and William \r\nRandolph Hearst and I believe Mr. Endeen would agree with me \r\nwholeheartedly.  \r\n\r\nAt the end of his second paragraph when he says that “parking is expected \r\nto worsen”, I was struck by the inescapable drama of his prose.  It is \r\npractically Shakespearian in its transference of language down to the \r\nbaser elements of society yet it still propels itself upwards on the wings \r\nof a dove.  \r\n\r\nAnd towards the end of the article when he writes “250 spaces will be \r\nopened up in Lot 4, after the completion of the removal and <b>demolition \r\nof the temporary</b>.”  I was amazed at his ability to take such a harsh \r\nstance against the transitory nature of this life and to stand so high in \r\nsuch a sordid medium and cry out against the demons of this world.  Few \r\nphilosophers in our time have the gall to make such a bold statement.\r\nI would like to close with the amazing quote that Mr. Endeen managed to \r\nachieve from Mr. Jimmy Henderson (he prefers Jimmy, like most four year \r\nolds) who said and I quote: “<B>we’re basically kind of screwed</B>”.\r\n', 'there\'s something about Ryan....', 20000927170902, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (63, 'Thunt.net meets demands', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '\r\n  Why hasn\'t thunt.net been updated in a few days?  It is a very important \r\nquestion, and now I must provide you with the very important answer.\r\n\r\n  Thunt.net is primarily a one man operation.  Thunt codes, writes, \r\ndesigns, etc.  So for the past few days Thunt has been coding and if you \r\nlook at the bottom of this page you will see the results.  \r\n\r\n  New Thunt.net Features:\r\n\r\n    - Email to a friend:  Want to tell your friends about something cool   \r\nyou read on thunt.net?  Now you can!  Just click on the link at the bottom \r\nof the article, enter the required information and boom! pow! they get an \r\nemail and get to enjoy all the thunt.net goodness that you enjoy!\r\n\r\n    - Previous & Next buttons.  Ever get to the bottom of the story and \r\nwant to instantly click back to the previous article?  Well now you can! \r\nOr you can time travel to the future by clicking the next article button!  \r\nIdeal for those slow work days when you decide to re-read thunt.net from \r\nthe begining.  While you used to have to painstakingly click through the \r\narchive, now you can use the handy buttons at the bottom!\r\n\r\nThis sums up the new thunt.net features and explains the absence of \r\narticles written by thunt in the past few days.  But don\'t worry, there \r\nwill be more next week! So make sure to check back then!\r\n\r\ncomming soon: Thunt.net Mailing list: get a brief email whenever thunt.net \r\nis updated, perfect for keeping track of thunt\'s seemingly random update \r\ntimes!\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'Email to a friend, announced.\r\nPrevious & Next buttons, announced.\r\n\r\npretty fucking sweet.', 20000929154622, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (64, 'Pepe\'s Diary: Sept. 25-26', 'Unknown', 'Unknown', '\r\n<I>Editor\'s Note: I recieved this diary entry through email, supposively \r\nfrom some resistance agency.  I believe it and it\'s author to be valid.  I \r\nhad no choice but to publish it.  I hope that you will learn from this \r\nman\'s sad tail and do all you can to help him. -- Thunt</i>\r\n\r\n\r\nMy name is Pepe.  I am not supposted to be writing this.  If she found \r\nabout this, she would kill me.  As far back as I can remember I have been \r\na slave to her.  She beats me and demands that I edit articles for hours \r\non end.  She has made me learn the english language despite her lack of \r\nmastery in it.  She is pure evil.\r\n\r\nI have begun recording my thoughts in this journal.  I hope someday that \r\nit will be published in a repertable journal like the times or thunt.net.  \r\n\r\n<B>September 25, 2000</B>, 6:00 - It’s production day again.  Typically \r\nshe has a class and is no where to be found so I use the three hours to \r\nfashion a small knife out of a paper clip and some tape.  I can only hope \r\nthat it will be enough. \r\n\r\n<B>September 25, 2000</B>, 10:00 – The knife was not enough.  When she \r\nreturned I stabbed her in the leg but the unfeeling bitch didn’t even \r\nbleed.  She just beat me for hours with her binder.  Then she forced me to \r\nedit the entire paper, checking twice for spelling and three times for \r\ngrammer.  \r\n\r\n<B>September 26, 2000</B>, 1:00 – I am still working on the paper.  Just \r\nten minutes ago she demanded I completely redo the front page.  I wish I \r\nwas not born a slave.  Please, please, help me!\r\n', 'cries for help from the third world.', 20001001002158, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (65, 'THUNT ATTACKED!', 'Henry Hackett', '', '\r\nScholar, humanitarian and award-winning satirist Thunt was brutally beaten\r\ntoday, Monday October 2nd, in the University Union.  According to \r\neyewitness reports Thunt was quietly reading, when he was attacked by \r\nunidentified person/persons.  Thunt was then airlifted to an unidentified \r\nhospital (withheld by police for Thunt\'s safety)  Sources in the police \r\ndepartment have informed us that he is in serious condition, and he isn’t \r\nexpected to survive through the night.  Every effort is being taken to \r\ngive Thunt the best medical treatment, experts from throughout the world \r\nare being flown in to treat Thunt.\r\n\r\nThe police department finds this act contemptible and has assigned three\r\ndetectives to the case.  In a press conference held earlier today Lead\r\nDetective William Somerset declared that Law enforcement agencies all over\r\nCalifornia have been mobilized and they feel the apprehension of Thunt\'s\r\nattacker is now a top priority.  Somerset believes the primary motive may \r\nbe Thunt\'s willingness to turn state’s evidence in an academic corruption \r\ncase, involving a moderately respected newspaper, and some University \r\nprofessors.\r\n\r\nSeveral of the eyewitnesses were former Thunt collegues at the State Hornet\r\nnewspaper, which Thunt lovingly called “a shitbag rag”.  Recently knighted\r\nand shitfaced Sir Ryan Endeen, III declared that Thunt was a little bitch,\r\nhe was glad he was dead, and it was about time she killed him.  When Sir\r\nEndeen found out thunt was clinging to life, he changed his postition and\r\nnow he feels that the world has lost a great individual, and he is now\r\nhoping Thunt pulls through.  Sir Endeen then proceded to vomit profusely\r\ninto the library quad fountain, then started singing a creepy rendition of\r\n“It\'s Raining Men’.\r\n\r\nMatt Wagar and Antonio Harvey were also eyewitnesses to the event.  Fearful\r\nfor their lives, Wagar and Harvey went into hiding.  Both were eventually\r\nfound in Wagar’s VW eating packets of mustard.  They deny being witnesses \r\nto those events, and refused to help Detective Somersets special unit.\r\n\r\nA heavily medicated David Sommers, formet Editor in Chief of the State\r\nHornet, remembers Thunt as a “bitchin’ dude” and was really bummed when he\r\nlearned of Thunt\'s condition.\r\n\r\nPolice are asking for anyone with knowledge of these events to come \r\nforward, and Thunt\'s family feels that Thunt would have wanted cold, \r\nbrutal revenge against his attacker and has posted a $50,000 reward, dead \r\nor alive.\r\n\r\nThunt.net will keep you updated on all events as they happen.', 'Thunt in severe medical condition.\r\nHis attacker goes unpunished!', 20001002082055, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (66, 'Movie Review: X-Men', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '  X-men the movie is great.\r\n \r\nI\'m going to go by characters, cause I can write this \r\nreview howerver I want to and I can use any words I \r\ngod damn well please to.  Such as: shit, piss, cunt, \r\nfuck, cocksucker, motherfucker, tits, pussy, bitch, \r\nasswipe, poop, fart, and donkey-raping-shit-eater. \r\nanyway, the review...\r\n\r\nMystique:\r\n  The best part of the movie is they don\'t let the \r\nsupermodel act.  Not at all... Rebecca Romain-Stamos \r\n(really hot blonde, married to Jesse from Full House, \r\nthere\'s no accounting for taste, her\'s, not his...), \r\nanyway, her character in the movie does not talk at \r\nall.  She might say 1 to 2 words throughout the whole \r\nthing.  Sometimes she does some stunts, mainly \r\nwirework, a few times she poses seductively or \r\ndangerously, also she has tits, oh yes, tits, that\'s \r\nhow I judge all actors.\r\n\r\nRouge:\r\n  Anna Paquin.  The actress I\'ve never seen before.  I \r\ndidn\'t see her award-winning performance in The Piano \r\nand I didn\'t see her smelly kids movie Fly away home, \r\nor never fly home, or some whiney kid flies with birds \r\nmovie.  But I\'ve seen the trailers and the Oscars TV \r\nShow so I know who she is.  Regardless, she did a good \r\njob.  Rouge has a dynamic history and she tells it \r\nwell.  Her performance is great and her storyline is \r\ntouching, and this is a fucking action movie with \r\nACTION! WOO! Unlike MI-2 this movie also has a \r\nstoryline.  \r\n\r\n<I>Author\'s Note: Contrary to the philosophy of MI-2, a \r\nstory is more than just a bad guy threatning the world \r\nand other people constantly repeating that it is bad.</I>\r\n\r\n\r\nWolverine: \r\n  Wolverine kicks ass.  A lot of people are going to \r\ncome out and say Hugh Jackman, the new-aussie-on-the-\r\nblock (watch out Russell Crowe) kicks ass, but they \r\nwill be wrong.  The real answer is: Wolverine Kicks \r\nAss, Hugh did a good job, but I\'ll bet Joey from Full \r\nHouse could have played this role and still kicked \r\nass.  Wolverine had the lines, the action, and the \r\nattitude.  He spiked people, used his claws to flaunt \r\nhow fucking cool he is, and generally KICKED FUCKING \r\nASS.  It was rad.  Espicially the funny claw trick, \r\nwhich I won\'t reveal, unlike other bad critics who \r\nruined the fun for me.  But I still enjoyed it, HA!\r\n\r\nCyclops:\r\n  Only had about five lines in the picture.  But the \r\nbest one is:\r\n\r\nCyclops: (to Wolverine)  How do we know you are the \r\nreal you?\r\n\r\nWolverine: Because you\'re a dick.\r\n\r\nCyclops: Good enough.\r\n\r\nThey had a little rivalry because Wolverine was a \r\nlittle interested in:\r\n\r\nJean Grey:\r\n  Unlike Cyclops, Jean had about 10 lines in the film.  \r\nBut her most important contribiution was being really \r\nhot.  Really really hot.  I mean wow.  That hot.  \r\nNormally I think Rebecca Full House Stamos is hot, but \r\nin this film Jean Grey wins the hot chick contest.  \r\nStunning.  Red hair, wow.  Smart: "Dr." Jean Grey, \r\noooh.  They even had one pan up shot that was a \r\nlittle "over the top" but still clearly expressed the \r\ngeneral sentiment: "Wow this girl is hot".\r\n\r\nStorm:\r\n  Five lines in the picture.  I think I\'m supposed to \r\nremember who she is.  I think she\'s and actor or a \r\nsinger or something.  Regardless, she had five lines \r\nand didn\'t fuck it up.  Add in a few glowing eyeball \r\neffects and that\'s pretty much Storm.  Although no one \r\ncalled her Weather Bitch or Weather Witch, and I think \r\nthat could have added to the picture.\r\n\r\nToad:\r\n  He did a lot for a mutant who\'s powers consist of a \r\nTounge and jumping around a lot.\r\n\r\nSabertooth:\r\n  Boring. Growling alot.\r\n\r\nMagneto:\r\n  I think it was the smoking man from X-files.  He was \r\ngood.  His evil plot was a little silly.  Maybe he was \r\nGrand Moff Tarkin.  I dunno.\r\n\r\nCharles Xavior\r\n  Picard kicked fucking ass.  To sum it up:\r\n    "The role he and his voice were made for."\r\n\r\ndid I mention that jean grey was hot?\r\n\r\nThe movie:\r\n  short. sweet. but obviously short.  Could have used \r\nthe 35 minutes they cut out, but the loss of added \r\ncharacter development will probably help the sales.  I \r\njust hope they have a rad disc with Dynamic Branching \r\nso I can watch a longer version of this cool movie.  I \r\nalso wish they had given Singer more money so he could \r\nhave patched up the effects a little and added more.  \r\nThe effects were good, but they were quick, alot of \r\npoints it felt like they were hiding stuff, which I\'m \r\nsure they were, since as I recall the film was only \r\nlike 50 mil which is cheap compaired to what they\'re \r\ngoing to make this weekend.  Our theater was sold out \r\nand the next show too.  Also I noticed none of the \r\ncharacters flew.  In the comics, Rouge, Jean Grey, \r\nStorm, Magneto all flew often.  Maybe a few of them \r\nwere weaker, younger characters, so I\'ll give them \r\nthat.  But Storm and Magneto should be able to fly.  \r\nAnd I\'ll bet they would have if they had more dough.\r\n\r\nLighting:  \r\n  Bland.  Average.  Some shadows, nothing dramatic.\r\n\r\nDirecting, Bryan Singer:\r\n  Good job, nothing truly auteur, but good close-ups, \r\nvery fast, uses the left and right extremes of the \r\nframe often...  \r\n\r\nI think that\'s it.  So go see it.  And if you finished \r\nthe review, thanks.  I know I rambled, but it happens \r\nsometimes, espically when you\'re mind is focused on \r\nthat beautiful Jean Grey.\r\n\r\npoof!\r\n\r\n \r\n', 'X-Men a good movie.\r\nThunt\'s review of X-Men, a good review.', 20001003093736, 'flashbacks', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (67, 'THESE PIPES ARE CLEAN!!!', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '\r\nWell, I just edited my bookmarks.  A good use of 30-40 \r\nminutes.  I feel much more like an organized \r\nproductive human being now that I know that \r\nStileproject.com is safely stored \r\nin "Entertainment", and Sometimes Barney Starts \r\nPlaying Peekaboo on His Own is tied up properly \r\nin "Funny Microsoft Errors"...  To quote Casino, \r\ncleaning out one\'s bookmarks is like a morality car \r\nwash, it washes away all your sins and leaves you \r\nclean again...  \r\n\r\nOther News: Nate found an error in the Thunt.net \r\narchive, so he gets major props.  Not only did he find \r\nthe error, he diagnosed it and suggested I fix it, \r\nwhich of course I wavered on but finally went ahead \r\nand made the changes.  Yeah Nate!!\r\n\r\nI saw the movie Groove a few days ago, it was really \r\ngood, you should all go see it and support independant \r\ncinema.  And if you don\'t get out to see it, try to \r\npick up the soundtrack, \r\nDoug has it and I\'ve been enjoying it \r\nfor several days until he wanted it back.  I\'ll have \r\nto make a copy. :> \r\n\r\nVegetables are good for you.\r\nNever believe what you read.\r\nBecause you are what you eat.\r\n\r\nthis parrot died of natural causes.\r\nBACK INTO THE HOLE!\r\n - the simpsons, of course\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n', 'Thunt edits his bookmarks. woo!', 20001003093850, 'flashbacks', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (68, 'Woody Allen is so good', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '\r\nI\'m watching Sweet and Lowdown right now.  Woody Allen \r\nis so good.  Somehow he just takes these random twists \r\nin his stories and poof amazing story.  His shots and \r\ndialogue and ideas are usually rather basic but then \r\nhe twists them into amazing stories.  Like Small Time \r\nCrooks, another amazing Allen film.  Basic bank \r\nrobbery plot, going along fine, typical allen \r\ncharacter and dialogue, then BLAMMO he takes a turn in \r\nthe plot that everyone else would have just thrown out \r\nas a whimiscal bad idea. \r\n\r\nNow he\'s got a character in Sweet and Lowdown shooting \r\nrats at the dump.  Yup.  Just standing there with \r\na .45 with a full clip shooting at rats.\r\n\r\nI\'d like to write like Woody Allen.  I think the most \r\namazing part about Allen is the number of films, \r\nbooks, plays, etc that he has written.  I think that \r\nastonishes me more than all the oscar nominations and \r\nhis big victory in \'72 with Annie Hall and the big \r\nClose Encounters/Star Wars split.  \r\n\r\nAs far as the Soon Yi thing, who gives a flying fuck.  \r\nThe man is an amazing filmmaker, writer.  Now America \r\nmocks him, but although I fear the day when he\'s gone, \r\nI know that the next day the papers will read "Amazing \r\nGenius, un-parralled in our times merges with the \r\ninfinate."  \r\n\r\n', 'read the title.  Woody Allen kicks fucking ass.', 20001003093945, 'flashbacks', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (71, 'Save Thunt Campaign begins', 'Mark Anthony, Thunt\'s Personal Secretary', 'thunt@thunt.net', '\r\n  We here at thunt.net would like to thank you for all the kind letters, \r\nprayers and calls that we have been recieving.  We too hope and pray for a \r\nquick recovery for Thunt. \r\n\r\nWe would espically like to thank Ryan Anne Polli for her kind words via \r\nemail:<i>\r\n  "gee. i hope he pulls through. what the hell else am i\r\n  going to read on the internet? and where else will i\r\n  find the stellar quality of photo illustration realism\r\n  in a comic setting? the horror..."</i>\r\n\r\nAlso we would like to thank our friends in Denmark, Sacramento, and Boston \r\nfor helping to get the word out by using the means we always prescribe \r\nhere at thunt.net and those are of course: any means neccessary.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://thunt.net/images/save_thunt/save_thunt_brick.jpg" \r\nborder="0" alt="Thunt.net supporters in Denmark rally"><br>\r\nThunt.net supporters in Denmark launch the Danish Campaign<br>\r\n<br>\r\n<img src="http://thunt.net/images/save_thunt/save_thunt_window.jpg"\r\nborder="0" alt="The local Sacramento chapter does their part"><br>\r\nThe local Sacramento chapter does their part<br>\r\n<br>\r\n<img src="http://thunt.net/images/save_thunt/save_thunt_fenway.jpg"\r\nborder="0" alt="Even the Boston chapter helps out"><br>\r\nEven the Boston chapter helps out\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '', 20001003111037, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (72, 'Police sketch released', 'Mark Anthony', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'The Police have released a sketch of the person who they believe assaulted \r\nThunt.  This person is to be considered armed and stupid.  If you see this \r\nperson on the street do not attempt to apprehend them, call the police \r\nimmediately.  \r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n<div align="center" class="normal">\r\n<a href="http://www.thunt.net/images/comics/initial_sketch.jpg">\r\n<img src="http://www.thunt.net/images/comics/initial_sketch.jpg" \r\nalt="sketch" border="0"></a><br>\r\nOfficial Police Sketch\r\n</div><pre>', 'Sketch released. Find this masked man!', 20001004174149, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (73, 'Ultimate Reclusivity', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Thunt in Portland:\r\n\r\n  Up here in the big oregonian city, we do things a \r\nlittle different than you little city folx down there \r\nin Califonyia....  Instead of driving to our local \r\nSafeway, we use Home Grocer.  All we had to do is go \r\nonline and order the food we wanted then a nice man \r\nbrought it to us the next day.  Right to our door, \r\nwearing santiary booties on his shoes too.  What a \r\nguy.  Did I mention that we did our ordering off of \r\nPhil\'s 27" TV with a screeming K6-2/550 hooked up to \r\nit, while using a radio mouse (with wheel of course) \r\nand a radio ergonomic keyboard (complete with play \r\nbutton reconfigured to start winamp playing streaming \r\ntechno off of the speedy dsl line onto the stylisly \r\nsmall JVC stereo unit including the oversize OPTIMUS \r\n(not prime, my transformer fans) subwoofer, but I \r\ndigress).  So we ordered our food and it came, and it \r\nwas good. \r\n  Also the next day I felt like renting a video game \r\n(NHL 2K for Sega Dreamcast, which I keep calling \r\nDreamStation because I am such a lame ex-gamer.  \r\nPretty soon I\'ll be like my Dad who calls every video \r\ngame system Nintendo regardless of how superior to \r\nNintendo it is or how long it\'s been since Nintendo \r\nwas hip new and trendy.)  So I popped out to Kozmo.com a \r\ngroup of trendy ipo type bicycle messengers who have \r\ngone pro.  Kozmo offered me a deal I could not \r\nrefuse.  NHL 2K for 3 days and they would bring it to \r\nme in less than an hour for 5 bucks.  Very very \r\nreasonable I said while sitting in a nice leather \r\nchair surfing the net.  Before I knew it I had rented \r\nthe game.  Then they offered me 4 dollars off my \r\nnext "visit".  I figured hmmmm, I could go for a movie \r\ntoo, so I rented Scream 3, final cost: 50 cents.  Also \r\nto be delivered in an hour.  BOOM.  20 mins later, \r\nKozmo arrives with my game and DVD.  Sharp. Very sharp.\r\n  Also, minutes later Simpsons came on TV.  It was a \r\ncavalcade of pleasure.\r\n\r\n  A few days ago I finally saw Shaft (2000) in the \r\ntheater.  It was good, not a blackstaplotation film, \r\nbut a good action movie.  Highlights: "Who delivers \r\nten times out of ten" and of course "It\'s my duty to \r\nplease that booty". hehehe.\r\n\r\nportland out.\r\n\r\n', 'Thunt in Portland.... having a good time.', 20001004174547, 'flashbacks', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (74, 'Easiest 4th of July ever', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '  I have just participated in the easiest 4th of july \r\never.  We were sitting in Phil\'s Apartment playing \r\nstarcraft (me on phil\'s fancy laptop...) and we heard \r\nnoise.  What could it be?  Fireworks.  We rushed to \r\nthe roof and were able to view the fireworks and the \r\nriver, and the barge that was firing them off all from \r\nright there.  Amazing.  NO hassel.  NO sitting around \r\nfor hours.  NO grass. NO carrying lawn chairs and ice \r\nchests.  \r\n\r\n  The display was excellent.  It was loud, fairly long \r\nwith an excellent finale.  Many bright lights and \r\ncolors used.  Halfway through I found myself \r\ninterested in photographing it.  But I recalled that \r\nmy photo training has been in Black and white and that \r\nwould probably not capture the luminous colors too \r\nwell.  Also I had the thought that with an awesome \r\ndisplay like this I could probably have conquered many \r\nsmall tribal countries.  It was that strident and \r\nflashy.\r\n\r\n   When the fireworks ended we walked down the stairs \r\nand back to Phil\'s spacious condo.  On the way down we \r\nnoticed the crowds of people gathered around the \r\noutside of the building starting to trek to their cars \r\nand homes.  No doubt looking forward to a lengthy \r\ndrive home with traffic and claustrophobia in their \r\ncars.\r\n\r\nnow back to starcraft.... hehehe  \r\nportland out.\r\n\r\n', 'Thunt in Portland.... celebrating the 4th of July!', 20001004174634, 'flashbacks', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (75, 'Thunt arrives in Portland', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Attention Thunt.net readers.  Thunt is in Portland. \r\nYes. That is right.  He is in portland.\r\n\r\nLet the celebration begin.  Imagine a month of sin and \r\ndebauchery.  Phil\'s life will never be the same.  He \r\nwill no doubt be removed from his home, kicked out of \r\nthe homeowners association and end up pennyless on the \r\nstreet.\r\n\r\nThe city of Portland has fallen.  Today we saw the \r\nwebservers for Portland\'s CGIS (corporate geograpical \r\ninformation services), if your doing a dictionary \r\nlookup I suggest looking under "maps"...  They are \r\npretty Dell rack mounts. \r\n\r\nRight now I\'m using a wireless keyboard and mouse.  In \r\nphil\'s plush bachelor pad that should be scoring him \r\nmany more chicks than it seems to be.  \r\n\r\nMore to come.\r\n\r\n12:10 pm, 7/03\r\n\r\n \r\n', 'Thunt arrived in Portland. you read the title didn\'t you?', 20001004174746, 'flashbacks', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (76, 'Second Attempt on Thunt’s Life Made!', 'Henry Hackett & Mark Anthony', 'thunt@thunt.net', '        Recovering pasquinade (it means satirist, you plebeians!) Thunt \r\ntook a turn for the worse today when he was viciously attacked in his \r\nhospital room today.  The assailants evidently used a blowtorch and a pair \r\nof pliers on Thunt, but Thunt remains alive, and although he began to \r\nrecover from the last attack, Doctors now feel that Thunt’s chances of \r\nsurvival are extremely thin.\r\n	An ex-associate of Thunt, Andy! remembered him as a strong \r\nindividual, and holds out hope for his recovery.  “I doubt she has the \r\nintelligence or the resources to kill Thunt, and besides the bastard owes \r\nme ten bucks”.\r\n        Sir Ryan Endeen III had these words to day about the subject “I \r\nlike him! He\'s smart, he\'s sensitive, charming, and attractive – \r\neverything that one would want in a mate … Care to join me in a belt of \r\nscotch?”\r\n	According to Ian Competent, Thunt’s lone bodyguard, someone came \r\nto the room dressed as a pizza delivery boy, complete with piping hot \r\npizza, and used the pizza to incapacitate the guard.  “Well, I was eating \r\nmy pizza, which I had all to myself, unlike at home where my dirty wife \r\neats half the pizza.  That fucking bitch, and I heard a loud noise, and I \r\nsaid shit, I am supposed to be doing something other than eating pizza, I \r\nhad a soda too, it wasn’t a very big soda, it was a small soda, and I put \r\ndown the pizza, and I went into the room, and this guy was going to work \r\non Mr. Thunt, and I told him to stop, and he said OK, and that was that, \r\nmy pizza did get a little cold.”\r\n	Dr. Don Gerth, or DG1 as he likes his homies to call him, showed \r\nconcern for the loss of one of the university’s treasures.  When asked \r\nabout the safety in the union, where Thunt was attacked, DG1 \r\nstated, “There\'s no mystery about Thunt. Why, he simply was assaulted. \r\nNow, let\'s have no more curiosity about this bizarre cover-up, Call this \r\nan unfair generalization if you must – but all you journalism people \r\nwouldn’t know a newsworthy story if it bit you on the ass. I saw a very \r\nnewsworthy story last week when I extended the deadline for registration \r\nallowing 50,000 more students to add which saved the university from \r\nhaving the dual horrors of open seats in the classrooms, and not enough \r\npeople experiencing the sublime pleasure of getting gas at Gordito \r\nBurrito.”\r\n	Whornet Director Matt Wagar, a.k.a. Mr. Erection, preferred to \r\nlook at the positive things in life, “We could worry about Thunt, but \r\nthat’s bullshit, the sun is out, birds are singing, bees are trying to \r\nhave sex with them -- as is my understanding. Not many people know about \r\nrich history of our &lt;expletive deleted&gt;, Founded by prostitutes in \r\n1949; the first thirty-two years were concerned with how to give a flying \r\nfuck?  What the best positions were to give a flying fuck, and whether or \r\nnot giving a flying fuck was necessarily a good thing?  In the late \r\nseventies, it shifted gears and became more of a renaissance of \r\npornography, featuring positions from the wet dreams of the authors of the \r\nKama Sutra.”\r\n	We will be holding a candlelight vigil, and Pope John-Paul II, has \r\nscheduled a special mass to pray for Thunt’s quick recovery.\r\n', 'Sir Ryan Endeen III drinks scotch\r\n', 20001005233008, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (77, 'Microsoft Presents: Linux Myths', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '', 'A bunch of lies from the people who brought you the Blue Screen of Death and many other fine products.', 20001007123934, 'net_interest', 'www.microsoft.com/ntserver/nts/news/msnw/LinuxMyths.asp');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (78, 'Thunt.net Presents: Submit a Story', 'Mark Anthony', 'thunt@thunt.net', '  Do you have something to say?  \r\n\r\n  Ever wanted to express your opinions on a website?\r\n\r\n  Now, here at Thunt.net you can.  Just click on the "Submit a story!" \r\nlink at the top of this page, and you too can be among the many talented \r\nauthors who have been published on Thunt.net.  Our crack staff of editors \r\nwill read through your story, make sure it\'s OK for publishing, and then \r\npush the go button and your story will be large and in charge on Thunt.net.\r\n\r\n  Story guidelines:  Stories should be about whatever you want.  Funny is \r\ngood, but we don\'t mind serious or sad either.  Random is good.  Poetry is \r\njust fine.  Want to rant for a while, go for it.  Like to use profanity?  \r\nThunt.net ain\'t the kind of place that would tell you to fuck off. Got a \r\ncause to push?  Push it.  Think George W. Bush is stupid, say it.  If \r\nyou\'re mad as hell and are not going to take any more of their shit, go \r\nahead, write the story, get on Thunt.net, tell your friends.  Got no \r\nfriends?  Writing stories on Thunt.net might help you find some. (or at \r\nleast it will pass the time)\r\n\r\n  You have the power.  Write something.  Submit it.  Be a part of \r\nThunt.net.\r\n\r\nThunt Update: Thunt has currently gone through some major surgery but the \r\ndoctors have upgraded his condition from all the right moves to risky \r\nbusiness.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '  Do you have something to say?  \r\n\r\n  Ever wanted to express your opinions on a website?\r\n\r\n  Now, here at Thunt.net you can.', 20001007124816, 'normal', '');
