INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (84, 'Doug "Nike" Coker', 'Mark Anthony & Shroom', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'We\'ve just learned that previous nike banner spokesman Douglas R. Coker \r\nhas quit his high paying job as a shaved head advertisement at Nike and \r\ndedicated his head-space to humanitarian endeavors.  We have a picture of \r\nhis new "do" below.\r\n\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n<center>\r\n<img src="http://www.thunt.net/images/save_thunt/savethunt_doug.jpg" \r\nalt="Save Thunt!"><br>\r\n<font class="normal">Doug "Nike" Coker<br>\r\n<br>\r\n<br>\r\nphoto by <a href="mailto:shroom@thunt.net">shroom</a>\r\n</font>\r\n</center>\r\n<pre class="normal">', 'Doug shaves his head. Right on.', 20001010223600, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (85, 'Movement: a poem', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'charged pulsars drift through space\r\n\r\n  personal items are sucked into boxes like dust    \r\n  into a black hole\r\n\r\nanother voyage across the universe\r\n\r\n  I have a headache.\r\n\r\n<i>editors note: This poem was recently published in a collection by <a \r\nhref="http://www.poetry.com">poetry.com</a>.</i>\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'a  p o e m', 20001011220205, 'flashbacks', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (86, 'chaos #1', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Greetings.\r\n\r\n I have returned from Battlebots. It was good.  I \r\ndon\'t feel like describing it now so I won\'t. Briefly: \r\nhard metal seats (oww), cool robot fighting (good), tv \r\ncoverage by comedy central (bad, slowed action \r\ngreatly), robots smashed and cut up by saw blades and \r\nkinetic energy (good).\r\n\r\n1:56 am - winamp AVS plugin pretty. downloading \r\nanother stupid new version of realplayer. all the old \r\nones expire. fucking stupid company. \r\n\r\nI\'ll pick you up in my car and we\'ll paint this town.\r\n\r\nsend recieve internet.\r\n\r\nbusiness reply mail.\r\n\r\nice\r\n\r\ncleanlyness is next to godlyness.\r\n\r\n   -=Futility=-\r\n1. Every task worth doing\r\n2. Seems not worth doing\r\n3. Every life worth living \r\n4. seems worth less.\r\n\r\nmaybe your friends are simply those who have not \r\nbetrayed you YET. are animals our only true friends?\r\nand we eat them. dining on one\'s friends the ulitmate betrayl?\r\n\r\nor is the ultimate betrayl something more real?\r\ndoing what one has said one would not do?\r\n\r\nto be without faith, without religion, without mercy.\r\nby these means one can aquire power but not glory.\r\n-Machivelli\r\n\r\nif believing in god requires daily worship;\r\nis my god television or the computer?\r\n\r\nsex drugs and rock and roll.\r\n\r\nthe natural human condition is one of misery.\r\nwhat makes it livable is that it lasts so long.\r\n\r\nyour opinion matters.\r\n\r\nantidisestablishmentarianism.\r\n\r\n', 'chaos is chaos.', 20001011220600, 'flashbacks', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (87, 'Thunt to attend Battlebots', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '  Friday, (I don\'t know the date) - Thomas Hunt \r\nannounced this morning that he would be attending the \r\nBattlebots Event (remote controlled robots who fight) \r\nin San Fransisco.  We were fortunate enough to obtain \r\nan interview with the iconclast before he departs on \r\nhis epic journey.  \r\n\r\nThunt.net: So Thomas, who will be going with you on \r\nthis momentous voyage?\r\n\r\nThomas: Well, I believe Rex, Dodi, Nate and some other \r\nguy who I think is named Jason will be joining me on \r\nthis fantastic voyage into the great beyond.\r\n\r\nThunt.net: Will there be continuing coverage on \r\nThunt.net of this event?\r\n\r\nThomas: Yes, of course, espically with the new PHP \r\ndriven Thunt.net it is even easier to update the page, \r\nso expect a flurry of updates describing the fantastic \r\nbattlebots action as well as the movements and actions \r\nof our intrepid crew.\r\n\r\nThunt.net: Are you schitzophrenic?\r\n\r\nThomas: No, I just think the "fake press \r\nrelease/interview" style is something that I can \r\nreally pull off with ease.\r\n\r\nThunt.net: Well, I think we\'ll have to let that brave \r\nThomas Hunt get going...  Thank you for spending some \r\ntime with us, Mr. Hunt.\r\n\r\nThomas: It was my pleasure, any time.\r\n\r\nThunt.net: Next up on Thunt.net, Violence and the \r\nMedia: 10 reasons why you should beat the hell out of \r\nyour local news anchors.\r\n\r\nAnd now a word from our sponser:\r\n  <i>The greeks based their gods on themselves, and   \r\n  then they called themselves god-like.</i>\r\n\r\n', 'if you talk to yourself you are crazy.\r\nif you write an interview about you talking to yourself are you sane?', 20001011220744, 'flashbacks', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (88, 'My first PHP driven whiney article', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '  Apartments are hard to find.  They all say "from \r\n$$$".  What the fuck is that all about?  From?? Like \r\nif you get the ratty one on the corner next to the \r\nparty animals that\'s the price, or is like car \r\ndealerships where they only have one apartment at that \r\nprice and it\'s already rented, but they are still able \r\nto claim that their other apartments are "from" that \r\nprice.  It\'s a load of shit!  Also you can never find \r\nan apartment that meets your price, let alone in the \r\narea you want to live in and if you find one at your \r\nprice in the area you want to live in, you can bet \r\nyour ass that it\'s a dump.  Or if you find one at your \r\nexact price a little out of area, it must be in a \r\ncrime infested zone.  Where your daily trip to the car \r\nwill be more like a walk through a demilitarized zone \r\nand your second day living there you will have to hire \r\nand escort and five of those white suburbans they blew \r\nup so many times in clear and present danger.  \r\n ', 'apartments are hard to find....', 20001015141852, 'flashbacks', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (80, 'Activists', 'Shroom', 'shroom', 'One day I decided to visit my friend Cracker at UCSC.  (note:  Graham will\r\nbe known as \'Cracker\' to protect the innocent).  Being the somewhat\r\nenvironmentalist type of person that I am, I biked to campus from my place\r\nof residence within the city limits of Santa Cruz.  Also, I don\'t own a\r\ncar.  You see, biking all the way up to campus is no big deal to me.  It\'s\r\nnice.  Try biking home day-in-day-out from UC Berkeley to your place in the\r\nBerkeley hills for a few years.  Then you\'ll understand where I\'m coming\r\nfrom.\r\n\r\nSo where was I?  Oh yes, sweating like a pig on a spit and dripping like I\r\nwas just spat on by gaggle of pigs, I find myself wandering in the vicinity\r\nof Porter College.  Porter College is one of 9 (soon to be 10) colleges on\r\nthe UCSC campus.  "What?" you say?  How can there be colleges within\r\ncolleges?  That\'s what I\'m still trying to figure out.\r\n\r\nSo there I am attempting to figure out which dorm building Cracker lives\r\nin.  There are no signs.  Just a few buildings.  I\'m at a loss.  What do I\r\ndo besides knock on every door in each building.  According to Murphy, the\r\nlast door I knock on will be his.  "There\'s got to be a better way", I\r\nthink to myself.\r\n\r\nJust then I notice flesh.  Sun-bathing flesh.  What strikes me\r\nparticularly  off guard is this flesh is sparsely  covered by a bra.  \r\nWoo hoo!  What better person to ask directions than a scantily clad \r\nsunbathing porter-type babe.  I bike up to her position on the well kept \r\ngrassy knoll and ask her if she happens to know where building 653Alpha42-\r\nwhisky-delta-foxtrot-3 is.  This really wasn\'t the number, see, since the \r\nactual building number has since vacated my memory.\r\n\r\nHer initial reaction to my query was the type you\'d expect if you decided\r\nto instead of wearing clothes to smear yourself in bullshit.  Not as bad,\r\nmind you, if you also did the same with toothpaste.  That would have been a\r\ntotally different reaction.  I thought perhaps there was a standard rule\r\nthat would protect sunbathers from harassment.  I could understand this. \r\nIf I was barely clothed and constantly had people asking me for directions,\r\nI\'d become peeved myself.  Of course, I would probably go somewhere else\r\nlike near a help desk or one of those nation park maps that are usually\r\nmade out of redwood (hmmm?).\r\n\r\nShe reluctantly gave me the info and I thanked her.  I made it to the\r\nproper building and noticed the door was locked.  But someone was coming\r\nout.  Nice.  As the woman opened the door she asked if she could help me. \r\nHmm, I didn\'t think the school budget could afford door-hops?  I said I\'m\r\njust on my way to visit a friend.  She must have thought she was still\r\nworking for the US National Missile Defense Program for she would not allow\r\nme to enter.  Apparently only Porter students can enter.  She told me I\r\nwould have to go through the \'other\' door to phone my friend down.\r\n\r\nSo far my experience at Port, a college I rarely visit save for the random\r\nvisits to the dining hall, has been most unwelcoming.  I make my way to the\r\nother door, walk through, down the hall, past the door I was allowed to not\r\nenter through, up the stairs and up to my friend’s dorm room.  That was\r\neasy.  It\'s a good thing I wasn\'t a spy or serial hide-hard-drives-behind-\r\ncopy-machines type shady character.\r\n\r\nI knock and enter.  Before we can being exchanging pleasantries, the\r\nscantily clad sun bather appears and knocks on Crackers door.  She has\r\nsince figured out how to mount her bra properly as well as ordained herself\r\nwith a t-shirt.\r\n\r\nI say to her, "oh hi, looks like I found it :}" (yes, I smiled). She asks\r\npromptly why I rode my bike on the grass.  At this point, I assume she is\r\nan RA (resident assistant, basically the people who keep the fort...err\r\nresidence halls down).  I also assume there is another known local law that\r\nprevents people from approaching people sunbathing on grassy knolls on a\r\nbike.\r\n\r\nI don\'t remember what I said at that point. Something along the lines \r\nof, "I don\'t know?".  What could you say at this point?  Anything would \r\nseem like a smart alec remark and I was attempting to prevent any more \r\nconfrontation with people.  Actually, I would have been less inclined if \r\nno one was on the grassy knoll.  Instead there were a few people, some \r\nwith lawn chairs.  She continued to cross-examine me.\r\n\r\n"I just want to know what\'s going on in peoples head that feel they can\r\nride their bikes all over the grass.  I\'m taking an environmental studies\r\nclass and we are trying to understand why people do these types of things."\r\nWow!  This girl is really taking her job seriously.  She also seems to be\r\nsomewhat overly empowered when it comes to policing our \'environment\'. \r\nWhat without her there might not be a single well watered and fertilized\r\nmowed lawn in site!  It would truly be an ugly campus indeed.\r\n\r\n"Promise me you will never do that again."\r\n\r\n"Sure."\r\n\r\nAnd off she goes.  Apparently her environmentalist senses began tingling \r\nand so had to go and protect another patch of lawn somewhere else.  I asked\r\nCracker if she was his RA.  This was the first time he saw her. He was also\r\nas confused as I was.\r\n\r\nTo this day, I thank her for making me realize just what kind of person I\r\nwas before our little talk.  My previous destructive behavior was\r\nunthinkable and unforgivable.  Now when I walk around campus and see\r\npatches of forest clear cut in favor of a new parking lot or buildings I\r\nthink back to that nice sun bather.  I know she\'ll be patrolling day and\r\nnite the small patches of grass, plants, and buildings that will replace\r\nthose lame redwoods, forest ferns, deer, squirrels, birds, and insects that\r\nonce plagued the surrounding UCSC campus.  Soon, UCSC will be beautiful.\r\n\r\n<I>Shroom currently resides in Berkeley and has organized several violent \r\nprotests in favor of nude sunbathing.</I>\r\n', 'lame environmentalists are lame.', 20001007221148, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (91, 'More companies that really suck ass, for Dummies!', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '\r\nThose verizon bastards really suck ass.<BR>\r\nNow Online at <a href="http://www.verizonreallysucksass.com" \r\ntarget="_top">www.VerizonReallySucksAss.com</a><BR>\r\n<br>\r\nThe above statement is an example of free speech.  IE: Freedom of \r\nexpression, as clearly protected under\r\nthe first ammendment to the United States Constitution.  The people at \r\nVerizon disagree.  They believe that \r\nspeaking as freely as you want is only ok if you\'re using a Verizon Cell \r\nPhone on the James Earl Jones sponsered\r\nVerizon network.<br>\r\n\r\n<BR>\r\nLearn more at <a href="http://www.verizonreallysucks.com" \r\ntarget="_top">VerizonReallySucks.com</a>, sponsered by your friends at <a  \r\ntarget="_top" href="http://www.2600.com">2600 Magazine</a>\r\n<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<center>\r\n<a href="mailto:thunt@thunt.net">Just Sue Me!</a><br>\r\n</center>\r\n<br>', 'VerizonSucksAss.com', 20001015142631, 'flashbacks', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (92, 'Elvis sighted at Blockbuster!', 'Marc Anthony', 'thunt@thunt.net', '  It was Sunday.  A normal sort of Sunday.  Birds were chirping, God was \r\ntelling the Christians to go to hell, heavens were enjoying football.  All \r\nseemed to be right with the universe.  At least that\'s what I thought.  \r\n  I didn\'t really have any plans for the day so I decided to walk down to \r\nthe local Blockbuster video store and rent a flick to while away the \r\nevening.  Ahhh, Blockbuster.  It\'s like a magical candyland where dreams \r\ncome true.  There are so many good movies, and none of them are offensive \r\nwith violence and nudity.  A perfect place for family entertainment.  I \r\nstarted off my search for a video by browsing the classics section.  We \r\nall know that it\'s a good idea to start out in the classics section, \r\nbecause all movies made before 1997 are pure shit, so you can cross them \r\noff your list right away and it\'s fun to look at those shitty movies in \r\nthe classics section and laugh at them.  Some of them don\'t even have \r\ncolor and others look all brown and shitty looking.  Like the shit they \r\nare.  Then I walked to the foreign section.  Because the only good kind of \r\nmovie are those that are made in English, cause other countries suck \r\ndonkey balls and are lucky we saved their dumb asses in that big war with \r\nthe fighting and shit.  So, as I\'m about to begin trashing on foreign \r\nfilms, cause they speak differently than me, I noticed him.  He was \r\nstanding outside the store looking in through the glass window.  He was \r\nwearing a black overcoat and a nicely tailored suit.  But there was \r\nsomething about his face that revealed more than he wanted to.  Because I \r\nknew, the second when he smiled that it was him.  It was Elvis.  I mean, \r\nthe man revolutionized rock \'n\' roll by stealing from the \'negroes\'.  The \r\nman is a fucking national hero and he is hiding out, afraid to even enter \r\na Blockbuster, because someone might identify him and rat him out to the \r\ntabloids again.  It\'s a sad sad state of affairs in America when a man who \r\nwas once King has to hide from his loving public.  Oh, and by the way, I\'m \r\nglad to see that my good friend Thunt has completely recovered.  Let us \r\nnever speak of this again.', '  It was Sunday.  A normal sort of Sunday.  Birds were chirping, God was telling the Christians to go to hell, heavens were enjoying football.  All seemed to be right with the universe.  At least that\'s what I thought.', 20001016160041, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (90, 'Cartoons on the Internet: Syndicate vs. Independent', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '	The Internet.  Millions, perhaps billions of computer users \r\nsurfing the web, with thousands more signing on everyday.  Some of them \r\nlooking for humor, many of them enjoying comic strips in their daily \r\nnewspapers.  Now this new media has given them a new option: Daily \r\nInternet Comics.  The question now is, can independent comics defeat \r\nsyndicated comics?  \r\n\r\n	Five years ago, this battle would have been in a large degree \r\nslanted towards the syndicated comics.  The Internet was not as popular.  \r\nNewspapers were most peoples source of comic strips.  For an independent \r\nto make it in those harsh times they had to be picked up locally or \r\nperhaps in smaller, more underground papers such as The Onion, or the \r\nSacramento News and Review.  Now the world is different.  Millions are on \r\nthe Internet.  In addition, they are noticing that they do not have to \r\nread tired old comics like Snoopy and Beatle Bailey.  They can have new \r\ncomics about what they do and with a sense of humor, that is more, their \r\nown than the sense of humor that corporate America has tried to force upon \r\nthem.   Within this new choice lies the future of independent comics.  \r\nComics that are drawn by students and as a hobby are now competing with \r\nprofessionally drawn comics like Dilbert and Doonesbury.  It is a new \r\nworld, and it will be interesting to see how things turn out.\r\n\r\n	However, the syndicates have not given up.  They have hosted their \r\ncomics online to provide competition to the young crop of independents.  \r\nWhile this may be seen by many to be a predatory move to wipe out these \r\nnew independents, I can only see this as a good thing for consumers of \r\ncomic strips.   Now you have your choice of comics, whether or not they \r\nwish to have a corporate sense of humor or a private one.\r\n\r\n\r\nHere\'s a comparison between Dilbert (corporate) and Userfriendly \r\n(independent)\r\n\r\n<div class="headline">Corporate:</div><BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<a class=link href="http://www.dilbert.com"><img border=0 \r\nsrc="http://www.dilbert.com/comics/dilbert/archive/images/dilbert2000101217\r\n907.gif"></a><BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<div class="headline">Independant:</div><BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<a class=link href="http://www.userfriendly.org/static/"><img border=0 \r\nsrc="http://www.userfriendly.org/cartoons/archives/00apr/uf001758.gif"></a>\r\n<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nThanks for reading.  Here is some more information:\r\n<BR>\r\n<UL>Works Cited\r\n	<B>Corporate Comics:</B><BR>\r\n		<LI><a class=link href="http://www.dilbert.com">Dilbert</a>\r\n		<LI><a class=link \r\nhref="http://www.doonesbury.com/dailydose/">Doonesbury</a>\r\n		<LI><a class=link href="http://www.foxtrot.com">Foxtrot</a>\r\n	<BR><BR>\r\n	<B>Independent Comics:</B><BR>\r\n		<LI><a class=link \r\nhref="http://www.userfriendly.org/static/">User Friendly</a>\r\n		<LI><a class=link href="http://www.penny-arcade.com">Penny \r\nArcade</a>\r\n		<LI><a class=link href="http://www.thebench.org">The \r\nBench - Open Source Comics!</a>\r\n	<BR><BR>\r\n	<a class=link href="http://www.faqs.org/ftp/faqs/comics/">Here is \r\nan HTML listing of an FTP site with Comic info</a><BR>\r\n	<BR><BR>\r\n	<B>Newsgroups about Comics:</B><BR>\r\n		<LI>alt.comics.dilbert\r\n		<LI>clari.living.comics.foxtrot\r\n		<LI>clari.living.comics.doonesbury\r\n	<BR>\r\n</UL>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n', 'thunt\'s report on comics for his CSC08 class.\r\n', 20001015142403, 'flashbacks', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (93, '20 ways the world could end.', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '', 'guarrented to quell any rouge optimism you might have.', 20001016231232, 'net_interest', 'www.discover.com/oct_00/featworld.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (94, 'Later I called this 4 reasons why you can feel better about yourself.', 'John', 'jpbruneau@hotmail.com', 'Problem#1: Butt for now it\'s just:\r\nDamnit!\r\n\r\nI got the skidders again. Everyone tells me its the samenella.  Every time \r\nI play with my gecko, within a min. I have to shit like I was \r\nchugging Exlax tm.\r\n\r\nProblem #2:\r\nI was talking to tom* on ICQ and he told me to post something. \r\nConveniently I have a shitload of studying to get done. So naturally \r\nI\'m writing this. I should if, I\'m not studying be cleaning... the flys \r\nout of the sink. Or reading for enjoyment, I have my Lego catalog or \r\nShawn Fanning Time or even my Nerds tm box just sitting there.  But no.  I \r\nwrite this crap.\r\n\r\n*(Not so much a problem as a disease)\r\n\r\nProblem#3:\r\n\r\nI\'m an ICAM major, for those of you who don\'t know what that means: Its \r\nInter-Disciplinary Computing Arts and Music, for those of you \r\nwho dont know what that means: Its computer graphics and a joke of \r\nunrelated crap. Practical courses taught form a theoretical \r\nstandpoint. I dont need to read 13 chapters on the thoughts and emotions \r\ndisplayed by video game space*. Neither do I need to know \r\nhow to calculate the acoustics of a room given a spring, a pint of coke \r\nand the weight in Newtons of a tuning fork on mars.  And for \r\nthose of you who don\'t know what that means... It means Living a Lifetime \r\nof shame and scrutiny.  To CSE we are mere fools who \r\ncouldn\'t hack it. To VA we are nerds who are devoid of creativity and \r\ninspiration. "You can\'t paint With ones and zero\'s man!" I was \r\ntold earlier this year by my studio Prof. when he learned of my secret. Im \r\nnot sure on what level he was speaking but he was very \r\nintense so I didn\'t bother ask. I only attended never went back to class. \r\nThis self-loathing results in darker and darker spiral with only \r\none hope for escape: Alcoholism\r\n\r\n*(Im not fucking Kidding! PacMan\'s maze is a metaphor for civil rights)\r\n\r\nProblem#4: Alcoholism (not to be confused with Alcobuddhism)\r\n\r\nI wanna Drink tonight! I had a Long day and everyone keeps telling me \r\nabout how its Monday and they have school tomorrow. It\'s not \r\nfair I drink whenever they want me to. I never give this "Im not in the \r\nmood." or "I have a headache tonight" Bull shit! With out the \r\nsweet honey of Micky\'s Fine Malt Liquor tm I will never be content going \r\nabout the drudgery of my pointless classes or happy knowing \r\nmy fellow students despise me and my gecko is trying to poison me.  Or the \r\nfact that my testicles were once ovaries until they got an \r\nextra hormone.* Besides  The neighbors are being real basterds and I need \r\nan excuse to pee on them.\r\n\r\n*(I relearned in bio-psyc what I already knew form Jurassic park)\r\nAuthors note: I dont know what Alcobuddhism is but I think It best \r\ndescribes my friend Andy who smoked his way out of UCSC (that \r\ntakes a lot of refer), claimed he was Buddha or at least that Buddha was \r\nhim, and passed out on my living room floor. He should start \r\npaying rent soon. I think. Vote Nader!\r\n\r\n(This does not necessarily represent the views of thunt.net. Tom neither \r\nindorses nor denies the use of alcohol, Mary Jane, Ralf Nader, \r\nor even \'gateway\' drugs like heroin and should not be held accountable for \r\nhis actions. ever.)\r\n\r\nFor more on the adventures of Andy and Nick (my roommate) who is currently \r\nwatching The Late Late Show, alas if only NBC came in \r\nclearer, You can read Kobra Kai or check out Oma Yang\'s new CD "From the \r\nhart of Jumbo Malaria"\r\n', '"two dogs and a cat or a bat fucking a pig"', 20001017095508, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (95, '$$$$ MAKE MONEY FAST $$$$', 'shroom', 'shroom', '                           $$$$ ATENTION $$$$$\r\n                     $$$$ START MAKING MONEY TODAY $$$$\r\n                         $$$$ FAST AND EASY $$$$\r\n\r\nYES!  The WORLD\'S greatest fantastic opportunity is here now!  YOU can\r\nnow make all the MONEY you\'d ever want and more.  Have more money than\r\nyou can count or spend.  Make more money than you know what to do with. \r\nEarn more MONEY than you could possibly spend in in a life time!  You can\r\ntalk and walk right?  Why not be LOADED as well!$!$!$!$!$!\r\n\r\nWhats the secret money making opportunity that I\'M inviting YOU to partake\r\nin NOW that millions of americans have no clue about?????????????????????\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n                         $$ GET A FUCKING JOB $$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<I>Editor\'s Note: I suggest emailing this to all of your friends, and \r\nmaybe even your friend\'s friends...  If we get this ball rolling, this \r\ncould completely wipe out unemployment.</i>', 'YES!  The WORLDS greatest fantastic opportunity is here now!', 20001018174125, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (96, 'Movies to watch: three super sub flicks', 'Ben Black', 'bigben119@home.com', 'Like most thunt.net readers, you are probably always on the lookout for \r\nthat next great film to find its way to DVD.  Here are three great movies \r\nthat just happen to all take place on a submarine, and are all available \r\non DVD:\r\n\r\n<B>Run Silent, Run Deep</B>\r\nThis one first rolled in theaters in 1958.  It is NOT one of the formula \r\nwar pictures that Hollywood couldn\'t stop making after WWII.  It\'s a \r\nbattle of wills between Cary Grant and Burt Lancaster.  About 95 minutes \r\nlong, a good warm-up for...\r\n\r\n<B>The Hunt for Red October</B>\r\nTom Clancy has gotten a bit long-winded with his novels, lately.  The last \r\nfew have each broken the 1000 page mark with ease.  However, back when he \r\nwas still up-and-coming, he wrote an excellent story about a Soviet \r\nsubmarine that everyone is anxious to find.  The book is excellent, and \r\ndeserves your time.  Edited liberally to fit into a 2 hour and 15 minute \r\nmovie, the story still stands strong.  Look for strong performances from \r\nthe entire cast.  It\'s worth watching again.\r\n\r\n\r\nI thought that The Hunt for Red October was the best submarine movie \r\nmade.  Until I watched...\r\n\r\n<B>Das Boot (Director\'s Cut)</B>\r\nThis movie is incredible.  First released in 1981 at 145 minutes.  \r\nDirector Wolfgang Peterson apparently felt that wasn\'t adequate to tell \r\nthe story he wanted to tell with this film.  For the Director\'s Cut \r\nedition on DVD, he restored almost a full hour of editing.  Yes, movie \r\nbuffs, this one now weighs in at about 200 minutes.  However, don\'t be \r\nfooled.  Wolfgang knows his stuff, and the movie is excellent.  A very \r\ncaptivating tale of young german sailors full of themselves and the glory \r\nthat they will find at sea.  Reality hits, naturally.  I can\'t say enough \r\nabout this film.\r\n\r\n\r\n<B>About the disks</B>\r\nThe DVDs, apart from the movies they contain, are nothing exciting.  Each \r\nmovie is presented in widescreen format.  Run Silent and Red October \r\nsimply have the movie, and perhaps trailers.  Das Boot has a pitifly short \r\nfeaturette on making the film.  It also has a commentary track, but I \r\ndidn\'t get the time to listen to it.  \r\n\r\nDas Boot offers the choice between english dubbing or subtitles.  For a \r\nchuckle, try the dubbing and compare it to the subtitle for the same \r\nscene.  The "tour of the sub" is a good chapter for this.  The dubbing is \r\nsubtly different than the subtitles, which feel more genuine in their \r\nlanguage and choice of words.\r\n\r\n\r\nSo, there you have it, readers.  Three great films to put on your list the \r\nnext time you rent DVDs.  If your local selection sucks, as does mine, you \r\nmight try NetFlix (www.netflix.com) for your rentals.  It\'s an odd \r\nprogram, DVDs by mail, but the selection is excellent.  Their catalog \r\ndescription of films is weak, so it\'s best if you know what you want going \r\nin.\r\n\r\n\r\nAbout the author:\r\n<i>Full time kernel hacker, part time movie buff.  Former shout-out man \r\nfor thunt.net.  At one point an excellent writer, laziness has taken its \r\ntoll, and the result is in front of you. </i>\r\n\r\n<i>Editor\'s note: Thunt didn\'t even have to write a snappy about the \r\nauthor, the author wrote it himself, now that\'s snappy!</i>\r\n', 'Looking for a cool trio of movies on DVD?  Our man in Colorado is doing the dirty work of watching films and passing tips on to thunt.net readers.', 20001020171722, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (97, 'How to set up a Fascist Regime in your workplace', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '<B>Underpay your subordinates</b>\r\n	Nothing makes people happier than knowing they are paid less than \r\nyou.  I suggest cutting the salaries of your workers back at the beginning \r\nof the year holding back most of the money in the payroll budget, so that \r\nyou’ll have a nice nest egg to embezzle at the end of the year.  Oh, and \r\nit’s also a really good idea to tell your brainless subordinates that you \r\nwill give them raises if they perform well.  Like Pavlov and his dogs, \r\nnothing works better than the power of positive reinforcement.  Or was \r\nthat negative reinforcement?  Regardless, on to point two…\r\n\r\n<B>Random Threats</b>\r\n	You might have thought Minor Threat was a good band, but wait \r\nuntil you hear how much fun you can have with Random Threats.  While in \r\npoint one I suggested you, tell your employees that you will give them \r\nraises.  That was not entirely true.  I suggest you threaten your \r\nemployees with massive pay cuts at the drop of the hat.  Lets say that one-\r\nday, one of your employees fails to open the door for you.  Fine them 50 \r\ndollars.  Do not fuck around.  You have to show those little scumbags \r\nwho’s the boss.  And I’m not talking about the 80’s TV show with Alyssa \r\nMilano and TonyFuckingDanza.  I’m talking about fascism, like Hitler and \r\nStalin.  They didn’t take any crap and neither should you.  And lets say \r\none of your subordinates drinks the last cup of coffee, or reads a web \r\npage you told them not to read, threaten to fire their ass.  Don’t even \r\nfuck around with the pay cut, pass go, collect your 200 dollars and inform \r\nthem that they might have to look for a new job.  Remember, you may depend \r\non your workers to run your factory, but they are generally so dumb they \r\ndo not know that.  Feel free to power trip all over them and keep the \r\nbastards in line.  And remember, for each pay cut you give them, that just \r\nputs more money in the “Send the boss to Hawaii” and the “Jack Daniels \r\nMemorial Charity Fund”.  \r\n\r\n<B>Censorship</b>\r\n	If any of your subordinates speak out against you, they must be \r\nsilenced immediately.  I suggest framing them.  It worked for Stalin (vs. \r\nTrotsky) and it will work for you.  Lets say for example that your \r\nConstruction Division builds a faulty Lighthouse.  Three days later, it \r\nfalls down.  Now, none of your subordinates have any knowledge about \r\nLighthouses.  This is where the framing part comes in.  If you want to get \r\nrid of Vice President Snowball, I suggest editing all of your records and \r\nremoving your name and adding Snowball’s name.  Then tell your \r\nsubordinates that Snowball is responsible for the Lighthouse tumbling to \r\nthe ground.  They will hate Snowball and probably castrate him.  Remember \r\nwhat happened to Trotsky.  Due to Stalin’s brilliant framing, he ended up \r\nin Mexico City with an ice pick sticking out of the side of his head.  \r\nThis plan is great because it ends resistance and gives you someone to \r\nblame in case any of your plans go haywire.\r\n\r\n<B>Rigging Elections</b>\r\n	In the People’s Republic of China, they have a policy: One Man, \r\nOne Vote, One Candidate.  This is the best way to rig an election; the \r\npeople have no choice but to vote for you.  Another good way is with an \r\napproval poll.  The people know they have to vote “Yes: I approve of the \r\nfascist regime” or else you can have your secret police hunt them down \r\nlike the donut pilfering grab-asses they are. Finally comes the best way \r\nto rig an election, have a man inside.  When the parliamentary committee \r\nis deciding who should be Prime Minister, your man is inside the debates.  \r\nHe steers the discussion away from other more qualified candidates and \r\ncreates controversy.  If this is done right, the committee will ignore the \r\nqualified candidates and listen to the “sage-like” advice of your man.  \r\nThis is one way, that with just one man on the inside, you can rig an \r\nelection and gain power over a whole country.  \r\n\r\nThese are just some of the many ways to set up a facist regime in your \r\nworkplace.  If you would like to know more, please visit your local \r\nlibrary where you can learn more about Pavlov, Communists, and Fascists, \r\noh my!\r\n\r\n\r\n', '<B>Underpay your subordinates</b>:\r\n	Nothing makes people happier than knowing they are paid less than you.  I suggest cutting the salaries of your workers back at the beginning of the year holding back most of the money in the payroll budget, so that you', 20001022144359, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (98, 'World Death Rate Holding Steady at 100 Percent', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '', 'GENEVA, SWITZERLAND--World Health Organization officials expressed disappointment Monday at the groups finding that, despite the enormous efforts of doctors, rescue workers and other medical professionals worldwide, the global death rate remains constant', 20001022144938, 'net_interest', 'www.theonion.com/onion3102/deathrate.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (99, 'Thunt.net for Dummies', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '05-07-00 12:35 pm\r\n5 days until Thomas-mas!\r\n\r\nHave you guys heard about this?  <a href="http://www.idgbooks.com">IDG \r\nBooks</a>, the maker of the "for dummies" books is suing everyone who uses \r\nthe words "for dummies" on their webpage.  It\'s\r\nreally funny...  \r\n\r\nFor a hilarous dialogue between a parody site and IDG check out <a \r\nhref="http://www.octapod.org.au/dummies/">Corporate Standover Tactics for \r\nDummies</a>\r\nIt\'s a really great site.  The company tries to explain how they have \r\ncopywrited the phrase "for dummies" and the author responds sarcastically.\r\nI think the author should do what Larry Flynt did to Fallwell, "Counter-\r\nsue"...<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<a href="http://www.users.one.se/~feltby/idgb_smells/">IDGB are \r\nDummies</a> takes a more campaign oriented approach against this\r\nkind of corporate stupidity...<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nThis is a classic story <a \r\nhref="http://www.ucolick.org/~de/idgNonsense.html">here</a>... The author\r\nwrote a help file for CVS, which he casually called <a \r\nhref="http://www.ucolick.org/~de/CVSbeginner.html">CVS for dummies</a>,\r\nhe too recieved a nice cease and desist from the Dummies Legal Crew<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nI like this idea.  No one can copywrite words like "for dummies".  It\'s \r\ninsane!  Therefore, I\'ll be titling most of the stuff I \r\nwrite for a while, with a for dummies extension.  Hopefully I\'ll get sued \r\ntoo, cause anyone can look at my huge credit card \r\ndebt and know that I\'m the man to sue....<BR>\r\n<BR>', 'Have you guys heard about this?  <a href="http://www.idgbooks.com">IDG Books</a>, the maker of the \r\n"for dummies" books is suing everyone who uses the words "for dummies" on their webpage.  It\'s\r\nreally funny...', 20001022145209, 'flashbacks', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (100, 'A thought, from Kevin Smith', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '05-01-00 5:13 pm\r\n11 days until Thomas-mas!\r\n\r\nJust a thought.\r\n\r\n"The great irony is that most Christians aren\'t Christian. They just don\'t \r\nbehave as Christ would behave. Christ was not a judgmental condemnation \r\nfreak. Christ hung out with hookers and tax collectors, who I guess were \r\nas bad as hookers at the time, and lepers. I mean the bungled and the \r\nbotched. He wasn\'t the guy who was like, "I only want to hang out with \r\nreally good people." I mean he hung out with people, in general, period."\r\n\r\nKevin Smith, Writer/Director (Clerks, Mallrats, Chasing Amy, Dogma)\r\n\r\nExcerpted from his interview at \r\n<a href="http://www.dvdfile.com">DVDFILE.COM</a>', 'Just a thought from Kevin Smith, Writer/Director (Clerks, Mallrats, Chasing Amy, Dogma)\r\n\r\n', 20001022145327, 'flashbacks', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (101, 'Whoring out to Amazon.com or "Recommended Reading"', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '04-24-00 3:04  \r\n\r\nIn another attempt to whore and become the whore I know I am, I\'m offering \r\na list of shit I think you should buy.  The catch is that there are nice \r\nand purdy links to amazon.com with each book... you get the idea.<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<U>Three Books everyone should own</U><BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<OL>\r\n	<LI><A \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0451191145/thuntnet" \r\nclass="link">Atlas Shrugged by Ayn Rand</a>\r\n	<LI><A \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0316769487/thuntnet" \r\nclass="link">The Catcher in the Rye by J.D. Salinger</a>\r\n	<LI><A \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0553213601/thuntnet" \r\nclass="link">Cyrano De Bergerac by Edmund Rostand</a>\r\n</OL>\r\n<BR>\r\n<U>Other favorites from my shelf</u><BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<UL>\r\n	<LI><A class="link" \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0140707050/thuntnet">MacBeth \r\n(New Penguin Shakespeare)</A> \r\n	<LI><A class="link" \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0451526929/thuntnet">Hamlet</A\r\n> \r\n	<LI><A class="link" \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0517053616/thuntnet">The \r\nComplete Works of William Shakespeare</A> \r\n	<LI><A class="link" \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0684833395/thuntnet">Catch-\r\n22</A> \r\n	<LI><A class="link" \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0451524934/thuntnet">1984</A> \r\n	<LI><A class="link" \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0451526341/thuntnet">Animal \r\nFarm : A Fairy Story</A> \r\n	<LI><A class="link" \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0060929871/thuntnet">Brave \r\nNew World (Perennial Classics)</A> \r\n	<LI><A class="link" \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0553562614/thuntnet">Snow \r\nCrash</A> \r\n	<LI><A class="link" \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0679735771/thuntnet">American \r\nPsycho : A Novel</A> \r\n	<LI><A class="link" \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0517149257/thuntnet">The \r\nUltimate Hitchhiker\'s Guide</A> \r\n	<LI><A class="link" \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0805062971/thuntnet">Fight \r\nClub</A> \r\n	<LI><A class="link" \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0440539811/thuntnet">The \r\nIlluminatus Trilogy</A> \r\n	<LI><A class="link" \r\nHREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0440500702/thuntnet">Schroding\r\ner\'s Cat Trilogy</A> \r\n</UL>\r\nPositive: I remembered who has borrowed some of these books and now I vow \r\nto take their heads.\r\nYou know who you are and what you have.  Bhaskar and Mike!<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nNegative: I found out that Robert Anton Wilson, author of the last two on \r\nthe list and the two borrowed books,\r\nhas written a great deal more than I thought.  I want them, yet I am so \r\npoor.  Also I fear if I purchased them,\r\nthey would be borrowed away before I could read them! CURSES!<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n', 'In another attempt to whore and become the whore I know I am, I\'m offering a list of shit I think you should buy.  The catch is that there are nice and purdy links to amazon.com with each book... you get the idea.', 20001022145518, 'flashbacks', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (102, 'Arafat\'s response to Barak\'s timeout: \'Go to hell\'', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '', 'Fuckin\'A man.  Foreign Policy becomes interesting again.  This guy straight up told his advisary to go to hell.  Now that\'s rad.', 20001022152348, 'net_interest', 'dailynews.netscape.com/dailynews/cnnnews.tmpl?story=mideast.reaction.021022.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (104, 'Fuck the Government', 'Chris Carroll', 'godmodule@yahoo.com', '   Hello, children. Today we are going to learn about one of the many ways \r\nthat the government tries to screw you over and silence your political \r\nvoice. You see, I moved a few months ago to Sacramento and even though I \r\nfilled out the proper application from DMV, as well as the Post Office, I \r\nhave not yet received a sample ballot. I also confirmed today that I am \r\nsomehow not registered to vote in this county. The response that I \r\nreceived from the party on the other line was this: "sometimes we don\'t \r\nget our information from the DMV." My question is this: where the HELL do \r\nyou get the information from then?! My theory is that the government \r\ndoesn\'t like me. They complain about a low voter turnout, but they seem to \r\nlose registration forms. Funny, huh? Don\'t you ever wonder how big your \r\nFBI file is? Now don\'t get me wrong here, I\'m not paranoid. It could all \r\nbe a little misunderstanding. Or maybe not... See, a certain Mr. Thunt \r\nalso moved a few months ago and he didn\'t receive a sample ballot either. \r\nCoincidence? I think not. Fuck the government for trying to take away my \r\nvote, even if I don\'t have a choice besides a couple of idiots who want to \r\nreinstate the draft and send people to die for something that they might \r\nnot believe in. The two party system of this country is a joke. Even \r\nthough there are more than 2 people running for president, the American \r\npeople would never guess it. Let me simplify, you are narrowed down to two \r\nchoices, Republican or Democrat. This happens because Americans are too \r\nfucking ignorant to explore other possibilities. People are so close \r\nminded. Anyway, thank you for letting me rant, Thunt. In the meantime \r\nkiddies, don\'t let the government get you.\r\n\r\n-Chris Carroll, Leftist Extraordinaire\r\n\r\n<i>Editor\'s Note: Upon reinstatement of the draft, I will be hosting a \r\nhousewarming party in Canada.  All dissidents are invited.  Escape: Accept \r\nno substitutes.</i>\r\n', 'Hello, children. Today we are going to learn about one of the many ways that the government tries to screw you over and silence your political voice.', 20001027101234, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (105, 'ca4animals.org launched!', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '  Thomas Hunt has just completed principal construction of \r\n<a \r\nhref="http://www.ca4animals.org">www.ca4animals.org</a>.  The Californians \r\nfor Animal Protection is a group run by Thunt\'s crazy animal\r\nrights friends in San Fransisco, with the infamous "Bhaskar" at\r\nthe forefront of the action.  \r\n\r\n  The site is epic.  In two major ways, it\'s construction and it\'s goals. \r\n\r\nEarthshaking Goals: The Board of Supervisiors in San Francisco is voting \r\non a proposition to ban the sale of fur in San Francisco, this would be an \r\nfantastic victory for the animal rights cause.\r\n\r\nZeus-like Construction: The site features a mySQL database accessed by a \r\nPHP front end, with two modes of displays and a fancy form to enter data \r\n(hense the group themselves were allowed to enter the data themselves... \r\nhehehe saving me some work)\r\n\r\nSo I suggest you check it out and vote pro-animal in the upcomming \r\nelection.  \r\n\r\n\r\n', '  Thomas Hunt has just completed principal construction of <a href="http://www.ca4animals.org">www.ca4animals.org</a>.  The Californians for Animal Protection is a group run by Thunt\'s crazy animal rights friends in San Fransisco, with the infamous', 20001031114117, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (106, 'Smells like crushed teen spirit', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '', 'The 10 scariest things that could happen to the digital world.\r\n\r\n- - - - - - - - - - - -\r\nBy the Salon Technology Staff\r\n\r\n', 20001031120238, 'net_interest', 'www.salon.com/tech/log/2000/10/31/halloween/index.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (107, 'Geek accused of crime for being a Geek', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '', 'Another geek whose computers were taken by the FBI because he was a geek.  Terrifying.', 20001031175811, 'net_interest', 'devrandom.net/~dilinger/');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (108, 'ca4animals.org featured on IDA\'s main page', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', ' Pretty cool news to report today on the animal rights front...  \r\n<a href="http://idausa.org">IDA</a> (In Defense of Animals), a national \r\nanimal rights organization has placed a link and a story about <a \r\nhref="http://ca4animals.org">Californians for Animal Protection</a> on \r\ntheir main page.  It\'s pretty rad to see Bhaskar\'s newly formed group get \r\nthis kind of attention.  Let\'s all cross our fingers and hope the election \r\ngoes well.\r\n\r\n', ' Pretty cool news to report today on the animal rights front...  \r\n<a href="http://idausa.org">IDA</a> (In Defense of Animals), a national animal rights organization has placed a link and a story about <a href="http://ca4animals.org">Californians for Anim', 20001102185247, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (109, 'The voyage of the good ship Nosferatu III Released!', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Thunt\'s second Defcon video has just been released to the internet!\r\n\r\nCheck it out at <a href="http://thunt.net/defcon">thunt.net/defcon</a>!!\r\n\r\nThe Juicy Details:\r\n  Four men and one woman against the mighty forces of mother nature. Watch \r\nas the drama explodes as this swarthy crew rides the good ship Nosferatu \r\nIII all the way to Los Vegas. Expect a great deal of profanity, piracy and \r\npornography. May not be apropriate for small children or christians.\r\n\r\nStarring: Brian Feaster, Emily Stumpf, Tim Heilman, \'Graham\', and \'Thunt\'.\r\n\r\nDirected by Thomas Hunt \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'Thunt\'s second Defcon video has just been released to the internet!\r\n\r\nCheck it out at <a href="http://thunt.net/defcon">thunt.net/defcon</a>!!\r\n\r\nThe Juicy Details:\r\n  Four men and one woman against the mighty forces of mother nature. Watch as the drama', 20001103135556, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (110, 'Hunter S. Thompson Article on ESPN.com', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '', 'Baseball has become unruly\r\nBy Hunter S. Thompson\r\nSpecial to Page 2\r\n\r\nHi, folks. My name is Thompson, and I don\'t have much space for this high-speed presentation, so let\'s get started and see how tight we can make it. My job is to devise a whole new se', 20001106152625, 'net_interest', 'espn.go.com/page2/s/thompson/001106.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (111, 'An Open Letter from Moore to Gore', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '', 'Dear Vice-President Gore:\r\n\r\nHi! How are you! It\'s been awhile since we\'ve talked. Everything OK?\r\n\r\nSorry. Enough teasing. I\'ve been getting a lot of calls from your friends and supporters. Man, are they freaked out! They actually think you are going to', 20001106191537, 'net_interest', 'www.michaelmoore.com/2000_10_31.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (112, 'Feeling American in the morning', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '  I feel like such a good little American today, having voted in my first \r\nPresidential Election.  An election I was almost not allowed to vote in \r\nseeing as how I moved, failed to re-register, and my sample ballott was \r\nnot forwarded by the post office.  But fortunately I thought to myself, \r\nhmmm, I was registered over there, and perhaps I still am.  So I went \r\nthere, barely identified myself and within a few minutes I was voting. \r\nHell fucking yeah!  \r\n\r\n  So, who did I vote for.  Well, I voted like a good Anti today.  I voted \r\nanti-Bush (gore), anti-Feinstien (that rabid bitch wants to end free \r\nspeech on the internet, so I did vote for Republican Tom Cambell), and \r\nanti-vouchers.\r\n\r\n  Have you voted today?  Are you going to vote today?  Well, you should.  \r\nBecause voting is your American right.  Or perhaps you shouldn\'t, because \r\neveryone who doesn\'t vote only make my vote stronger.  \r\n\r\n  Comming Soon: Thomas rants on how lame the electoral college system is.  \r\nOr perhaps how it saved the world from the evils of the \'W\' monster.', '  I feel like such a good little American today, having voted in my first Presidential Election.  An election I was almost not allowed to vote in seeing as how I moved, failed to re-register, and my sample ballott was not forwarded by the post office.  Bu', 20001107093000, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (113, 'Driveways of the Rich and Famous', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '', '', 20001108180910, 'net_interest', 'www.driveways.com/');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (114, 'I Outwitted the Government', 'Chris Carroll', 'godmodule@yahoo.com', 'Hello again kiddies. Last time I wrote on thunt.net I was very angry at \r\nthe government for taking away my right to vote. Well, today I voted \r\nbecause I am smarter than the government. I went down to the registrar and \r\ngot a court order (yes, I have a real court case on file!) which enabled \r\nme to pick up my ballot yesterday and vote today. I did it, I beat the \r\ngovernment...for now. The next thing you know, the government will be \r\nfinding ways to screw Chris over again. But you know what, I\'ll just keep \r\non fighting back. Take that, and this, and that you silly government. \r\nDon\'t make me he-bitch man-slap ya.\r\n\r\nAnyway, I have to agree with thunt when he says he voted anti-Bush and so \r\ndid I. Simple and plain, if George W becomes the next president, we\'re all \r\ngoing to war. Bush has already killed more people than he can count, even \r\nif he took his pants and socks off. I also voted anti-Feinstein although I \r\nwill admit that I was not aware that she wants to ban free speech on the \r\ninternet. I am comforted that I voted against her. As for the local \r\nelection, I believe that I should be the next mayor. As your mayor, I \r\nwould try to be as hypocritical as possible and try to best those that \r\ncame before me.\r\n\r\nSincerely your mayor,\r\n\r\nChris Carroll\r\n\r\nP.S.: Thunt for President!!!!', 'Hello again kiddies. Last time I wrote on thunt.net I was very angry at the government for taking away my right to vote. Well, today I voted because I am smarter than the government.', 20001109193443, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (115, 'Am I hot or Not', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '', 'fun game to play.\r\ninteresting combo of insulting people and voyeristic porn.\r\n', 20001113180159, 'net_interest', 'www.amihotornot.com/');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (116, 'Frost on my Window: Another day without a President', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '  Frost on my window, another day without a President.\r\n  Our country sits like a leaderless beast as I read my e-mail.\r\n  Like a slumbering tiger, but there are no worries.\r\n  The people are finally learning that their vote doesn\'t count.\r\n  The pundits claim the electoral college protects the small states.\r\n  If it protects the small states what does it do for the large states?\r\n\r\n  It\'s a cloudy day and the air is cold.\r\n  We in California will have to wear warm clothes today.\r\n  A shock to our system, but the news is old.\r\n  Which millionare will step up to lead us this winter?\r\n  No one can say.  Will there be a difference?\r\n  There surely wasn\'t one on election day.\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'another lame attempt at poetry, I should really spend more time at it rather than trying to crank out a new poem in the hours between 10:13 AM and 10:14 AM.\r\n', 20001114101222, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (117, 'A Public Apology to the former techinal staff of StateHornet.com', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '\r\n     I would like to publicly apologize to the staff members who served \r\nwith me last year at the statehornet.com.  Their names are Matt Brown, \r\nLucas Harbour, Jon Navarra, Chris Carroll and Phil Sublett.  I feel that \r\nit is my duty to apologize for what has been happening lately.  The media \r\nthat has been covering the success of stathornet.com has been doing \r\nnothing but lying.  A company named CampusEngine has been taking credit \r\nfor our hard work.  They have been claiming that it was their tools that \r\nwere responsible for the success of the statehornet.com.  These claims has \r\nbeen backed by those in power at the State Hornet Newspaper.  However, the \r\ntruth is that Matt Brown, Lucas Harbour, Jon Navarra, Chris Carroll and \r\nPhil Sublett were responsible for the success of the statehornet.com.  It \r\nwas your hard work updating the page every day that made it a daily online \r\nnewspaper.  It was your tireless efforts converting the print edition to \r\nHTML and filming video so we could put it online that made the \r\nstatehornet.com a success.  I am sorry that I have allowed others to take \r\ncredit for your sacrifices.  I am sorry that neither our names nor even \r\nour existence has been mentioned in these magazines.  I was not contacted \r\nby these publications, and if I were I certainly would have given you the \r\ncredit that you deserve.\r\n\r\nAs I was nominally in charge of the online division of the \r\nstatehornet.com, I take full responsibility for the way that your hard \r\nwork has been taken advantage of by these profiteers and I pledge that I \r\nwill do what I can to see that your hard work receives its just reward.\r\n\r\n  Thomas Hunt\r\n  Former Senior Site Manager, StateHornet.com\r\n\r\n\r\nRelated Stories (lies):\r\n\r\n<a \r\nhref="http://www.convergemag.com/Publications/CNVGOct00/newMediaLearning.sh\r\ntm">Convergence Magazine</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.campusengine.com/about/press/press08.shtml">\r\nCampus Engine Press Release</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.sacbee.com/ib/news/old/ib_news02_20000615.html">\r\nSacramento Bee - Inside Business</a>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '     I would like to publicly apologize to the staff members who served with me last year at the statehornet.com.  Their names are Matt Brown, Lucas Harbour, Jon Navarra, Chris Carroll and Phil Sublett.  I feel that it is my duty to apologize for what has', 20001115011535, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (118, 'Happy Thanksgiving from CampusEngine.com!', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '\r\nI regret to inform you of the most horrible news, that I heard today on \r\nFox 40 news at 10.  CampusEngine.com, america\'s favorite start-up company \r\nhas laid off over half of their workforce (25 of 66 workers).  This is \r\njust horrible to hear about.  I personally am mortified to see that the \r\nmanagement of campus engine would layoff almost half of their workforce \r\nthe day before Thanksgiving.  And the way that it was covered on all of \r\nthe major local news organizations can only be regarded as bad press, \r\nespically when each newscast mentioned how much "angel" money campus \r\nengine had recently won.  Although they didn\'t say, you could tell the \r\nnewscasters were pondering to themselves, where did this money go?  Was it \r\nmisspent?  Did it disapear?  I personally have no clue nor comment, and \r\nneither did the newspeople reading the story, but it is interesting to \r\nthink about what if\'s from time to time.\r\n\r\nAlso in the news today was the State Hornet (with the campus engine \r\nstory).  Channel 3 news even had a picture of our good friend Ryan Endeen, \r\nof course it was a low angle shot, kinda up his nose, but it\'s still \r\npretty cool to see the good man Ryan getting some press from this Campus \r\nEngine layoff thing.\r\n\r\nAlso the hornet webpage was on TV with the Campus Engine story!  Isn\'t that\r\ngreat!  Of course on the top center of the news section there was a broken \r\nimage. Boy if I was in charge of that shitty website, I would shoot \r\nmyself, or if I was one of the technical visionaries who feel free to give \r\ninterviews to magazines about how they created the website, I would also \r\nfeel horrible.  But, I\'m not. \r\n\r\nI hope you all have a great Thanksgiving and spend the holiday either \r\nthankful that you have a good paying job at a profitable company (or with \r\nthe government, who could be more profitable!) or that you spend the \r\nholiday polishing your resume and preparing to go back out into that brave \r\nnew world that we live in.\r\n\r\n\r\n', '\r\nI regret to inform you of the most horrible news, that I heard today on Fox 40 news at 10.  CampusEngine.com, america\'s favorite start-up company has laid off over half of their workforce (25 of 66 workers).  This is just horrible to hear about.  I pers', 20001122225550, 'normal', '');
