INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (124, 'Another soul saved!', 'St. Shrewm', 'shroom', 'I had given a WWJD bracelet to a friend whom I knew\r\nwas struggling with alcohol. He had it a\r\ncouple of days when he called me one evening. He\r\nsaid "Bob, I hate this bracelet!" Shocked I hesitated\r\nand asked why. He said, "Every time I go to the\r\nrefrigerator and reach for a beer, I see my bracelet\r\nand I can\'t take one! AND I WANT A BEER! Then when I\r\ngo to take it off, I see Jesus watching me and I\r\nbreakdown. PRAISE THE LORD! Thank you! \r\nBob, North Carolina, USA \r\n\r\nRelated Links:\r\n<a href="http://www.wwjd.com/test.html">WWJD Testimonials</a>\r\n<a href="http://www.brunching.com/features/feature-loreletssee.html">\r\nLore: What would Jesus Eat?</a>\r\n\r\n<i>Editor\'s note: The new what would thunt do? (WWTD) line of bracelets \r\nwill be out this Spring.  Only 12.99, and a definate must for all of you \r\nsinners. BTW: Why would Jesus not want a beer?  As I recall he spent most \r\nof his time turning water into wine.  What an alkie.</i>  ', 'www.wwjd.com/test.html  Testimonials of a very prettybracelet', 20001206213424, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (233, 'Brief Thunt.net outage', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Just a real brief FYI for all you Thunt.neters out there.  <a \r\nhref=http://dv8.org>Dv8.org</a>, the server that hosts Thunt.net, has been \r\nupgraded to php 3.0.18...  And due to a error during this upgrade, \r\nThunt.net was down most of the day on Sunday April 29th.  We apologize for \r\nthe inconvience. ', '', 20010429181239, 'net_interest', 'http://dv8.org');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (125, 'Call Out Your Professor', 'Matt Brown', 'grinch@homegettingablowjob.com', 'I have a radical new idea that could forever alter our university \r\nsystem.  In our day and age, even getting enrolled in a class could \r\nmean dozens of signatures and forms.  Even the elective courses in our \r\ndegree programs have to be chosen with the approval of a academic \r\nadvisor.  All of this is nothing compared to the hell of a grade appeal.  \r\nWhen a professor, or who ever the department could con into “teaching” the \r\ncourse, sits down to assign grades, so many other factors can enter the \r\ndecision, and many students feel like they were cheated.  The current \r\ngrade appeal process is simply unacaptable, because the faculty always \r\nsticks together, and your average student doesn\'t stand a chance.\r\n\r\nThat is why a new grade resoultion process is needed, and I think our best \r\nbet is to return to a classical dispute resolution system – the duel.  If \r\na student has a problem with the grade they received, they should be able \r\nto walk right up to that person and call them out.  The teacher would then \r\nbe given the right to choose between pistols or swords at dawn in front of \r\nthe library.  This could also work with other student vs. administration \r\nbattles.  I myself had to appeal two parking tickets last week, all \r\nbecause the masterbating reject with the ticket machine wasn’t able to \r\nlocate the daily permit, that happened to be right on my motherfucking  \r\ndashboard.  I felt unsatisified with the “fill out this form, and we’ll \r\nlet you know” appeal.  I believe that I should be able to face my accuser, \r\nand challenge him/her to open combat.\r\n\r\nThere are some people out there who feel violence doesn’t solve problems, \r\nand they can go fuck themselves.  When you study history, all you learn is \r\nhow people use violence to solve their problems, it’s the most effective \r\nway to resolve any disagreement.  In fact  when solutions have been non-\r\nviolent, it has led to nothing but disaster.\r\n\r\nSociety has degraded to the point where mass beaurcracies are cruching the \r\nindividual.  Humanity is still all about self-interest, so we cannot \r\nattempt to solve problems with logic.  The strong still get their way, but \r\nthe way we determine strength has changed, and the “normal” person doesn’t \r\nhave a chance.\r\n\r\nI know my solution may be a bit drastic and uncomfortable at first, but \r\nthe people would be able to govern themselves again.  I welcome any of \r\nyour thoughts on Thunt\'s message board.\r\n\r\np.s.  If you are frightened and think this is serious, then obviously \r\nthunt.net has taught you nothing, and I have a really good deal on some \r\nelevator passes.\r\n\r\np.p.s. Kudos to the exclamation point and other friends on their recent \r\naccolades, you guys kick ass.\r\n\r\n<i>Editor\'s Note: Editing is hard.  Sometimes you want to chop whole parts \r\nout.  Other times you just leave whole parts in because, why the hell \r\nnot.  You guess which policy I\'m following.  It\'s a fun game.</i>', 'The blueprint to a better society', 20001208185024, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (126, 'The KOOLest thing I\'ve ever seen', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'You absolutely will not believe what the State of Kentucky just put up on \r\nthe Internet.\r\n\r\nKentucky Offender Online Lookup.\r\n\r\nYes, that\'s right, now you can look up the data of anyone in the Kentucky \r\nprison system.  Right now they only have pictures of death row inmates, \r\nbut soon they will expand that to the entire system.  Aparently it is only \r\nsupposted to be available to the news media (very trustworthy) and the \r\npolice (extremely honorable).  But just right now, I was able to search \r\nthe database without any credentials at all.  This is sooo KOOL!\r\n\r\nhehehe.\r\n\r\nCheck it out at: \r\n  <a href="http://www.cor.state.ky.us/~KOOL/ioffsrch.asp">KOOL</a>\r\n\r\nRelated Links:\r\n<a href="http://www.courier-\r\njournal.com/localnews/2000/0012/06/001206kool.html">\r\n  Courier Journal covers the story</a>\r\n<a href="http://www.hackernews.com/arch.html?121000#2">\r\n  HNN Coverage</a>\r\n', 'Summarized', 20001210114006, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (127, 'Subterranean Homesick Country', 'Thomas Hunt', '', '<i>Johnny\'s in the basement\r\nMixing up the medicine\r\nI\'m on the pavement\r\nThinking about the government</i>\r\n             - Bob Dylan, </pre><a href="http://orad.dent.kyushu-\r\nu.ac.jp/dylan/subterre.html">Subterranean Homesick Blues</a>/\r\n<a href="mp3/Bob_Dylan-Subterranean_Homesick_Blues.mp3">Mp3</a><pre class="normal">\r\n\r\nAs I sit here listening to Bob Dylan I realize how awful things have \r\nbecome in America.  The Supreme Court recently decided the fate of the \r\nPresidential Election.  They decided not to count the votes and let the \r\nson of the former President become King. This is a sad time for America.  \r\nFor over 200 year now, we have been a democracy.  Now we become a \r\nmonarchy.  It\'s amazing to think how much the Supreme Court failed the \r\npeople today.  They voted strictly on party lines and against the will of \r\nthe populace.  The people are beginning to turn their back on the \r\nelectoral system.  There is no more reason to vote.  It was difficult \r\nbefore to think that your one vote mattered, but that question has been \r\nclearly answered today.\r\n\r\n<i>Keep a clean nose\r\nWatch the plain clothes\r\nYou don\'t need a weather man\r\nTo know which way the wind blows</i>\r\n\r\nJefferson.  Lincoln.  Washington.  Three men who won elections and lost \r\nall that they stood for today.  \r\n\r\nI believe this election will be a revelation to the interest groups who \r\ncontributed so much money to these two campaigns.  Now you don\'t even have \r\nto buy the candidates, you should just skip directly to buying the \r\nelection.  Perhaps America should choose her President based on which \r\ninterest group could raise the most money would choose the new President. \r\nAnd perhaps after the election all of the money could be given to NASA, an \r\nagency with a great history that I have been enjoying on the "From the \r\nEarth to the Moon" series and who I believe could use this interest group \r\nmoney for something more important than more commercials for Bush or \r\nGore.  Instead of TV Time, lets buy some moon time.  It\'s been a while \r\nsince we\'ve been up there.  And I think it\'s time to go back.  And we \r\nshould build a colony up there.  That way, at least there would be a few \r\nAmericans to carry on after King W. enters the United Kingdom of America \r\ninto a fatal nuclear war with the People\'s Republic of China (clearly just \r\nas democratic as America, and they probably have much better food).\r\n\r\n<i>Girl by the whirlpool\r\nLookin\' for a new fool\r\nDon\'t follow leaders\r\nWatch the parkin\' meters</i>\r\n\r\nWe\'ve found the new fool.  Every Republican who celebrates W.\'s great \r\nvictory in the Presidential election.  Every member of the party that \r\nusurps the sacred name "Republic" and dares to say that we should not \r\ncount every vote.  Every member of the party who says: All elections \r\nshould be decided by machine count.  \r\n\r\nGod knows the founding fathers envisioned machines deciding the fate of \r\nour elections.  That\'s why they counted the votes by hand in the months \r\nfollowing the election.  And we would have continued their tradition if it \r\nwasn\'t for the 20th amendment.\r\n\r\n<i>Better jump down a manhole\r\nLight yourself a candle\r\nDon\'t wear sandals\r\nTry to avoid the scandals\r\nDon\'t wanna be a bum\r\nYou better chew gum\r\nThe pump don\'t work\r\n\'Cause the vandals took the handles</i>\r\n\r\n\r\nThe end is here.  I hope you have lots of guns, water and supplies, \r\nbecause the United States of America is floundering and with the fall of \r\nthe Great American Empire, so falls the world.\r\n\r\n\r\n', '', 20001212232937, 'normal', '');
