INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (198, 'A break in the case!', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'In a shocking announcement today, Ryan Endeen admitted that he and his \r\nassassins were responsible for Ryan\'s death.\r\n\r\n"Yeah, I did it, so what" said Ryan Endeen as he calmly smoked a \r\ncigarette.  Mr. Endeen, who did not seem to be broken up about Ryan\'s \r\ndeath agreed to an interview with Thunt.net.\r\n\r\nThunt.net: Ryan, why did you kill Ryan?\r\n\r\nEndeen: Mainly because we had the same name.  I was sick and tired of \r\nbeing called Endeen.  Do you know how long it\'s been since someone called \r\nme Ryan?  Even the girls I date call me Endeen.  It\'s just getting fucking \r\nold man.\r\n\r\nThunt.net: So it wasn\'t David Sommers contribution of 20 dollars that led \r\nto your homicidal actions?\r\n\r\nEndeen: Well I did take his money if that\'s what you\'re getting at.  \r\nCigarettes are expensive and God knows the money I make at the Hornet \r\nisn\'t enough to pay for my habit.  Especially since I lost 300 this month \r\nto Wagar.  I should have known not to bet on the XFL, the whole fucking \r\nthing is fixed.  Anyway, David wasn\'t the only one who paid, but I didn\'t \r\ndo it for the money.\r\n\r\nThunt.net: Why do women pluck their eyebrows and wear fake eyelashes?\r\n\r\nEndeen: How the hell am I supposed to know?  Shit, I\'m out of cigarettes.  \r\nThis interview is over.\r\n\r\nSince our interview, there has been a campus-wide manhunt for Endeen.   So \r\nfar, all that the efficient campus cops have discovered is three girls in \r\nyellow sundresses, a box of Krispy Kreme donuts and an empty pack of Camel \r\nCigarettes.  Endeen is considered smoking and silly.  Do not attempt to \r\napprehend him and if you do, keep your hands and arms away from his mouth.\r\n', '', 20010322072258, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (199, 'Hilarious Love Letter Found In Street', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'From the Onion:\r\n\r\nYPSILANTI, MI--A pair of Eastern Michigan University students found a love letter \r\nin the street Monday, deeming the sentiment-laden missive "beyond hilarious."\r\n  \r\n"Oh, my God, check it out," said Eastern Michigan junior Trent Meijer, \r\nexcitedly reading the letter to fellow junior Matt Sweeney. "\'You are like a \r\nfeather floating in a sudden \r\nspring shower.\' How friggin\' funny is that?"\r\n', '', 20010324115844, 'net_interest', 'http://www.theonion.com/onion3710/hilarious_love_letter.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (200, 'Ryan Anne not Dead?', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'In a shocking revelation today, Thunt.net reporters have learned that Ryan \r\nAnne Polli is not dead.\r\n\r\nHow do we know she\'s not dead?  Well, simply put, our lead reporter saw \r\nher at school.  He rushed up to her and pinched her on the arm.  She \r\nappeared to be real and by pinching her, he had ensured that she was not \r\ndreaming.  It was all true.  She was alive.  Of course, she could have \r\nbeen a robot, but that\'s another story.\r\n\r\nRegardless of the robot possibilities, this leads to the moral of today\'s \r\nstory: never believe anything you read on Thunt.net.  All of the articles \r\nof this past week have been the lies of a raving madman.  Endeen the \r\nassassin, Ryan drawing pictures of ponies, Sarah taking photos, Andy \r\ndesigning the paper: all lies.  What you are reading right now is a lie.  \r\nOh, shit.  Is this a paradox?  If I\'m lying in a text that constantly \r\nlies, is that a truth?  \r\n\r\nI know this has been a wild roller coaster ride for Ryan\'s friends, \r\nfamilies and enemies.  There have been some factual mistakes here at \r\nThunt.net and for this I apologize.  I would especially like to apologize \r\nfor those (Matt\'s parents) who might have seen the crucifix-masturbating-\r\nchampion comment in the original lie declaring Ryan dead.  That was just \r\nuncalled for, really, what a horrible oversight that was.  The real \r\ncrucifix-masturbating-champion was Linda Blair in the Exorcist, not Ryan.  \r\nThat was my mistake, and my fact checkers promptly informed me the next \r\nday, when it would have been pointless to repair the error.  Also Endeen\'s \r\nlawyers have informed me that he is busy getting cancer from Marlboro \r\nLights not Camels, although the article didn\'t specifically say that he \r\nwas smoking camels, if you read the text carefully, I would like to make \r\nsure that I don\'t botch any of Endeen\'s cigarette endorsement plans.  In \r\naddition, the Animal Rights activists have informed me that if the \r\nVeterinarian from the "Ryan Anne Dead" article attempted to neuter her, he \r\nwould fail.  Ryan would have to be spayed.  Again, I apologize for all of \r\nthe factual mistakes, cause I am really really sorry.\r\n', '', 20010326072716, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (201, 'Thunt.net and Mattbrown.com launch GARBAGE CAM!', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'This is the day you have all been waiting for.  Thunt.net and \r\nMattBrown.com would like to announce GARBAGE CAM!  You can finally spend \r\nhours staring at the dumpster behind our apartment.  As part of this press \r\nrelease, I would like to present to you a message from Thomas Hunt, Co-\r\nFounder of Garbage Cam.\r\n\r\n"Garbage is a serious business at my house. That\'s why we pay extra to \r\nhave the Garbage Patrol TM. The Garbage Patrol makes sure that we are \r\nrecycling by sending men and women (Garbage Patrol is an equal opportunity \r\nemployer) by every day (sometimes twice or three times daily) to check the \r\ndumpster behind our apartment to ensure that we are recycling. They are \r\ndedicated men and women and we at Thunt.net and MattBrown.com want to \r\nensure that word of their glory spreads all over the internet."\r\n</pre>\r\n<center>\r\n<a href="http://thunt.net/garbage.html">\r\n<img src="http://www.mattbrown.com/garbage.jpg" width=200 height=150 alt="Garbage CAM!"></a><br>\r\n<font class="normal">The actual dumpster</font>\r\n<br>\r\n</center>\r\n<pre class="normal">\r\nMore information can be found on the Garbage Cam Website, available online \r\nonly at <a \r\nhref="http://thunt.net/garbage.html">http://thunt.net/garbage.html</a>.\r\n\r\nThanks for reading! And help us learn more about the incredibly \r\nfascinating Garbage Patrol!\r\n', '', 20010327114134, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (202, 'Oh, I\'m No Good With Soap', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'More classic humor from <a href="http://theonion.com">The Onion</a>.  \r\n\r\nA man admits the trouble that he\'s always had understanding \r\nthe concept of soap.', '', 20010328105329, 'net_interest', 'http://www.theonion.com/onion3711/no_good_with_soap.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (203, 'Six Websites involving Thunt', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '\r\n</pre>\r\n<font class=normal>\r\n<br>\r\n1. <a href=\'http://thunt.net\'>Thunt.net</a> - Thunt\'s "online magazine".  \r\nHear his right-wing conservative views and check out his "net interest" \r\n(or cool links to other sites).  Updated Frequently.\r\n<br><br>\r\n2. <a href=\'http://thomashunt.com\'>ThomasHunt.com</a> - A disgusting \r\nattempt to sell Thunt to corporations.  Please note the cleanliness and \r\nlack of the word FUCK.\r\n<br><br>\r\n3. <a href=\'http://gaia.csus.edu/~huntt\'>Thomas Hunt - Lab Instructor</a> -\r\n A website set up by Thunt when he was teaching the lab section of \r\nComputer Science 8.\r\n<br><br>\r\n4. <a href=\'http://www.thuntphotos.com\'>ThuntPhotos.com</a> - A selection \r\nof photographs taken by Thunt while he was in Photo40 (B&W Photography at \r\nCSUS).\r\n<br><br>\r\n5. <a href=\'http://angryteaparty.com\'>AngryTeaParty.com</a> - A site co-\r\nfounded by Thunt.  Featuring the Rants, Reviews and Poetry of a selection \r\nof very talented and very funny authors.  Updated Frequently.\r\n<br><br>\r\n6. <a href=\'http://athenaWD.com\'>AthenaWD.com</a> - Athena Web Design, a \r\nweb design company started by Thunt and Matt Brown.\r\n<br><br>\r\n', '', 20010330132211, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (204, 'A national disgrace', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'A facinating article from <a href=\'http://salon.com\'>Salon.com</a> that \r\nspeaks out about GWB\'s decision to pull out of the Kyoto Protocol.  I \r\nreally can\'t stand that guy.  He said he based his decision on the effects \r\nthat having clean air might have on the economy.  Translation: Businesses \r\ndon\'t want to be clean.  Let\'s give everyone black lung and then sell them \r\ngas masks with a large markup.', '', 20010331124237, 'net_interest', 'http://salon.com/news/feature/2001/03/29/kyoto/index.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (205, 'Sex Tips For Geeks', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Hackers don\'t have to be helpless chum in the dating-game shark pool. We \r\nhave some advantages; with a little understanding of human ethology we can \r\nlearn how to use them effectively.\r\n\r\nSex advice from the king of all geeks, Eric S. Raymond (ESR).', '', 20010401114013, 'net_interest', 'http://tuxedo.org/~esr/writings/sextips/');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (206, 'Henry David Thoreau Quotes', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'A simple site but packed with wisdom.  I have recently finished reading \r\nWalden myself and I find Thoreau to be a man worth studying.<BR><BR>\r\n\r\n\r\nHighlights:\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n"What does education often do? It makes a straight-cut ditch of a free, \r\nmeandering brook." \r\n<BR><BR>\r\n"Aim above morality. Be not simply good, be good for something."\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n"The mass of men lead lives of quiet desperation."', '', 20010402130707, 'net_interest', 'http://www.cp-tel.net/miller/BilLee/quotes/Thoreau.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (207, 'Bereaved? Come Bathe In The Healing Light Of My Cock', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'One of the best <a href="http://theonion.com">Onion</a> articles in recent memory:<BR><BR>\r\n\r\n      Are you bereaved from the loss of a loved one? Are you all alone in \r\nthis world, with nowhere to turn? Are you one of the billions of wounded \r\nsouls who have suffered a deep and unnameable anguish? Well, there is \r\nsomeone out there who understands. Or, to be more precise, something that \r\nunderstands. Something far bigger than you can possibly imagine.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n      You need to know that no matter how low you are feeling, you have a \r\nfriend right now. A friend named My Cock.', '', 20010404180615, 'net_interest', 'http://www.theonion.com/onion3712/healing_light.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (208, 'The French call him "an idiot"', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '<a href="http://salon.com">Salon.com</a> examines the reaction to GWB in Europe.<BR><BR>\r\n\r\n"By simultaneously destabilizing global security in China, Korea, the \r\nMiddle East and Russia, by recklessly abrogating the Kyoto climate change \r\ntreaty, by bullying his allies in Europe and Asia, by pursuing a tax \r\npolicy that will turn America into the most unequal society in modern \r\nhistory, George W. Bush is fully living up to my expectation that he would \r\nbecome the worst U.S. President since Herbert Hoover," writes the [London] \r\nTimes\' Anatole Kaletsky. ', '', 20010406113828, 'net_interest', 'http://salon.com/news/feature/2001/04/06/europe/index.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (209, 'William Gibson on Japan', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk">The Guardian</a> interviews the author of Neuromancer, Mona Lisa Overdrive and \r\nCount Zero, etc.<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nConsider the Mobile Girl, that ubiquitous feature of contemporary Tokyo \r\nstreet life: a schoolgirl busily, constantly messaging on her mobile phone \r\n(which she never uses for voice communication if she can avoid it). The \r\nMobile Girl can convert pad strokes to kanji faster than should be humanly \r\npossible, and rates her standing in her cellular community according to \r\nthe amount of numbers in her phone\'s memory. What is it that the Mobile \r\nGirls are so busily conveying to one another? Probably not much at all: \r\nthe equivalent of a schoolgirl\'s note, passed behind the teacher\'s back. \r\nContent is not the issue here, but rather the speed, the weird unconscious \r\nsurety, with which the schoolgirls of Tokyo took up a secondary feature \r\n(text messaging) of a new version of the cellular telephone, and \r\ngenerated, almost overnight, a micro-culture. ', '', 20010407102204, 'net_interest', 'http://www.observer.co.uk/life/story/0,6903,466391,00.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (210, 'I hate TV', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'A TV Critic breaks down and attempts to quit the idiot box, from <a \r\nhref=\'http://salon.com\'>Salon.com</a>.<br>\r\n<BR>\r\nOh, I don\'t mind watching a good "I Love Lucy" for the 20th time, or an \r\nepisode of "Homicide: Life on the Street" that I missed during its \r\noriginal run. But I hate looking for something new, and that\'s not good \r\nfor a television critic. Nonfiction series leave me cold, and I\'m \r\nreferring to "Frontline" as much as "Temptation Island." (I caught a few \r\nminutes of the PBS documentary "Jazz," but it felt like a better use of my \r\ntime to put on a CD and read the liner notes.) ', '', 20010407114241, 'net_interest', 'http://salon.com/ent/tv/feature/2001/04/07/i_hate_tv/index.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (211, '3 Brief film reviews and Frigidity', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Good Day Thunt-keters.  I\'m awake, well barely anyway.  We had our good \r\nole ACM Game Night last night, or more correctly, last night deep into \r\nthis morning.  I felt lucky that I managed to escape at the reasonable \r\ntime of 1:30 AM, seeing how last game night if I recall correctly I was \r\nthere until 5 or 6 and felt like puking for the next two or three days.  \r\nNot that I feel to great right now, but hell, I\'m alive anyway.  There \r\nweren\'t too many people there but we had some pretty good Counterstrike \r\n(Half-life Add-on) Games.  I\'m not as good as I used to be, but \r\noccasionally I come off with some good kills.  \r\n\r\nIt\'s now 12:10 pm here at the labs.  The temperature is cold because the \r\nair conditioners are on full blast to protect the servers.  My hands are \r\nfreezing, but I type on regardless.  It looked like it might rain again.  \r\nThe weather is eerie.  Beginning of the week I\'m wearing shorts and \r\nshades, end of the week back to jeans and sweatshirts.  \r\n\r\nIt\'s been a slow couple of weeks on Thunt.net since the Ryan\'s Death \r\nfandango.  I have the strange feeling that people might actually be \r\nreading what I\'m writing now and that kind of freaks me out.  I mean if \r\nyou look at the flashbacks of early Thunt.net, mainly I just blew off \r\nsteam and typed randomly to try to combat the pressures of a scholarly \r\ncollege life.  But now I feel that every time I type something it has to \r\nspark controversy or at the least stir up the idiots on the message board \r\nto write something more interesting than  "STUPID: This board sucks ass" \r\nand "Homer: Bor-ing".  Well, I\'m not sure that\'s going to happen this time.\r\n\r\nReasons for the slow week.  Hell I could give you the standard answer that \r\nI had two midterms and a paper due last week, but that doesn\'t really \r\nmatter now does it?  I don\'t think so.  "Sure, I did them and they\'re \r\ndone" he said nonchalantly with senior-itus weighing heavily on his treble-\r\nfree voice.  Damn my hands are freezing.  This typing isn\'t working I’m \r\ngoing to have to cut open some of the computers and use the overheating \r\nprocessors for warmth.  Other reasons: Boredom.  Nothing much is happening \r\nI guess.  The year is winding down.  The semester is coming to a close.\r\n\r\nMovies watched recently (that I\'d never seen before):  \r\n\r\n<B>Glory</B> - I watched Glory for the first time after much ragging from \r\nmy friends Matt and John, the latter being a true-blue civil war buff and \r\nre-enactor.  It was a good war movie.  I enjoyed it, despite it\'s morbid \r\nending, which I understand was historically accurate.  While I feel Ferris \r\nBueler did a good job in his role, I still believe is was miscast because \r\nI just can\'t see him as anything other than Ferris.  The movie was good, \r\nbut it wasn\'t groundbreaking or anything.  For groundbreaking, mind-\r\nblowing shit please see Pierrot le fou, 400 Blows and Soy Cuba.\r\n\r\n<B>The English Patient</B> - I try to avoid tradegy-prone chick flicks, \r\nbut this movie was fucking rad.  I feel fortunate that Matt had it in his \r\nDVD collection and I got to experience it in full widescreen with good \r\nsound.  Truly amazing flick, well deserving of it\'s awards.  Nice visuals, \r\nexcellent pacing, the flashback structure works for once, and the bookends \r\nare gloriously cut together.  (by bookends I mean that the story begins \r\nand ends with the same visuals, most movies and stories try to do this and \r\nvery few succeed to the level that this film did.)  To put this movie in \r\nline with other war movie type dramas, I\'d say better than Saving Private \r\nRyan, but not as impressive as The Thin Red Line (1998).\r\n\r\n<B>The Doors</b> - Why hadn\'t I seen this movie yet?  I don\'t know.  I \r\nsuppose that having Val Klimer and Meg Ryan in it sounded like a lame \r\nbunch of answers, a cut up version of it was constantly on television (see \r\nother movies also constantly on: Ishtar, Chasers, Love Stinks, Short \r\nCircuit).  Also I heard it was bad. But then I heard it was directed by \r\nOliver Stone and I rushed to see it.  Well I didn\'t have to rush or hear \r\nreally, it just arrived in my Oliver Stone 10 pack DVD collection and I \r\nsaid, "hmmm, I guess he directed The Doors".  I\'ve always been a big fan \r\nof Stone\'s work and I can honestly say that I am now a big fan of his film \r\nThe Doors.  The visuals are stunning, Kilmer does an incredible job as \r\nMorrison, better than I ever believed possible for the Red Planet, Ghost \r\nin the Darkness, Top Gun Star.  Meg Ryan was pretty good, very unlike the \r\nmodern bland girl next door bullshit that she does in all of her recent \r\nfilms.  You even get to see a flash of her tit during one of the many sex \r\nscenes in the film.  Morrison and his life pretty much went rolling out of \r\ncontrol and Stone\'s film puts you right in the action and after it all I \r\nfelt pretty wasted despite the fact that I did not do any drugs during the \r\n2 hour and 30 minute masterpiece.  The sound on my Dolby Digital 5.1 DVD \r\nversion was well worth the extra money invested in the disc and the \r\nsurround sound system.  This movie is rad, it\'s a total trip, just make \r\nsure you\'re ready for the ride.  Other good rock movies: Stop Making Sense \r\n(Jonathon Demme\'s Talking Heads Live Concert Film), Gimme Shelter (Rolling \r\nStones at Altamont, you can see the point where the peace and love stopped \r\nand the 70s began.  They even run it in slow mo with Mick looking on and \r\nSympathy for the Devil playing), and of course Spinal Tap (The best \r\nrocumentary of them all.  Even if you didn\'t like Tap\'s early work, you\'ll \r\nlove their film.)\r\n\r\nI think I\'ve said enough.  I don\'t know if anyone will read to this point \r\nof the article.  If you do, please post your thoughts about the new \r\nslashdot-like weblog Thunt.net.  By shifting the front page focus from \r\narticles to a mix of articles and net interest I feel I\'ve added some \r\ninteresting stuff to Thunt.net, what do you think?  Post on the message \r\nboard or email me at <a href=mailto:thunt@thunt.net>thunt@thunt.net</a>.  \r\n', '', 20010407124132, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (212, 'Odyssey probe blasts off for Mars', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '<a href="http://cnn.com">Cnn.com</a> reports:<br>\r\n<br>\r\n(CNN) -- Beginning a new chapter in Mars exploration, NASA on Saturday \r\nlaunched a powerful new orbiter to scour the Red Planet for evidence of \r\nunderground water and geologic hot spots. ', '', 20010408101428, 'net_interest', 'http://www.cnn.com/2001/TECH/space/04/07/mars.odyssey/index.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (213, 'Death to the Minotaur', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '<a href="http://salon.com">Salon.com</a> reports on the purchase of \r\nWizards of the Coast by Hasbro.<br>\r\n', '', 20010408101707, 'net_interest', 'http://www.salon.com/tech/feature/2001/03/23/wizards/index.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (214, 'Shakespeare Insult Generator', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'You starvelling, you eel-skin, you dried neat\'s-tongue, you bull\'s-pizzle, \r\nyou stock-fish--O for breath to utter what is like thee!-you tailor\'s-\r\nyard, you sheath, you bow-case, you vile standing tuck! \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nTaken from: Henry IV, part I \r\n\r\n', '', 20010408111744, 'net_interest', 'http://www.pangloss.com/seidel/Shaker/index.html?');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (215, 'Wake UP! starring Andy Duong', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Thunt.net is proud to present: Wake UP!,  A film starring Andy Duong.  The \r\nfilm revolves around Andy Duong, a man who cannot wake up.  It is a life \r\nand death situation.  If he does not wake up a bomb will go off killing a \r\ngirl from Chico that he met once and later did fliers for.  The girl is \r\nhot.  The bomb is real.  The fliers looked nice.  But really matters here \r\nis the girl\'s ass.  What an ass.  Her face is attached to her ass.  \r\nAnyway, now we\'re really spoiling the plot for you.  Just click below and \r\nwatch the movie.  Don\'t forget to have <a \r\nhref=http://www.quicktime.com>QuickTime</a> installed.  Thanks for \r\nwatching!\r\n<center><a href=http://thunt.net/video/wakeup_low.mov>\r\nClick here to watch Wake UP!</a></center>\r\n\r\nThe Critics Agree:\r\n\r\n"You snooze you loose" – Joe \r\n\r\n"He who hesitates, masturbates" – Roger Ebert\r\n\r\n"And he [Andy] wasn\'t even wasted last night." – Matt Brown\r\n\r\n"Why are you asking me?  I\'m dead!" – Gene Siskel\r\n\r\n"Watch out Thunt.  Endeen, you\'re weird" – Andy Duong\r\n', '', 20010414182933, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (216, 'ASI: The Slates', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Welcome to Thunt.net\'s ASI Election 2001 Coverage.  We\'re going to need a \r\ncatchy name for this coverage, so I’ll be holding a contest on the message \r\nboard.  Please post any ideas you might have and maybe you’ll be the lucky \r\nwinner.  Current ideas: Who Gives a Shit? 2001 (WGS-2001), Who the fuck \r\ncares? 2001 (WFC-2001), or perhaps A Stupid Ignorant Frat Asshole Guy \r\nSucceeds in winning the presidency  (ASI-FAGS).  The latter being the \r\ncurrent front-runner although I\'d prefer a one-word title similar to \r\nComedy Central\'s Peabody winning “Indecision 2000”.\r\n\r\nI\'d like to begin my coverage by getting you up to date on the slates.  \r\nThere seem to be three slates running for election this year.  To inform\r\n anyone who is unfamiliar with the basic idea of slates, they assume that the \r\nvoters are uninformed idiots and will say hmmmmm, Jason Davis is a good \r\ncandidate, so after I vote for him, I\'ll vote for all of his frat buddies \r\non the Fuck Students First slate.  It\'s a moronic idea, but around this \r\nschool what do you expect.  The slates are also a neat way to mask campaign \r\nspending, and funnel illegal (mommy & daddies) money into your campaign.\r\n\r\n<B>Support US</B> – A stupid name you say?  We have just begun our \r\nelection coverage.  Expect more stupidity from the rag-tag bunch of morons \r\nrunning for office this year.  The Support US slate can clearly be \r\nidentified as the slate of weirdoes, freaks and ASI outsiders.  Led by \r\nHans something or other, they hope to capture the freak vote and turn the \r\ncampus into a freak paradise.  Don\'t expect them to win though, despite \r\nthe large population of freaks and weirdoes on this campus, the honest \r\ntruth is freaks don’t vote.  The people who vote are the fraternities and \r\nsororities because they herd their members to the voting booths like \r\nlambs to the slaughter (for similar policies see the religious right, note \r\nhow many polling places are churches and how few are at chemistry labs).  \r\nI expect these tattooed and pierced freaks to go back down from where they \r\ncame from and never be heard from again.  However to remain impartial and \r\nhonest to you my viewing public, I would like to state for the record that \r\nI know two of these freaks: Ryan Murphy who is running for Director of \r\nBusiness Administration and Alin Wakefield who is running for the Union \r\nBoard of Directors.  Despite my familiarity with these candidates, I do \r\nsupport and hope that they win their selective offices.\r\n\r\n<B>Vision</B> - As my good friend Brendan mentioned in his column a few \r\nweeks ago Vision is the party of Big Brother.  Their signs all feature a \r\nhideously frightening V embedded in an all knowing all seeing eye.  \r\nFrankly I’m terrified that some idiot thought that these signs and slogans \r\nwas a good idea.  I know no one reads books anymore but there was a fairly \r\npopular novel written by George Orwell named 1984, in which Big Brother \r\ncontrolled the common stupid people and watched their every move using \r\nviewscreens and a complex system of thought police.  The novel also \r\nfeatured Victory brand cigarettes, among other victory brand \r\nproducts.  The V in victory is prominently featured in the movie by the \r\nsame name, an excellent adaptation, although typically the book remains \r\nsuperior.  The idiots who selected this logo should not be allowed to run \r\na cruise ship let alone this campus.  Their slate consists of mainly non-\r\nfrat infidels who have been serving in ASI due to the fluke election of \r\nArturo Pimmentale last semester.  Again, without the frat vote this slate \r\nwill sink, and with this stupid vision shit I hope they never rise again. \r\n\r\nDOWN WITH BIG BROTHER.\r\nDOWN WITH BIG BROTHER.\r\nDOWN WITH BIG BROTHER.\r\nDOWN WITH BIG BROTHER.\r\nDOWN WITH BIG BROTHER.\r\nDOWN WITH BIG BROTHER.\r\nDOWN WITH BIG BROTHER.\r\n\r\n<B>Students First</B> - The last slate to enter the campaign, and the \r\nfirst in lame tired slogans is the Students First slate.  This is the \r\nfavorite, and as I always bet on the biggest evil, I have to say that we \r\nat Thunt.net expect a near sweep from this hackneyed campaign.  Ably \r\nhelmed by former ASI President Jason Bryant and BMW owner (thank you mommy \r\nand daddy) this slate is filled with ASI insiders and should be able to \r\nmonopolize the all important fraternity and sorority vote.  Highlights of \r\nthis slate include the Gladiator-esque Rugby Player Joe Devlin running for \r\nPresident and the Politician\'s Politician David Sommers running for \r\nExecutive Vice President.  As with the Support US slate, expect Thunt.net \r\nto support Mr. Sommers in his quest for glory, but again don\'t expect the \r\nsatire to be light.  Just because he used to be Editor-In-Chief of the \r\nState Whore doesn’t mean that Thunt.net will relax our coverage of him.  \r\nAlthough our rumor-hounds at the Whore have informed us that the Whore \r\nwill be supporting him without any disclaimer expressing their obvious \r\nbias.  Expect morals and ethics here on Thunt.net. Sommers has aligned \r\nhimself with the frats and sorority fiends and for this he will have his \r\nvictory, but Thunt.net will have its say.\r\n\r\nThis is now the end of the first part of Thunt.net\'s election coverage: \r\nThe Slates.  Please note that here at Thunt.net we are not interested in \r\nfact checking or politically correctness.  The candidates are public \r\nfigures by their desire for office and hence leave themselves open to \r\nsatire as stated by the Supreme Court Decision: Hustler Magazine, Inc. v. \r\nFalwell, 485 U.S. 46, 108 S.Ct. 876, 99 L.Ed.2d. 41 (1988).  In which a \r\n<B>unanimous</B> Supreme Court held that satire has played a prominent \r\nrole in public and political debate and that the Court could see no \r\nstandard to distinguish among types of parodies that would not harm public \r\ndiscourse, which would be poorer without such satire.  Thanks for reading!\r\n', '', 20010416110952, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (217, 'Steven Bushemi stabbed in the face', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'WILMINGTON, N.C. (Reuters) - Actor Steve Buscemi suffered stab wounds to \r\nthe throat and head on Thursday after getting involved in a bar fight that \r\nled to the arrest of actor Vince Vaughn and screenwriter Scott Rosenberg.', '', 20010416155509, 'net_interest', 'http://dailynews.yahoo.com/h/nm/20010414/en/people-buscemi_1.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (218, 'Punk rock icon Joey Ramone dies', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'NEW YORK (April 16, 2001 9:45 a.m. EDT) - Singer Joey Ramone, the punk \r\nrock icon whose raucous style melded with the Ramones\' three-chord thrash \r\nto launch an explosion of bands like the Clash and the Sex Pistols, died \r\nSunday at age 49.', '', 20010416155842, 'net_interest', 'http://www.nando.net/24hour/sacbee/entertainment/story/0,2208,500473737-500726720-504102585-0,00.htm');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (219, 'Ted Turner suicidal after marital, business problems, magazine reports', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'NEW YORK (April 16, 2001 12:00 p.m. EDT http://www.nandotimes.com) - CNN \r\nfounder Ted Turner was suicidal after the breakup of his marriage to Jane \r\nFonda and losing control of Turner Broadcasting in the reorganization of \r\nAOL Time Warner, according to The New Yorker magazine. <BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nThunt.net Comments: Ha HA.', '', 20010416160034, 'net_interest', 'http://www.nando.net/24hour/sacbee/entertainment/story/0,2208,500473834-500726881-504106403-0,00.htm');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (220, 'The overthrow of the Whore', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'I would like to begin by saying that from what I hear there is a highly \r\nskilled group of individuals and Andy running for Editor-in-chief this \r\nyear.  I thought I would take some time out from my exciting ASI Election \r\ncoverage to identify some of the brave fools who desire to become the \r\nEditor-in-chief of the State Whore.\r\n\r\n<B>Tony</B> - Tony is a great guy and I think he would do a swell job as \r\nEIC.  Tony has a great deal of experience and is really a hard worker.  I \r\nbelieve the paper would be in capable hands with Tony at the helm.\r\n\r\n<B>Brendan</B> - Brendan cannot write 500 words on a single subject in his \r\ncolumn but he has a great sense of humor and actually believes that he is \r\nfunny.  Brendan has some good ideas for the paper and I think he would \r\nmake a great EIC.\r\n\r\n<B>Andrea</B> - Damn Andrea is hot.  And she seems frightfully intelligent \r\ntoo.  Although I think Brendan and Tony have to be the favorites in this \r\nelection, I think that Andrea has a good outside chance of becoming EIC.  \r\nAlthough I do not feel that being Copy Editor correlates much to being \r\nEIC, I think Andrea could wow the board at the interview and achieve a \r\nsurprise victory.\r\n\r\n<B>Andy</B> - Andy is running for EIC.  Yes the Andy that spells his name \r\nANDY! And put fart, poop and dick jokes in the newspaper.  Andy is a \r\nbrilliant designer but I think he lacks the restraint to safely (lawsuit \r\nand protest free) manage the paper.  Although I did help him write his \r\ncover letter, so I am sure they will give him an interview but I cannot \r\nsee the board deciding on Andy.  It would be awesome if he won, but as a \r\nwise gambler, that\'s not where I\'d put my money.\r\n\r\nFor those who are interested in setting up a pool, or laying a wager on \r\nthe race, I\'ve set up an odds projection:\r\n\r\n<U>Odds</U>\r\n - Tony 1:2\r\n - Brendan 1:2\r\n - Andrea 1:5\r\n - Andy 1:12\r\n\r\n\r\n', '', 20010417172602, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (221, 'Thunt.net announces EIC endorsement', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'We at Thunt.net are proud to announce our endorsement of Andrew Duong for \r\nEditor-in-chief of the State Whore.  Mr. Duong has wowed our board with \r\nhis unreadable Mr. T marketing campaign, successful stomping of Ryan \r\nEndeen and remarkable skateboarding abilities, we can think of no better \r\nman or woman to be Editor-in-chief. \r\n\r\n<center><a href=http://thunt.net/images/andy_skateboarding.jpg><img \r\nsrc=http://thunt.net/images/andy_skateboarding.jpg width=400>\r\nEditor-in-Chief, Andrew Duong</a>\r\n</center>\r\n', '', 20010418103750, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (222, 'ASI: The Dirt', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Ok, since this is Thunt.net, not the New York Times, we allow ourselves \r\nfrom time to time to print rumors.  This is one of those times...\r\n\r\n<B>Sommer\'s flight from Support US</B> - Thunt.net sources tell us that \r\noriginally Sommers was working for the Support US? slate as their campaign \r\nmanager.  Well, apparently Mr. Sommers felt that they weren\'t allowing him \r\nto do as much as he wanted to, so he jumped ship and took two or three of \r\ntheir candidates with him.  Sommers is now running for VP of University \r\nAffairs on the "StudentsFirst?" slate, starring Joe Devlin.  Obviously bad \r\nnews for the pierced freak Hans because with Jason "BMW" Bryant, \r\nJoe "Gladiator" Devlin and David "hero of the shield law" Sommers working \r\ntogether, they form an unholy alliance that will either bring on the \r\napocalypse or support the flaming death and destruction of the Support US? \r\ncampaign.\r\n\r\n\r\n<B>Jason Bryant is a Choad</B> - Readers of the ever popular Thunt.net \r\nmessage board know full well that someone claiming to be Jason Bryant \r\nposted to the board (Apr 18, 2001 at 12:32 am).  A second party \r\nnamed "Jason Bryant\'s a fucking idiot" replied the next day at 11:23 am.  \r\nI have two questions about these interesting posts.  First question, is \r\nthis really Jason Bryant posting?  Let\'s examine the message.  It is \r\ncampy, lame, mildly complimentary to Thunt.net and ends with a campaign \r\nannouncement, so from what we know about Jason Bryant, that\'s all up to \r\ncode.  But there is a minor discrepancy.  What would Jason Bryant be doing \r\nup at 12:30 at night reading the Thunt.net message board?  While I do \r\nadmit that from time to time I myself keep a strange and depraved sleeping \r\nschedule that few normal people will ever try and few will ever comprehend \r\n(going to bed at 4am and sleeping until noon).  But is Bryant a freak of \r\nsimilar colors or are we merely dealing with a well-disguised imposter?  A \r\ndifficult question for a difficult age.  Second question, is Jason Bryant \r\na Choad?  If he\'s posting to the message board at 12:30 am, that proves \r\nthat he has less of a life than we all thought and those two girls getting \r\nout of his beamer with him at Albertson\'s must have been hired hands, and \r\nnot hired to do the kind of work you\'d like those girls to do, ho ho.  But \r\nhaving no life is different than being a choad (props go to the poster for \r\nchoosing such an excellent and indeed rare word to insult our current ASI \r\nPresident.  I myself haven\'t seen the word choad used since I saw Trey \r\nParker\'s Orgazmo in the no defunct Landmark/Sacramento Inn theater a few \r\nyears ago.)  Regardless of the rarity and brilliance of the insult, we are \r\nstill left with the question: Bryant? Choad?  I for one say yes.  Bryant \r\nhas handled the presidency poorly since he was elected and they threw him \r\nin the fountain election night.  I\'ve heard nothing but horror stories \r\nabout his strange and deluded administration since that fateful night.  I \r\nheard he tried to bribe and coerce the State Whore into doing his bidding \r\nand giving him positive press coverage, but failed due to the impeccable \r\nintegrity of the News Editor who refused to do her vicious handiwork.  \r\nAdditionally the whole Child Care scandal reeks of choadadom.  Closing the \r\nChild Center to balance the budget, putting the little children out on the \r\nstreet without even a Where\'s Waldo book to keep them company.  \r\nAtrocious!  Not to say that I haven\'t had the same idea myself about a \r\nhundred times, seeing as how I have no children to send to that useless \r\nChild Center and I think it\'s a god damned waste of student tax payers \r\nmoney.  But I especially abhor Bryant\'s actions because he went at the \r\nglorious project like a pussy.  He cried to anyone that would listen, "Boo \r\nhooo, mismanagement of ASI\'s millions is going to force us to cut the \r\nchild center", "think about the children" and other such political \r\nnonsense.  Well, the campus (the whiney people with children, mainly) \r\nunited against Bryant\'s plan and somehow they saved the Child Center, \r\nbecause every day when I walk by there I expect it will have been \r\ndestroyed with a wrecking ball to add more parking to our already impacted \r\ncampus, but every day there are little children running and playing \r\ntotally oblivious of Jason Bryant, the great destroyer\'s vicious designs \r\non their playground space.  Jason Bryant is indeed a Choad and no doubt \r\nhe\'ll go far.\r\n\r\n\r\n', '', 20010419085056, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (223, 'Shock and surprise in EIC Selection', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Shock and surprise fill the air today in the wake of the Hornet \r\nElections.  The Hornet has chosen a "surprise" candidate (meaning someone \r\nwho I don\'t know personally).  Her name is Layla Boom or something like \r\nthat.  Apparently she assisted cult leader Matt Wagar and his News Section \r\nin this last year and based upon a stellar interview and her journalism \r\nclasses with Mike "married to Silvia, pity me" Fitzgerald has led her to \r\nvictory.  \r\n\r\nThe shock has been easy to take for those of us who don\'t care, but some \r\npeople had their entire future riding on this election and for them, \r\ndefeat is hard to take.  Wonnacott had to cancel his victory party and \r\ncelebrate a hideous trouncing.  anDy! took to bed at the hour of eight o \r\nclock after having to wake up early at nine am for the interview.  Tony no \r\ndoubt smashed some shit, complained loudly to the elder Fitz and is \r\nprobably going to quit the paper and work at the Sacbee, not a bad \r\ndecision if you ask me.  Andrea probably took the decision with a grain of \r\nsalt and felt no hatred or envy for the winner.  Dina no doubt hopes that \r\nthis new EIC will distract people from making fun of her and her Louis-\r\nPhilippe/Charles X-like reign of foolishness and idiocy but its not going \r\nto happen.  Like Chernobyl and Three-Mile-Island, when you make a mistake \r\nthis big, it takes years for the radiation to dissipate.  \r\n\r\nAs to the new EIC, we wish her the best of luck and hope that someday \r\nstudents will be able to read the State Hornet without being embarrassed \r\nby the poor quality of articles and lack of journalistic integrity.  We at \r\nThunt.net hope for that day, but again we don\'t really care.  Graduation \r\nlooms on the horizon for our brave hero and thoughts turn to the world \r\nafter our first college degree.  What level of insane debauchery will we \r\nbe involved in this time next year, I don\'t know, but that miserable \r\nexcuse of a paper will not be on our mind.\r\n\r\nAs to the losers, I give my most heartfelt condolences.  In every race, \r\nthere has to be a winner and many losers, but what\'s important is that you \r\ntried.  What\'s important is that the EIC from Santa Cruz lost as well.  \r\nWhat\'s important is that George-ogre also failed.  With losers like that \r\nyou\'re in good company, company to be enjoyed and mocked.  \r\n', '', 20010421102930, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (224, 'Choosing a College', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '<a href="http://www.theonion.com">The Onion</a> helps you make the \r\nimportant decisions in your life, based upon such qualifications as:<br>\r\n<BR>\r\nThe Armed Forces Scholarship Program is a great way to earn a considerable \r\namount of money toward college, but it has a small "joining the goddamn \r\narmy" downside. <BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nWhen consulting Playboy\'s annual party-school rankings, be sure to look \r\nclosely at the students-per-hot-tub ratio. <BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nIf you are having a hard time deciding between Princeton and Yale, cry me \r\na fucking river, Fauntleroy. ', '', 20010421103706, 'net_interest', 'http://www.theonion.com/onion3714/choosing_a_college_tips.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (225, 'Song About Heroin Used To Advertise Bank', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '"We needed something that conveyed Metrobank\'s global financial presence, \r\nhigh-powered transaction capabilities, and respected position throughout \r\nthe business community," said Jared Morris, president of Ogilvy & Mather, \r\nthe spot\'s creator. "So, we thought, what better way than to call to mind \r\npunk forefather Iggy Pop\'s long, terrifying struggle with a near-fatal \r\nheroin habit?"', '', 20010421103820, 'net_interest', 'http://www.theonion.com/onion3714/song_about_heroin.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (226, 'The company of men', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Having read all three of Palahniuk\'s books, I can tell you his work is \r\ninteresting enough for this convention dedicated him to be a positive use \r\nof time.  Reading the article from <a \r\nhref="http://salon.com">Salon.com</a> further proves this conclusion...\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n"Admirers of "Fight Club" author Chuck Palahniuk convene to discuss art, \r\nlife, masculine pain and why groin kicks are very, very popular."', '', 20010421104956, 'net_interest', 'http://salon.com/books/feature/2001/04/20/palahniuk/index.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (227, 'Quickies from Salon.com', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '<B>Satirists beware: The FBI is after you:</B> The feds chase small time \r\nweb satirists, fucking bastards.<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<B>Kozmo.com finally has a bright idea:</B> The now defunct dotcom uses a \r\nbait and switch to give customers late fees on rentals, just like \r\nblockbuster.<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<B>Lessons in rock from Joey Ramone:</B> A touching piece detailing what \r\nJoey was listening to on his deathbed.<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<B>Microsoft declares war on MP3:</B> Microsoft plans to engineer Windows \r\nXP so that when you compress Mp3s on it, it will degrade the quality, so \r\nthat people will use WMA (windows media player format).  Unbelievable.\r\n', '', 20010421105757, 'net_interest', 'http://salon.com/tech/inbox/index.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (228, 'Lore: I  think', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Brilliant work from the <a href="http://brunching.com">Brunching \r\nShuttlecocks</a>.  About time someone did a comic about Altoids.  Mmmmm, \r\nAltoids....', '', 20010421111130, 'net_interest', 'http://brunching.com/features/loreithink.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (229, 'Hornet EIC Selection: ALL FUCKED UP!', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'The fix is in.  Or it was in, again.  I swear, this pub-board thing is one \r\ndamned well organized group of scam artists.  First, they fuck over \r\nSmoking Boy last year, and now they fuck over Brendan.  Now I want you to \r\nkeep in mind that this is only rumor, but here is the scoop:  \r\n\r\nMr. J. Nature, Mel Gibson, Smoking Boy, News Man and some other people are \r\nunited in their support for Brendan Wonnacott.  That means he should be \r\ncelebrating right now.  But wait, Michael J. Fox and Dinaaaa decide that \r\nhe\'s not the man for the job and somehow lead a charge that tips the pub \r\nboard and they decide that Brendan, who is best for the job would be best \r\nas Managing Editor and Layla Bomb should be Editor-in-Thief. \r\n\r\nI would just like to ask you all to reflect on this and think about how \r\ntotally fucked up this is.  I mean it was bad enough when Smoking Boy was \r\nrobbed of EIC, but for it to happen twice in a row, it\'s downright \r\ndespicable.  How is this publication board representative of the student \r\nbody if two of its members can railroad all of the other members into \r\nmaking a decision?  What is the value of a student voice if it is \r\nsilenced?  What should Laylee Bomb, new Editor-in-Thief do to set this \r\nright.  I for one think that she should step down and be managing editor.  \r\nIt would be a noble gesture that would prove that she is a team player and \r\nhas the best interests of the paper in mind.  I ask you, Ms. Bomb to step \r\ndown.  Do the right thing.  \r\n', '', 20010423001421, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (230, 'U-Turn Review', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'It\'s amazing how you\'ll be thinking about something, and then it\'s on the \r\nInternet, bam!  I was watching U-Turn thinking about a similar movie I had \r\nseen, I wracked my brain for days, and then I realized it was Red Rock \r\nWest.  I first recalled it because Dennis Hopper was the bad guy, and he\'s \r\ndamned memorable.  But as I was walking to school today, I remembered the \r\nname: Red Rock West.  Then it hit me that Nick Cage and Laura Flynn Boyle \r\nwere in it.  I went at it on a round about way, remembering first that I \r\nthought it resembled a David Lynch film, which led me to Cage (Wild at \r\nHeart) and Boyle (Twin Peaks).  Once I had reconstructed it I went out to \r\nthe net to read some reviews, and BAM! First review I come across, made \r\nthe same links to Red Rock West that I did.  Amazing level of coincidence.', '', 20010423084854, 'net_interest', 'http://www.film.com/film-review/1997/9610/109/default-review.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (231, 'Thunt votes in ASI Election!', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Yup.  I voted like a "good" citizen.  I voted for Students First, because \r\nI know Sommers, and I think they\'re going to win.  They had the least \r\nflashiest campaign, no webpage, and didn\'t try to bribe me with donuts.  \r\nI like that in a candidate (note for andy, candid...ate).  Also I had no \r\nchoice but to vote for their candidate for arts and letters because I \r\ndidn\'t know any of the other candidates and she was hot.  It\'s horrible to \r\nthink how many important decisions in this country are made by men who are \r\ncompletely motivated by hot women.  Oh well, enough lady macbeth talk for \r\none day.  If you\'re interested, I documented my voting experience (ala \r\nElection), at <a href=http://thunt.net/photo>http://thunt.net/photo</a>. \r\n \r\nPhotos by Josh Pryor, Camera by Matt Brown, Thumbnail Script by Doug \r\nCoker, Thunt\'s Wardrobe was provided by Thunt, inspired by Hunter S. \r\nThompson.  Thanks for reading!', '', 20010425133030, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (232, 'David defeats Goliath or The Goliath defeats David', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'As I walked along the campus, this bright sunny day, I know that what I \r\nread on the message board was true.  David Sommers and his Students First \r\nslate were brutally defeated by the grass roots donut-pushing Vision \r\nslate.  The ASI-tocracy of Jason Bryant has been defeated by the upstart \r\nvision-ers led by Arturo Pimentale.\r\n\r\nHow was I able to confirm this?  It was simple, all over campus the \r\nStudents First Billboards are still up while the Vision and even the \r\nSupportUS signs have been taken down.  These billboards remain standing \r\nlike corpses littering the field after a mighty battle.  It is clear that \r\nStudents First has lost because there is no one left alive to bury their \r\ndead.  The victors of a war always bury their own first, leaving their \r\nenemies to rot on the field and be picked apart by carrion.  \r\n\r\nWhy did Students First finish last?  Blame could easily drift right to the \r\ntop.  Perhaps Sommers should have stayed with the pierced freaks of \r\nSupportUS and they might have triumphed over the Orwellian Vision.  \r\nPerhaps the lack of donuts, fancy fliers and a website brought down the \r\ngolden dreams of Students First.  But once should not place all of the \r\nblame on the David the Brave.  Other members of the slate played a share \r\nin this colossal defeat.  Perhaps it is the fault of Champagne from Omega \r\nChi Alpha for not placing candid (yes candid)  photos of herself on the \r\nStudents First signs and fliers.  Maybe all they would have had to do was \r\nchange her name to Champagne "I\'m Hot!" Turismo.  Nah, it probably would \r\nhave taken more than that.  Sometimes it seems like they were doomed from \r\nthe start.  Perhaps David Sommers is just a bad luck charm. \r\n\r\nThis is no doubt a sad time for the perennially unlucky would-be dictator \r\nChairman Sommers.  He\'s just lost a major election and from what I can \r\ntell, his slate will have little or no power in the new Government (now \r\nwith Vision[tm]).  Additionally his chosen one for EIC: Mr. WannaCock?  \r\nwas hideously robbed by the nonentity Ms. Bomb.\r\n\r\nWhat\'s next for David Sommers?  What could go wrong now?  We here at \r\nThunt.net have fired up the old BS-2000 and we are about to take you on an \r\naction packed tour through: The Future of Daaaaaviiiiiddddd \r\nSommmmmmerssssssss………\r\n\r\n<B>Drunken Disaster</B> - In a drunken post-defeat stupor, David discovers \r\nthat he has slept with a MAN!  For the record, it was a man dressed as a \r\nwoman, but the event contributed in no small way to the everlasting \r\nsnowball effect that sent his political career spiraling out of control.  \r\nThe matter is made worse when the man-woman who calls himself Dino went on \r\ntelevision in a dirty sweatshirt and told Fox40 news that her and Sommers \r\nhad a night of "sexual passion" and that it should be considered "news".\r\n\r\n<B>Back to the Hornet!</b> - Sommers returns to the Hornet as a lowly news \r\nreporter.  He is assigned to write the Police Log, a degrading job that \r\ndoesn\'t even require writing, you simply have to copy down the information \r\nfrom the log at police headquarters.  Seeing it as a stupid and pointless \r\nduty that a trained monkey could do, Sommers began to photocopy the police \r\nlog and place it in the paper verbatim.  His editor liked the photocopies \r\nfor their edgy real-life quality and nominated for EIC again.  \r\nUnfortunately the trained monkey the trained monkey he hired to do all the \r\nphotocopying ran against him and won.  The monkey was supported by two \r\npowerful idiots: Teen Wolf and Teen Wolf Too.\r\n\r\nThe BS-2000 is starting to fail as class draws neigh.  Our Nobel-prize \r\nwinning hero Thunt must now rush to class, but fear not gentle souls, \r\nThunt will return soon with hard-hitting satire and a sense of humor that \r\nis borderline: sick, perverse and twisted.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '', 20010426114018, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (234, 'Thunt.net Poll: Wrap-Up', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'And now, a brief recap of the results of the past Thunt.net Polls.\r\n\r\n“Should Thunt cover the ASI Elections?”\r\n\r\n	<B>Yes: 59%</B>\r\n	No: 14%\r\n	What Elections? 27%\r\n\r\n	Total Votes: 22\r\n\r\nClearly the people wondered what elections and decided that what the hell, \r\nThunt should cover em, anyway.  Why the hell not.\r\n\r\n“What Slate has the stupidest name/slogan?”\r\n\r\n	Support US: 28%\r\n	Vision: 33%\r\n	<B>Students First: 39%</B>\r\n\r\n	Total Votes: 18\r\n\r\nIt’s clear that the people of Thunt.net sure know how to pick a looser.  \r\nStudents First was voted worst slogan and consequently they got their \r\nasses beat in the elections.  Better luck next time Dave.\r\n\r\n“Under the leadership of Ms. Boom will the paper be:”\r\n\r\n	Better: 41%\r\n	Worse: 9%\r\n	<B>Dinaaaaaaa: 50%</B>\r\n\r\n	Total Votes: 22\r\n\r\nIt’s great when the funny answer wins.  It shows the pointlessness of the \r\nquestion.  Of course the paper will be better, how could it be worse?\r\n\r\n“What’s your favorite drug?”\r\n\r\n	Oregano: 20%\r\n	<B>Cheap Malt Liquor: 35%</B>\r\n	<B>Red Bull: 35%</B>\r\n	Peyote: 10%\r\n\r\n	Total Votes: 20\r\n\r\nA tight race.  Let’s face it, Red Bull does have that super punch, but \r\nmalt liquor has that ghetto flava.  How can one be forced to choose one \r\nover the other.  I think they should be sold side by side in convenience \r\nstores everywhere, and perhaps in an convenient two-pack.\r\n\r\n“Dina’s next job will be at:”\r\n\r\n	Krispy Kreme: 5%\r\n	McDonald’s: 0%\r\n	Taco Bell: 15%\r\n	HP: 5%\r\n	<B>the corner of 3rd & G: 75%</B>\r\n\r\n	Total Votes: 20\r\n\r\nIt’s sad to see that almost all of Thunt.net feels that Dina would be \r\nbetter suited to the street life of a hooker than the high tech atmosphere \r\nof a Taco Bell.  As the creator of the poll it would be wrong for me to \r\ntell you that I too, voted for “the corner of 3rd & G”.  But I comfort \r\nmyself by the fact that I at least put HP on the list.  I mean, damn, I’m \r\na fine humanitarian for that show of kindness.\r\n\r\nThis is the end of poll wrap-up.  Expect another one someday.  Now \r\navailable in strawberry and cherry flavors, but not grape.\r\n', '', 20010501142330, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (235, 'A new column for Thunt.net', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'by demand of Matt Wagar.\r\n\r\n\r\nSix.  Six is the number, the thought that runs through my mind on this \r\ndark windy night.  Six is the number of assignments between me and the \r\ngoal, between me and freedom.  Three.  Three is the number of weeks I have \r\nleft in school to complete this six assignments.  Many of you know I\'ve \r\nbeen mad about numerology lately and you know as I know that according to \r\nmy charts, graphs and logic the number should still be nine.  Let me \r\nexplain how I\'ve knocked the fucker down to six.\r\n\r\nTHE END – 2001:\r\n\r\n- Third to Last\r\n9. Wednesday May 2nd – Anthro Paper #4 Due\r\n\r\n- Second to Last\r\n8. Tuesday May 8th – Hist192 - Seminar Presentation\r\n7. Tuesday May 8th – Hist118 – Presentation\r\n6. Wednesday May 16th – Anthro Paper #5 Due\r\n5. Thursday May 17th – Hist192 – Paper Due\r\n4. Thursday May 17th – Hist162 – Paper Due\r\n\r\n- Finals Week\r\n3. Tuesday May 22nd 8:00-10:00 – Hist118a Final\r\n2. Friday May 25th 8:00-10:00   - Ethnics Studies – Final (multiple choice)\r\n1. Friday May 25th 10:15-12:15 - English – Final (3 passages)\r\n\r\n\r\nQuite a load, eh?  I\'m running with 18 units, all hard, all real classes, \r\nno fucking band units, no fucking hornet units and no god damned PE \r\n(excuse me, kinesiology) units.  It\'s a hard path to freedom and their \r\nain\'t no underground railroad coming to save my ass, I\'ve got to get out \r\nalone.  \r\n\r\nSo, I put my nose to the grindstone and brutally eliminated my Anthro \r\nPaper #4 a week and a half early.  This early success led me to easily \r\nslaughtering my Hist192 Presentation, which I wrote the three page paper \r\nand notes for my presentation the next night.  A second victory soon led \r\nme to my third when tonight, I finished my part for our group\'s Hist118 \r\nPresentation.  It\'s a WWI class and I\'ve completed a short documentary for \r\nthe presentation, it\'s really fucking sweet with awesome dogfighting \r\nscenes and the rhythmic power of the William Tell Overture.  While both my \r\npresentations haven\'t been given yet, I\'m still feeling confident that I\'m \r\nready to rock on those motherfuckers.  Leaving only 3 Papers, 3 Finals and \r\n3 weeks.  Six assignments total.  There is a light at the end of the \r\ntunnel.  \r\n\r\nSo yes, Wagar I wrote a new column for Thunt.net.  I hope you\'re happy \r\ncause this is all the creative juice I\'ve got left right now.  Let me see, \r\nis there anything I forgot to do…. Hmmmm.  Nah, no reason to make fun of \r\nthe Hornet today, let those awful fuckers fail their classes, produce \r\ntheir shitrag paper and go out in style like the tasteless fools they \r\nare.  Ok, made fun of Hornet: Check.  Time to go cash in my Campus Engine \r\nstock, oh wait, it\'s worthless.  CE: Check.  Andy\'s comics are sooooo \r\nfunny.  ANDY: Check.  Ok, I think I\'ve done my thunt.netian duties and now \r\nto a restful sleep.  Good night neverneverland. \r\n', '', 20010503230725, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (236, 'A new secret Quentin Tarantino film?', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'I hate to link to ain\'t it cool, but the chance of this being true is \r\nworth the risk.  Did Quentin Tarantino direct Fourty Lashes secretly and \r\nis he going to release it at Cannes?', '', 20010504090006, 'net_interest', 'http://www.aintitcool.com/display.cgi?id=8893');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (237, 'Local Man Exhausted After Long Day Of Video Games', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'SAGINAW, MI--Jon Broskowski, a 32-year-old Saginaw liquor-store clerk, \r\ndescribed himself as "completely wiped" Monday after a long, hard day of \r\nvideo games.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n"I\'m totaled," said Broskowski, tossing his PlayStation 2 controller onto \r\nthe floor following one last "cool-down" game of Madden 2001. "That shit \r\nreally takes it out of you."\r\n', '', 20010505114438, 'net_interest', 'http://www.theonion.com/onion3716/local_man_exhausted.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (238, 'I Have Returned, Baby', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Although I have not been in contact with you in a great many months, let \r\nme assure you that you were in my thoughts every second of every day. As I \r\nate, as I slept, as I showered, and as I folded my laundry, rest assured \r\nthat your fineness was the predominant matter on my mind. Even during \r\nChristmas.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nI will pay for the meal with my Gold Visa, and we will then go to my place \r\nand retire to le boudoir, which is French for "my bedroom." There, as the \r\nmusic of Peabo Bryson plays, I will hit you doggy-style all night long.', '', 20010505115131, 'net_interest', 'http://www.theonion.com/onion3716/i_have_returned_baby.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (239, 'SMC: Summer Movie Prediction', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'from the good folx at <a href=http://www.brunching.com>Brunching \r\nShuttlecocks</a>, comes the Self Made Critic\'s Summer Movie Preview.  I \r\ncan\'t believe how many sequals to stupid movies there are. Mummy 2, Dr. \r\nDoolittle 2, Scary Movie 2, American Pie 2, and Rush Hour 2.  Me thinks \r\nhollywood has run out of new ideas.', '', 20010505115412, 'net_interest', 'http://brunching.com/selfmade/summermovies2001.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (24, 'About: Thunt.net 5', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Thunt.net 5, lovingly refered to as Mellow Yellow struck my mind on the \r\nevening of May 5, 2001 and was designed on the morning of May 6, 2001.  \r\nThe goal was a simplier implemenation of Thunt.net, while still keeping \r\nthe design pretty.  Graphics were virtually removed with the exception of \r\na small printer icon, and perhaps a small e-mail icon.  The redesign soon \r\nspread to the archive and photos sections, and Thunt.net became\r\nunited under a single look.<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nMusical Inspiration:<br>\r\n<BR>\r\n - The Who - Tommy<BR>\r\n - Counting Crows - Recovering the Satelites<BR>\r\n - Paul Oakenfold - Anthems<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n-- Thomas Hunt, 5/6/01, 12:56 am', '', 20010506125630, 'about', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (240, 'Lowest Common Denominator Continues To Plummet', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'As the LCD drops, competition for the stupidity dollar grows ever more \r\nfierce. Entertainment Tonight, once the nation\'s standard-bearer for \r\nhollow, insipid celebrity journalism, has been rendered respectable by the \r\nlikes of National Enquirer TV and E!\'s Mysteries And Scandals. Survivor, \r\nderided by critics upon its debut last year, now stands as the Old Gray \r\nLady of reality television, towering over such crass knock-offs as Boot \r\nCamp and Chains Of Love. Even Hollywood, America\'s primary provider of sub-\r\nliterate pabulum for nearly a century, must compete with hyper-violent \r\nvideo games, Internet sites featuring foul-mouthed animated genitalia, and \r\nmail-order Girls Gone Wild: Sexy Sorority Sweethearts videos for the \r\nlucrative stupid-person market.', '', 20010507113512, 'net_interest', 'http://www.theonion.com/onion3716/denominator_plummets.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (241, 'Thunt.net 5.0 Launched', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Thunt.net 5, lovingly refered to as Mellow Yellow struck my mind on the \r\nevening of May 5, 2001 and was designed on the morning of May 6, 2001.  \r\nThe goal was a simplier implemenation of Thunt.net, while still keeping \r\nthe design pretty.  Graphics were virtually removed with the exception of \r\na small printer icon, and perhaps a small e-mail icon.  The redesign soon \r\nspread to the archive and photos sections, and Thunt.net became\r\nunited under a single look.<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nMusical Inspiration:<br>\r\n<BR>\r\n - The Who - Tommy<BR>\r\n - Counting Crows - Recovering the Satelites<BR>\r\n - Paul Oakenfold - Anthems<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n-- Thomas Hunt, 5/6/01, 12:56 am', '', 20010507191916, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (242, 'fuck school', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'I really don\'t give a flying fuck about school anymore.  I went to my \r\nethnics studies class today.  What a grand waste of an hour and fifteen \r\nminutes of my time.  Later English and anthro will repeat the horrifying \r\nexperience.  Why even bother.  Who fucking cares.  I have seven things \r\nleft to do and none of them rely on class, with the exception of those \r\nfucks who take attendance, which seems to be every fucking teacher I\'ve \r\ngot, I don\'t see any god damned reason for me to attend anymore.  Every \r\nminute, every seconds my thoughts drift back to the road, to freedom, to \r\nsweet oblivion.  To a time when I\'ll sleep as much as I like.  When I \r\nwon\'t have to get dressed and rush to school to be on time for some \r\nbullshit class.  <BR><BR>\r\n\r\nEnough of this madness.  I\'m middle class enough.  I read books and I \r\nwrite pretty well.  Isn\'t that enough for these mad fuckers.  Won\'t they \r\njust leave me alone and let me cruise out these last two weeks in an \r\nanimal house fashion of constant toga parties and mad fat drunken orgies.  \r\nEnough of this false learning.  The seeds have been planted and I\'m ready \r\nto be let loose upon the world.  I\'ve got ideas, I\'ve got goals, plans and \r\nbooks to read.  Enough forced lectures, I\'ll attend the lectures I want to \r\nhear.  Enough forced learning, from now on I\'ll learn what I want to \r\nknow.  If I\'m not interested in your fucking recitation of the problems in \r\nyour school district, I\'ll fucking walk out.  And you won\'t give a fuck \r\neither because you only want to talk to people who support your backwards \r\nass cause, and clearly I\'m not one of them.<BR><BR>\r\n\r\nEnough of your nonsense.  Enough of your ASI elections.  Enough of your \r\nVision and your management opportunities at Krispy Kreme paying a cool \r\n30,000 a year.  I\'m not interested anymore and I don\'t think I ever was.  \r\nYou can have your society with your shiny cars and big houses.  Just give \r\nme the road and a library card.  Your bullshit will never reach me \r\nanymore. \r\n', '', 20010509103950, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (243, 'a dirt path', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'There\'s a dirt path by the biology building and the math/history \r\nbuilding.  The landscape engineers (gardeners) at Sac State decided that \r\ndirt paths were ugly, so they roped off the area and planted grass seed.  \r\nThe various chickens that live on campus pecked the ground and ate the \r\ngrass seed.  When the gardeners removed the ropes, the students began \r\nwalking on the path again and the baby grass was soon pounded into the \r\nearth.  The gardeners wonder why the students don\'t just walk around the \r\ncorner to get to where they\'re going and the students can\'t figure out why \r\nthe gardeners are trying to stop them from walking in a straight line \r\nbetween two points, which is after all, the fastest way to get somewhere.  \r\nPerhaps there is a greater theme at work here.  The gardeners are the type \r\nof people who never take shortcuts and always “keep off the grass”.  While \r\nthe students constantly take shortcuts in whatever they do.  They skim \r\nbooks instead of reading them.  They cut classes.  They cheat on tests.  \r\nThey do their essays the night before they are due.  The mentality of \r\ncollege students and the mentality of gardeners are profoundly different.  \r\nNo doubt, the war over this dirt path will continue by the biology and the \r\nmath/history building.\r\n', '', 20010510081134, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (244, 'Five proffessors worth taking at CSUS', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '<B>Brian Roberts</B> – History – Roberts is a hard-nosed history professor \r\nwho is willing to curse in class.  He has been published and is one of the \r\nfew teachers I’ve ever had who I’ve thought might be smarter than me.  \r\nRoberts teaches history in a way that few others do and helps it to be \r\ninteresting and exciting.  I can’t describe the way that Roberts teaches.  \r\nI can only say how incredible it is.  Unfortunately this recommendation \r\ncomes a little late, as Roberts is leaving to teach in Iowa or some god-\r\nawful Midwestern state.  It’s a major loss for Sac State and the History \r\nDepartment must be filled with fools to let him go.  He’s phenomenal.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<B>Jerry L. Tobey</B> – History – Tobey only returns to campus in the fall \r\nto teach one course: World War II.  And with good reason.  Tobey is an \r\nincredibly brilliant World War II scholar.  When you ask him a detailed \r\nhypothetical question he knows the answer.  Tobey is the kind of teacher \r\nwhen you ask for statistics or more information he rarely has to look it \r\nup and get back to you.  His lectures are perfect and his lecturing style \r\nis calm, cool and calculated.  His tests are organized and fair.  This was \r\none of the few classes where I actually read all of the text books and \r\nenjoyed it.  The books he assigned us were brilliantly written.  Books \r\nsuch as the Pulitzer prize winning <U>Freedom from Fear</u> by David \r\nKennedy, it’s a tome, but it’s amazingly well written.  Also we read \r\n<u>How the allies won</u> by Richard Avery and <u>The Second World War</u> \r\nby John Keegan.  Brilliant authors, brilliant works, brilliant teacher.  I \r\ncannot recommend Tobey enough.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<B>Thomas Strasser</B> – History/Humanities – Strasser takes you on an \r\nOdyssey through the Iliad.  A book that seems boring at first but comes \r\nalive as he forces the class to read aloud.  As a fairly decent reader, I \r\nenjoyed this class immensely.  I learned all about classical Greek and \r\nroman mythology.  Strasser is also a big fan of Woody Allen and you get to \r\nwrite a paper on Mighty Aphrodite.  An excellent film, that fits perfectly \r\ninto the subject of mythology.  He also equated Medea to Pulp Fiction as \r\nin both, you root for the bad guys.  He reminds me of Indiana Jones, he’s \r\nactually been to Greece and Rome on digs, and he speaks Greek.  An \r\nincredible teacher, I don’t know what the fuck he’s doing at Sac State. \r\n(Do not confuse him with Elizabeth Strasser in Anthropology.  She’s not a \r\nbad teacher, but she is a little German troll.)\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<B>Edward Bradley</B> – Math – I hate math.  But his British accent and \r\nsensible teaching style helped me survive this class.  I recall most what \r\nhe said about division by zero, “If you’re dividing by zero” he would say \r\nin his strong British accent, “you’ve got real problems.”  It was classic, \r\nand it helped me through.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<B>Chancey Ridley</B> – English – The man is a bit whacked, but he picked \r\nhis readings well and they proved his point: You must read the beginning, \r\nthe middle, and the end of literature.  The man is a devout structuralist, \r\nand by using <U>Walden</U>, <U>Legend of Sleepy Hollow</U> and even <U>The \r\nAdventures of Huckleberry Finn</U> he proves his point over and over \r\nagain.  Ridley gets on the list because he plans his classes well and when \r\nthere is nothing left to discuss he lets us go early and even cancels \r\nclass.  The students respond to this by doing their work and gain their \r\nrewards.  <BR><BR>\r\n', '', 20010511101047, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (245, 'BoobScan', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '', '', 20010513101748, 'net_interest', 'http://www.boobscan.com');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (246, 'Oh well, whatever, nevermind.', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Welcome to the end, the end of April in the spring of this foul year of \r\nour lord, two thousand and one.  It is a special time, a time of \r\ngraduation.  There\'s something about this time, perhaps it\'s the light \r\nquality of the air or the fact that my college career is coming to an end, \r\nbut for some reason I don\'t care about school anymore.  I simply attend my \r\nclasses to pass the time between now and May 26th, and I\'m not the only \r\none.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nI often ask myself, "Why do I even bother attending class?"  The answer is \r\nbrutally simple: most of my professors have that annoying and degrading \r\nhabit of taking roll.  Of course, they can never seem to tell the \r\ndifference between physical attendance and mental attendance.  Although \r\nsome of my professors are beginning to feel the shift.  The few who \r\nunderstand the dangerous mentality that is starting to form in their \r\nstudents are attempting to combat it with strategies that are reminiscent \r\nof lyrics from the classic Nirvana teen-anthem: "with the lights out, it\'s \r\nless dangerous, here we are now, entertain us."  Unfortunately, my \r\nprofessors lack the captivating power of the now-defunct Seattle based \r\ngrunge band.  My Anthropology professor has been begging us to read the \r\nassigned text for the last two weeks.  So far, her pleas have fallen upon \r\ndeaf ears.  My English professor took a different approach and asked us to \r\ndrink coffee before class, in an attempt to improve class participation.  \r\nAlas, there was little change the next week.  Both my History and Ethnics \r\nStudies professors have begun to augment their lectures with videos and \r\nslides.  However, these valiant attempts have the major downside of \r\nturning the lights out, quickly leaving the truly apathetic among us a \r\nchance to catch up on lost sleep.  Of course, these days sleep isn\'t lost \r\ndue to studying or frantic paper writing, it\'s lost due to video games, \r\nmovies and other such distractions.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nWhy are we so distracted?  What has stolen our passion for \r\nintellectualism?  Simply put, Graduation.  It looms over our heads like \r\nthe caps and gowns we were forced to purchase from ASI at 30 bucks a pop.  \r\nThe real world has us now.  Most of us will soon be shackled in jobs that \r\nwe will hold for the rest of our lives.  A few will again dodge the real \r\nworld and run to the convents of Masters Degrees and Law Schools, but the \r\nsanctuary they seek will only be temporary, the real world will still be \r\nwaiting for these cowards.  A few of us are going to try to refuse the \r\nwhole system entirely.  For us rare breeds the future bears real promise \r\nand perhaps bitter fruit.  We are the Peter Pans of this world and we \r\nstill hope to accomplish the two-fold feat of not growing up and \r\naccomplishing our dreams.  Dreams are strange things, when you\'re deep in \r\nthe shit that is college life; it\'s hard to have any dreams except getting \r\nout.  Your life becomes a day-to-day prison of papers and reading.  \r\nMonotony in our learning system sets in almost immediately as you stop \r\nreading fiction and stick to the hard liquor of textbooks and monographs.  \r\nFresh ideas are quickly discarded in an attempt to match the views of our \r\nprofessors, in pursuit of our new gods: grades. With these new gods, your \r\ndreams are soon left dormant as you dig in for four years of daily \r\ntorture.  Sure, it beats working, don\'t get me wrong, but I didn\'t find \r\nthe experience too enlightening either.  We attend a middle class \r\nconformity factory.  You come in as freaks and weirdoes and you leave as \r\nelite members of the 24% of Americans who have attended college.  You\'re a \r\nperfect candidate for employment and employment is what you\'ll get.  \r\nPerhaps deployment is a better term, as you are deployed into the real \r\nworld like an interchangeable part into Ford\'s assembly line.  Remember \r\nthe lesson learned by factory workers in Ford\'s factories: that \r\ninterchangeable parts are easily replaceable.  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nGraduation looms close on the horizon.  Laziness has taken hold and it is \r\nunlikely that while on this journey to the nirvana of perpetual employment \r\nwill ever break free of this fear.  The fear of the real world is the fear \r\nthat drives our apathy.  This month could be our last chance to goof off \r\nand not do our work without fear of being fired.  But this is how it has \r\nalways been, and always will, until the end.\r\n', '', 20010515185553, 'normal', '');
