INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (252, 'The film you must see: AndyDance', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'At long last you can now experience the horror, the aggravation, the \r\nnearly pornographic: AndyDance.  AndyDance is more than a film about Andy \r\nDancing, it is an experience.  <BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nReactions to AndyDance:\r\n<UL>\r\n<LI>"Andy once taught me to dance.  He rules!" - Matt Brown, Future Ballet \r\nInstructor<br>\r\n<br>\r\n<LI>"As Andy\'s roommate, I know all about AndyDance, he does it almost \r\nevery night. - Joe R, Pornography Enthusiast<br>\r\n<br>\r\n<LI>"SMUD: The power to do more."<br>\r\n<br>\r\n<LI>"I\'ve sampled the AndyDance, it makes me swoon." - Anid<br>\r\n<br>\r\n</ul>\r\n<center>\r\n<a href=\'http://thunt.net/video/andydance.mov\'><img \r\nsrc=\'http://www.tvdance.com/andyrichter/4a.gif\' border=0 \r\nalt=\'andydance\'></a><br>\r\n<a href=\'http://thunt.net/video/andydance.mov\'>Experience AndyDance: Click Here</a><br>\r\nEncoded in <a href=\'http://quicktime.com\'>QuickTime 4.0</a><br>\r\n</center>\r\n\r\n', '', 20010523165817, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (253, '10:30 on May 25th', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '10:30 on May 25th.  The clock chimed and I was free.  I earned my freedom \r\nby signing my name on my English Test.  The last test that I will take for \r\na quite a while.  The taste of freedom is a lukewarm Crossanwich, leftover \r\nfrom breakfast this morning, but I’m certain that its greasy taste is not \r\nthe true flavor of freedom, only a precursor of what is to come.', '', 20010525104754, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (254, 'Girls Gone Wild', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'The short film event of the century is here.  Two polls ago, you demanded \r\nmore porn on Thunt.net and now you’ve got it!  Thunt.net is proud to \r\npresent: The State Hornet: GIRLS GONE WILD!  <BR>\r\n<BR>\r\n<center>\r\n<a href=http://thunt.net/video/girlsgonewild.mov>Click here to View</a><Br>\r\n<a href=http://quicktime.com>Encoded in QuickTime</a><br>\r\n<br>\r\n</center>\r\n', '', 20010529200835, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (255, 'Swimming in Boredom in Vacaville', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Good evening thunt.neters.  I just wanted to drop a brief article in and \r\nlet you guys know what I’m up to.  A lot of people have been \r\nasking, “what’s going to happen to Thunt.net, now that you won’t have the \r\nhornet to make fun of?”  The answer is a simple one.  Thunt.net has never \r\nbeen just about making fun of the hornet.  If you browse the archives, \r\nespecially the “flashbacks” section (pre-thunt.net database), you’ll learn \r\nthat Thunt.net has been about making fun of lots of other things besides \r\nthe hornet.  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nNow, on to what I’ve been up to.  I’ve been hanging out at my parents \r\nhouse for a while.  Living in Vacaville is pretty damn lame.  Most of my \r\nfriends live in Sacramento or Davis, and now I’m stuck in Vacaville, so \r\nneedless to say I haven’t been too social lately.  Most of my time is \r\nspent reading, watching movies and of course swimming.  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nAlso, I’ve been watching a great deal of sports lately.  My father and \r\nbrother are interested in the Stanley Cup finals, which I’ve been \r\nfollowing with minor interest.  But what I’ve found more interesting than \r\nhockey is basketball.  I’ve always been a bit of a closet Laker fan.  I \r\nwas a fan back in the eighties when Kareem Abdul Jabar, Magic Johnson, \r\nJames Worthy, etc, played.  I decided to stop watching basketball the next \r\nyear when they said they were going to introduce expansion teams.  I’ve \r\nnever liked expansion teams and I’ve never looked back.  But these new \r\nLakers, Shaq and Kobe are incredible.  I tuned in to the finals to watch \r\ndomination.  I wanted to see the amazing power of Shaq and Kobe that I had \r\nseen in the Kings series, where I won a handy amount betting against the \r\nhome team, and the brilliant work that I had seen against the Spurs when \r\nthe Lakers were down by twenty points at the half and came back to win as \r\nif they were playing a friendly game in the park.  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nBasketball itself as a sport is a mild interest to me.  Several aspects of \r\nthe game intregiue me.  The fact that it is constant warfare, point to \r\npoint is extremely interesting.  The quickness of the game is like true \r\nwarfare, where battles do not stop for commercial breaks.  I enjoy the \r\nfact that the players play both ways, the same men having to be gifted at \r\nboth defense and offense.  It is still rather dull to watch sometimes, but \r\nthe brilliance of the Shaq/Kobe combination makes the game seem like a \r\nwell rehearsed ballet.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nI just saw a commercial for the French Open and it seemed to be a lot more \r\nabout Jennifer Capriati’s nipples than tennis.  But maybe that was just \r\nme.  Of course I do know who Anna Kornocova is, despite my lack of \r\ninterest in that sport.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nI digress.  I was shocked and still shocked to see the Lakers crumble and \r\nloose to the Sixers in the first game of the series.  I am even more \r\nshocked to watch this second game as the Lakers are blowing their twelve \r\npoint lead with Shaq in danger of fouling out.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nOne thing I really don’t like about basketball is the insistence of \r\nfouling as strategy.  Right now, both of the teams are past the foul \r\nlimit, and the game seems to hinge on Shaq fouling out as yesterday it \r\nhinged on Motombo fouling out.  It just seems un-sportsmanlike.  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nThe two series have been interested.  The Colorado Avalanche should have \r\nsteamrolled the New Jersey Devils, as they did last night, 4-0.  But they \r\nhave crumbled and cracked, some even laying blame on the goalie of all \r\ngoalies, Patrick Roy.  The Lakers seem to be on the way to doing the same \r\nthing.  Rumored to be considering a sweep of the Finals, as they swept the \r\nrest of the playoffs this year, the Lakers are off to a incredibly slow \r\nstart in this series.  Certainly the Lakers dropping the early games and \r\ncoming back with a vengeance will make for an interesting series, but as a \r\nminor Lakers fan I’d just rather seem them beat the hell of Iverson and \r\nhis Sixers.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nAnother neat thing about the two series is that they both have fancy \r\ncameras that they are trying out to mimic the Super Bowl’s matrix-esque \r\ncamera.  Hockey has Panasonic scan vision, allowing them to make the \r\nentire rink matrixey and rotate around the puck when needed.  They also \r\nhave a really neat goalie cam, which allows a clear view of where the puck \r\nentered or where the goalie was successful.  Basketball also has a neat \r\ncamera mounted on top of the basket that seems to be a wide angle lens, \r\nallowing the announcers to pause the camera and scan back and forth, \r\nmonitoring where every player is and where the play broke down or \r\nsucceeded.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nThese reality TV shows are really pissing me off and they aren’t even on \r\nyet.  Fear Factor, SpyTV, etc.  The rumor I heard is that they were \r\nplanned to keep the TV schedule interesting during the writer’s strike, \r\nbut unfortunately the strike was avoided and now these network slime balls \r\nare making the public suffer them regardless.  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nI think I’ve ranted my rant for today.  I’ll be uploading this update \r\nusing a blisteringly slow 56k dialup connection.  Who am I kidding saying \r\n56k, I’m more likely to connect at 28.8 or 33.3.  Well, I hope you’re all \r\nenjoying your summer as much as I’m enjoying my fun in Vacaville. \r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<I>fyi: the Lakers did hold on and win Game 2, 98-89.  But don’t kid \r\nyourself, it was a hell of a lot closer than it looks.  What a great \r\nseries of Basketball it’s turned out to be.  </I>\r\n', '', 20010608210747, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (256, 'Moulin Rouge', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '	I went in to hate this movie.  I wasn’t really sure what it was \r\nabout from the confusing trailers.  I assumed it was a period piece about \r\nburlesque houses and sex, and  that it was rated PG-13, never a good sign \r\nfor a film about sex.  I read Matt’s review of it on <a \r\nhref=http://www.angryteaparty.com>ATP</a> and while he gave it an \r\nincredibly favorly view, I assumed he was smoking crack.  Like I said, I \r\nwent to hate.  Unfortunately I couldn’t.  Frankly speaking, they had me \r\nfrom the first b&w shot of Paris where Lehrman began panning through the \r\nstreets maintaining his b&w crummy looking film, but performing visual \r\ntricks we know to be only of the digital age.  That was all it \r\ntook.<BR><BR>\r\n	The film could have been a major failure.  The idea of the man \r\nwriting the story as he remembers it happening is as old as Murder she \r\nwrote, and older.  But under Lehrman’s brilliant directing, the film \r\nshines as every shot is hand crafted, every cut is well timed, and the \r\nmusic, well the music deserves an entire paragraph to itself, and I will \r\nsee to that. <BR><BR>\r\n	The music is incredible.  Basically the film uses the 1900s Paris \r\nBurlesque house as a theater where they do for popular music, what \r\nShakespeare in Love did for obscure lines from Shakespeare.  I’m not going \r\nto reveal any of the songs mixed into the medleys, because I believe that \r\nwould ruin the pure joy and surprise of hearing them start talking what \r\nsounds like lyrics, but the obscurity is so that you don’t recognize \r\nthem.  Then they break into the chorus and your heart leaps out as you \r\nrealize the brillance at which the song has been mixed into the film. \r\n<BR><BR>\r\n	The movie is like the Rocky Horror Picture show because you want \r\nto sing and dance along with all of the songs, but unlike Rocky, this \r\nmovie is actually good.  <BR><BR>\r\n	Fuck good, this movie is great.  I plan to see it a few more times \r\nin the theater.  And when it gets to the cheap theater, I might go every \r\nday for a while, or just sit there all day and watch it a few more times.  \r\nAlso, I plan to get the soundtrack, post haste (using mp3s of course). \r\n<BR><BR>\r\n	Problems with the film:  Yes there are some.  But they are minor.  \r\nNicole Kidman’s nipples slip out of her dress a couple times during the \r\nfilm.  No wait.  That’s not a problem.  There is a long scene that reminds \r\nme of Yoda acting, but then perhaps that’s because Ewan McGregor is in the \r\nfilm and he was also in Episode I (btw: this film is ten times the film \r\nthat Episode I was, because Lehrman knows where to put the camera and \r\ndoesn’t have a wookie up his butt, like some directors).  Also whenever \r\nLehrman zoomed in on a building, and would then disolve into the inside, \r\nwere clear homages to Orson Welles’ classic Citizen Kane.  The film is cut \r\na little fast, but unlike other former-music video directors, Lehrman \r\nknows when to slow down the cutting and tell a story. \r\n<BR><BR>\r\n	Moulin Rouge is an incredible film.  Drop everything you are doing \r\nand go see it.  Right now.  Don’t check the message board, go see the \r\nfilm.  Go now! Go!  I’m going to stop typing now, because you should \r\nalready be on your way to the theater.   \r\n', '', 20010611123800, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (257, 'Portland Bound', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Tuesday June 26th our hero will depart on a most epic voyage.  An airplane \r\n(Well, it\'s a big pretty white plane with a red stripe, curtains at the \r\nwindows, wheels, and it just looks like a big Tylenol!) will carry our \r\nhero to Portland, Oregon.  Land of trees, rain and Phil.  Our hero will be \r\nvisiting Phillip Holmstrand in the beautifully designed, well-planned \r\nmetropolis.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nPortland is a fantastic city, home to the world\'s biggest tree, the \r\nworld\'s biggest logging company, and the world\'s biggest paper mill.  The \r\ngirls of Portland are known for their buck-teeth and strange desire for \r\nextra strength toothpicks.  Most inhabitants of the City of Portland spend \r\ntheir afternoons playing Quake III on the internet while watching Blade \r\nRunner on DVD.  They live by the river, which is so polluted it is a \r\nnationally recognized superfund site (way to go Portland, New Jersey won\'t \r\nknow what hit \'em).  Portland is also home to the Corporate GIS project, \r\nor Graphical Information Services.  GIS is not just a neat way of saying \r\nJIZZ, it\'s also the first step towards the American Dream: The \r\ntotalitarian police state.  Yes, that\'s right, with accurate mapping tied \r\ninto a satellite monitoring system you will be able to stop even Will \r\nSmith of Enemy of the State, or maybe even Warren Beatty in The Parallax \r\nView.  But there\'s one thing it won\'t stop and that\'s wheelchair-bound \r\nsuperman Christopher Reeves.  Only kryptonite and horseys (drawn by Polli) \r\ncan stop that elderly rear-windowed Superman.  But perhaps a short reading \r\nfrom Nietzsche\'s Man and Superman would stop him.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nYes, Portland is a fantastic city, and I look forward to visiting it \r\nagain.  Which means I\'ll have to cancel my plans to sit on my ass and \r\nwatch MTV on my 3D screen while jacking off, I mean drawing.  No, wait, \r\nthose aren\'t my plans.  Those are someone else\'s plans.  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nIn other news: went to the Wagar-discovered classic Cornerstone Restaurant \r\ntoday.  Fantastic as always.  Even discovered to my joy they have a "Beat \r\nLit" section in the groovy bookstore next door.  Having recently listened \r\nto On the Road by Kerouac, read Junky and Queer by Burroughs, I\'m starting \r\nto really get a feel for this beat lit and I like it. Oh Yeah.  Potato \r\nplatter, can\'t beat that, only 6.95! For a limited time only.  Don\'t smoke \r\ncrack.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nPeace out. \r\n', '', 20010622131446, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (258, 'No Sneeze Cloned Cats', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '', '', 20010627225059, 'net_interest', 'http://dailynews.yahoo.com/h/nm/20010627/sc/health_cats_dc_2.html');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (259, 'Portland, OR', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Well, I\'m in Portland now.  Survived the flight and everything.  I wasn\'t \r\ntoo worried cause I saw these two 3-5 year old blonde girls and I knew \r\nthat since they were on the plane with me there was no way that we could \r\ncrash because God would never kill people that young, although he has been \r\nknown to kill that young and younger (plague of egypt, first borne sons \r\nacross the land), but the thought passified me during the rather brief 59 \r\nminute flight.  Upon arival I took a shuttle to Phil\'s American Psycho \r\nApartment (see new photos in <a \r\nhref=http://thunt.net/photo/>thunt.net/photo</a>).  It\'s really nice.  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nI\'m torn between trying to write some shit, studying for the GRE (I\'m \r\nthinking about getting a masters in creative writing) and goofing off.  \r\nRight now, I\'m definately goofing off.  Weezer on the speakers, Twisted \r\nMetal Black for Ps2 on the tv, wearing a trashed white t-shirt and shorts, \r\ngood times.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nGood news: I\'m on a good internet connection again! WOO! And you know what \r\nthat means, a fucking assload of new photos in <a \r\nhref=http://thunt.net/photo/>thunt.net/photo</a>.  Check em out, you may \r\nsee yourself in pictures.  Also I checked out a cool program called <a \r\nhref=http://www.musiccity.com>Morpheous</a> (recommened by Matt, Joe).  \r\nIt\'s like Scour, but unlike Scour, it hasn\'t been shut down yet.  So far, \r\nI\'ve pulled down the South Park Shit episode, a few simpsons episodes, \r\nincluding the Monorail Episode (Classic Conan O\' Brien script) and much \r\nmuch more.  Check it out. <BR><BR>\r\nL8r', '', 20010628131841, 'normal', '');
