INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (261, 'monday', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '	It’s Monday.  I’m sitting around watching friends on the computer \r\nhere.  This show is pretty stupid, but on the computer it lacks commercial \r\ninterruptions.  But hell, what else am I gonna do.  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\n	I don’t know what’s wrong with thunt.net, but I want to assure you \r\nI’m looking into it.  It seems like some of my databases work and some \r\ndon’t.  I’m looking into fixing those that don’t work and doing nothing to \r\nthose that do.  This database you’re looking at here happens to work, so \r\nI’m going to update anyway.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n	Courtney Cox is getting ugly.  I don’t know why.  This show is \r\nfrom the end of the season.  I think Denise Richards is guest starring in \r\nthis episode.  The show seems to be about the fact that Denise Richards is \r\nhotter than Courtney Cox.  This is true.  Now Joey is circumcised and is \r\npretending not to be.  Pretty wild.  I don’t think I’ve ever seen anyone \r\nwho looks bad in long hair, but Courtney Cox looks like shit.  This is \r\ngreat, they just stole Monica’s money to pay for her party.  And now Ross \r\nis attracted to his cousin.  Ewww.  Nothing seems to be funnier than \r\nincest.  I guess.  Uh oh.  Ross is going crazy and he’s going after her.  \r\nThat’s not good.  Heh heh.  Shut down. HA.  I like it on TV when everyone \r\nruins everything and the other person says “that’s really sweet and \r\nconsiderate.”   \r\n<BR><BR>\r\n	Oop.  Friends is over.  Thanks for coming, and god bless us \r\neveryone!\r\n \r\n', '', 20010702171800, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (262, 'The truth about Capitalism', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Having just watched Dennis Miller make an ass out of himself, saying that \r\nwe should drill in Alaska so he can keep his stupid fucking SUV, I thought \r\nI would try to speak some truth for a while.  Can’t say I’ve heard any \r\ntruth anywhere lately.  So, here goes.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nWhat people have to understand is that business does not care about them.  \r\nIf a business can make a profit selling a product that kills people, they \r\nwill (tobacco).  If a business can make a product selling a product that \r\ndestroys peoples brain cells and causes car accidents, they will \r\n(alcohol).  If a business can sell a food product with no nutritional \r\nvalue whatsoever that makes its customers fat, they will (Twinkies).\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nPeople seem to believe that because businesses are made up of people, they \r\nwill care about people.  This is wrong.  For some reason the people who \r\nare in business forget the fact that they themselves are people and do \r\nwhatever is necessary to gain a profit.  They do not worship a religious \r\nGod figure, nor do they give a damn for human life.  They worship profit.  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nBusiness will wipe out species, destroy the rainforest, make Americans \r\nfat, lazy and complacent to make a profit.  They will fix elections, kill \r\nmillions, create monopolies, crush the competition, and destroy downtown \r\nshops to make a profit.  There is nothing that has stopped business from \r\ntheir holy duties.  Imagine a man wants to pay your company to make a \r\nweapon that will destroy the entire world.  You as a person might say “No \r\nthanks, I don’t want to be in anyway responsible for destroying the entire \r\nworld.  That would be bad.  I’ll just stick to being a human who didn’t \r\ndestroy the planet.”  But businesses such as Lockheed Martin, Boeing, Aero \r\njet, Bell Helicopter, etc, said “Will we make a profit?”  The Government \r\nsaid “Of course you will, this is America, after all.”  And the businesses \r\nsaid, “Ok, we’ll make neato bombers, submarines, missiles and other cool \r\nstuff that will destroy the world.  We don’t have a conscious and we don’t \r\ngive a fuck whether little Johnny gets to graduate elementary school or \r\nnot.  As long as we make a profit we will fuck every single human being on \r\nthe planet in the cornhole.  And while we’re at it, we’d love to knock off \r\na few more species.  Too many god damned caribou on this planet anyway.  \r\nAnd besides, when is the last time that caribou have helped us turn a \r\nprofit?  How about never.  Fuck those stupid caribou bastards.  Let’s tear \r\nup their natural environment in Alaska to dig for oil so that Americans \r\ncan have SUVs and pay less than $2 a gallon for gas.  SUVs are good \r\nbecause they pollute the planet reducing the amount of breathable air and \r\nhelping the greenhouse effect, they destroy small gas conserving cars in \r\naccidents, and they can drive OFF ROAD!  Of course, you should always keep \r\nyour SUV shiney and clean because you’re a disgusting yuppie swine.  And \r\nbesides you can’t even drive OFF ROAD anymore because we paved the whole \r\nfucking earth to make it easier for us to transport Twinkies in-between \r\nstates so that all of America could have a grease puff to eat while they \r\nwatch TV.  And while we were setting up their TV signals, we put enough \r\nradio waves in the air to give everyone brain cancer so that we could make \r\nmoney on cancer treatments.  We want all of your money and if we have to \r\nkill you to get it, that’s fine with us.  Because we’re American \r\nBusiness.  And in America, the business of America is business.  Fuck the \r\nPeople!\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<I>this message was brought to you by the George W. Bush drill in Alaska, \r\nand burn the stupid caribou breeding grounds, those fucking animals never \r\ndid nuthin fur me, and I’m the President now, just like my daddy \r\nFoundation.</I> \r\n', '', 20010704012138, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (263, 'Rocket Man', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Good evening everyone.  I\'ve been a bit of a bad webmaster lately and it \r\nseems to be the beginning of a trend rather than the end of one.  I\'m not \r\nwriting much lately, not just for you guys, but for everyone.  Mainly I\'ve \r\nbeen sitting around chewing cough drops, being sick, attending weddings \r\nand sitting around.  A lot of sitting around.  I feel andy-lazy, but I\'m \r\nstill keeping a relatively normal time schedule, seeing daylight most \r\neveryday.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nThere\'s an awesome "behind the music" on now about Green Day and the \r\ntrouble they had once being a punk band, and then becoming popular.  I \r\nenjoyed their first album greatly, Insomniac, their second was fair, \r\nNimrod, their third was excellent.  Their fourth, Warning is still growing \r\non me.  It\'s an interesting album, the title track "Warning" being \r\nexcellent, "Minority" is also excellent, but the rest of the album has a \r\nvery curious feel that seems rather polka-like.  Perhaps polka isn\'t the \r\nright word but it just has an odd carnival type feeling that I just can\'t \r\nshake.  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nThe show just focused on "Good Riddance", a very popular track from \r\nNimrod.  I\'m torn as to whether or not GR was a good idea or not.  They \r\nsaid it became incredibly popular, being played on the last episode of \r\nSeinfeld, the World Series, at proms and graduations.  Which is good, but \r\nI feel popularity has thoroughly ruined excellent songs such as Imagine, \r\nWe Will Rock You and of course We Are the Champions (author\'s note: \r\nbecause they were back to back on Queen\'s Greatest Hits (red), radio \r\nstations always play them together, despite the fact that they were \r\noriginally released by Queen on different albums in different periods of \r\nthe band\'s development.  It\'s true, look it up: <a \r\nhref=http://www.allmusic.com>allmusic.com</a>.  Green Day tried to come \r\noff like releasing GR was a "punk" thing to do because it was the \r\nunexpected.  I grant them that.  GR is an amazing song that I would never \r\nhad expected from Green Day.  Actually I believe it too beautiful to \r\nbelong to the band that once sang of "taking all you down with me, \r\nexplosives duct taped to my spine…"  (Please note, I know there are more \r\nthan four Green Day albums, from their punk-pre-popular days.  I have the \r\nalbums but haven\'t absorbed them yet and I just wish to speak of the \r\npopular albums for today\'s discussion.)\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nThe show has shifted gears now, it seems to be an advertisement for their \r\nnew album Warning, which is really too bad because I was enjoying the \r\ncontroversy of the past.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nOn to new topics.  Do you think the Elton John song Rocket Man is about \r\nheroin?  I do.  Or at least drugs anyway.  Rocket seems to imply Needle, \r\nyou shoot it, you fill it with fuel, it\'s pointy,  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nExamples:\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n"Got my bags packed, pre-flight" (loaded the needle).  <BR>\r\n"It\'s lonely out in space" (high).  <BR>\r\n"I\'m gonna be high as a kite by then" (obvious). <BR>\r\n"till touchdown brings me down again to find" (the after-crash, and \r\nrestarting).   <BR>\r\n"I\'m not the man they think I am at all" (hiding the addiction).  "<BR>\r\n<BR>\r\nAnd this part about Mars, he must be high.  What the fuck else could he be \r\ntalking about.  And they play this song in Supermarkets, for chrissake.  \r\nOf course I was at a party recently where full grown adults played Bob \r\nDylan\'s Rainy Day Women ("everybody must get stoned") as background music \r\nfor a 50th anniversary.  Nobody really noticed, which is ironic \r\nconsidering the stir the song made upon it\'s release.  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nI was at the supermarket today.  Did you know there is a book version of \r\nthe movie Pearl Harbor?  Can you imagine that?  It\'s like making a book \r\nversion to Armageddon, Bad Boys or Coyote Ugly.  Perhaps you would enjoy a \r\nbook version of the Van Damme flick Hard Target.  Excerpt:\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n"Mark (Van Damme) rose up and kicked the other guy.  He screamed in agony, \r\nbut then Van Damme, oops I mean Mark, spun around and kicked yet another \r\nguy.  The kicking went on unabated for about an hour and a half, perhaps \r\nless if you discount the credits.  But during the opening credits, Mark, \r\nwho is a part eskimo-indian-police officer did kick the shit out of some \r\nother guys because they said that Casablanca was a better movie than Gone \r\nwith the Wind, which in Mark\'s fucked up world is like saying that Coke is \r\nbetter than Pepsi."\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nIt goes on and on about the kicking.  One would think the author just \r\nsmoked some weed and then watched the picture on cable a few times.  Which \r\nit actually says on the dust jacket, John Smitthe is a unemployed carpet \r\nshampooer living in Torrance, CA.  He enjoys smoking weed and watching Van \r\nDamme movies.  He hopes to make a book of some other Van Damme movies in \r\nthe future.  The idea sits fine with Jean Claude because he cannot read.  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nWith all the other shit that is coming out in the theaters, that Planet of \r\nthe Apes movie is starting to look better and better.  Of course I want to \r\nsee the originals first, not that I don\'t know the plot or it hasn\'t been \r\nruined for me a hundred times, but it\'s important to see Charlton Soylent-\r\nGreen-Is-Best-Used-Without-a-trigger-lock-while-shooting-moses-in-the-ben-\r\nhur Heston scream at "damn, dirty apes".  Ironic to see a man of the cloth \r\ntalking about evolution so plainly.  Of course if we went back to being \r\napes that would be de-evolution, which I\'m certain Charlton as a good \r\nRepublican would be in favor of.  Anything to get back to good old fashion \r\nfamily values where blacks had no rights and women were treated as \r\nproperty.  And the man has a point, I think America would look great if we \r\nhad a few pyramids of our own to compete with the so called "Great" \r\npyramids of Giza.  No, the Luxor doesn\'t count.  Any place that has a non-\r\n24hour buffet must feel my wrath.  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nI think I have rambled enough so I\'ll take my leave of you.  Expect more \r\nrambling in the future, and some hot lesbian action on the message board.  \r\n(gotta plug the board, right?)  For the best Thunt.net experience, sign up \r\nfor the mailing list so you don\'t have to check everyday when I write, \r\nlike every week, and remember use only as directed. (do what I say.)\r\n', '', 20010716005036, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (264, 'Thunt.net Presents: Where are they now?', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Thinking back in time, Thunt.net would like to take a step backwards in \r\ntime to see whatever happened to some of those people who ran for ASI \r\noffice.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<B>Art Pimmentale</B> – Art has quit his position as President to work as \r\nat used car lot.  During the day he sells Hondas and Fords, and at night \r\nhe parties down at TGI Fridays, the ultimate place to party.  His drink is \r\na rum and coke, which he usually drinks with a side of coke.  In the \r\nfuture he plans to run for office again and then quit to get stoned.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<B>Champagne Turismo</B> - Champagne didn’t seem to learn from her defeat \r\nin the recent ASI election.  She has once again teamed up with her old pal \r\nDavid “Born Looser” Sommers.  That’s right.  Teamed up with Sommers.  You \r\nknow his dating record! Hubba Hubba!  But wait!  He’s not dating her!  \r\nThey’re living together!  But wait again!  They’re not LIVING together; \r\nthey’re just living together.  So it does prove that like fine wine, \r\nChampagne has good taste.  She’s sleeping with another ASI hanger-oner; we \r\nregret that we cannot reveal his name here, as decorum prevents it.  But \r\nlet’s just say that his initials are JB.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<B>Jason Bryant</b> - This former ASI President looked to be having a \r\nstring of bad luck.  As you recall his candidate for EIC, Brendan \r\nWonnacott was dropped like a bad habit (insert bad habit of your choice, \r\nnose picking, ass picking, picking up skanks, picking up hitchhikers, \r\npicking up dime sacks, picking up the pieces, etc).  Additionally, his \r\ngolden boy David Sommers and his Students First slate turned up Students \r\nLast at the polls, leaving Bryant shit out of luck in the worst way.  But \r\nthe man may be down, but he sure isn’t out.  Rumor has it that he dumped \r\nhis old service provider (although she was loved by one artist) and has \r\nsigned on with a new provider.  But now Bryant knows how important it is \r\nto have your own wine cellar.  It’s said that the man is now having all he \r\ncan drink.  Which in some circles is believed to be ten times better than \r\nall you can eat, which I’m told he’s having as well…\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<B>Chairman Sommers</B> - Apparently the new living arrangements are \r\nkeeping the Chairman in touch with his roots.  Or at least in touch with \r\nthe dyed blonde roots of some sorority sweethearts who like to hang out \r\nwith the infamous Champagne.  So in that department, things are well for \r\nMr. Sommers.  However when it comes to jobs, Mr. Sommers is in desperate \r\nneed of employment!  He’s been out of work for over six months now.  All \r\nhe does is sit around and smoke cigars, drink brandy and screw whores.  \r\nHis friends and family have tried to talk him out of it but the man is \r\ninflexible.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nSo that about raps it up for the ASI candidates of days past.  Let’s thank \r\nthem all for having legs as long as the Radio City Rock-ettes, tongues as \r\nlong as lounge lizards and mouths as big as Hoover vacuum cleaners.  Never \r\ngo back in time and count the number of exclamation marks used in this \r\narticle.  You don’t want to know!\r\n', '', 20010724155141, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (265, 'States in Review', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', '<B>California</B> – The boring flat farmlands of Dixon and Vacaville were soon transformed into the urban sprawl of Sacramento as I flew across the golden state.  The towering trees of Auburn and Truckee quickly replaced the sprawl.  I then zoomed across the state line into…\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<B>Nevada</B> – After Reno, Nevada became one long stretch of desert.  The mountains flew by as the hours dragged on.  Gas stations with slot machines and rest areas seem to be the only cultural attraction of this dull state.  As I reached Windover I saw the last bastion of legalized gambling and sinful debauchery.  The casinos seemed to scream out "This is your last chance to sin before Utah!"  I ignored their lecherous cries and passed through two huge rock formations as I entered…\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<B>Utah</B> – Past the rock formations the ground was covered with salt in every direction.  The salt flats are more immense than you can imagine.  It looked like snow, but I knew it was too hot outside for any snow to exist.  I stopped at the first available rest area.  A mean sign warned me to be on the look out for Snakes and Scorpions.  Snakes are bad enough, but in combination with scorpions it was clear that I wasn\'t going to spend much time at this rest stop.  I walked out onto the flats and performed all the scientific tests I could think of on this unusual substance.  When I walked on the salt it crackled and broke, it was not soft like snow but brittle.  I smelled it and tasted it.  It was salt, and it was everywhere.  After I got out of the salt flats, Utah wasn\'t as exciting.  Nice mountains and brilliant tactical design of nestling the cities right up against the mountains (see Salt Lake, Provo).  A few days after my arrival in Provo, I drove through the canyon into…\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<B>Wyoming</B> – For years I have said that Wyoming does not exist.  That it is a government conspiracy.  The facts are: It\'s a perfect rectangle.  You have never met anyone who is from Wyoming.  You have never visited Wyoming; you just think you did because they injected you with mind-bending drugs that made you think you were in Wyoming while they did vicious tests on you without your knowledge.  Now, having driven through Wyoming I\'m not entirely sure that this is false.  There are some really nice mountains with flat tops that I think are called mesas.  Also I passed the continental divide a few times, not sure what that means, but I\'ve been there now.  There are no major attractions in Wyoming.  With the exception of "Little America", a gas station, restaurant, auto repair rest area type place that I passed as I first entered the state.  After I passed it they immediately began advertising for the next "Little America", which was over three hundred miles away in Cheyenne.  It must be pretty pathetic to assume that everyone on that road is going all the way to Cheyenne.  Unfortunately for the tourist bureau in Wyoming I found this to be true.  I flew towards Cheyenne occasionally stopping for gas and playing cat and mouse with a hot girl from the University of Wyoming who drove a white Toyota Celica.  Of course this could have been a dream, I\'m not entirely sure that any of it happened, I was after all "in Wyoming", at least until I crossed the border into…\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<B>Colorado</B> – At first glance Colorado looks very similar to Wyoming.  The mountains are a little taller and you don\'t feel woozy anymore, as the government has stopped injecting you with drugs.  I haven\'t seen much of Colorado yet.  Ft. Collins, where I\'m staying with my good friend Ben is very close to the northern border of Colorado.  I plan to see Denver sometime soon and that may enhance my description of this state.  Although instead of a parade to celebrate my arrival, we had a brief but very strong rainstorm.  The rain came down diagonally as it was blown by a great wind.  We had to close all the windows and batten down the hatches of the apartment, but we weathered the storm and went out after for dinner.  It left the air clean and the temperature nice and cool.  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nAfter dinner we returned to Ben\'s apartment, which is fucking huge and watched a movie named Sugar and Spice that could only be described as "god awful".  It could have been a fun high school type movie where cheerleaders rob a bank, but unfortunately the writer and director took themselves seriously and made a unmatchable cross between gross out over the top humor that fails, and lame attempts to be poignant.  It\'s filmed in scope (2:35:1 aspect ratio, really wide), which is all wrong for the picture (scope is usually used for epic pictures such as Lawrence of Arabia, The Godfather and 2001), and the director uses it like a retarded child trying to eat with chopsticks.  Shot by shot the picture is horrifying as characters talk directly into the camera and scenes that feel 100% like dream sequences turn out to be real.  It\'s just that bad.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nThanks for journeying with me on Thunt.net – States in Review.  I\'ll have the pictures up soon, so you can experience the trip in full color.  Thanks for reading.\r\n', '', 20010801124037, 'normal', '');
INSERT INTO thuntnet_archive VALUES (266, 'New! New! New!', 'Thomas Hunt', 'thunt@thunt.net', 'Good morning everyone.  I\'ve got lots of new stuff for you today at \r\nThunt.net.  And now with no further ado, new stuff!\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<a href=http://thunt.net/photo>NEW: thunt.net/photo</a> – We\'ve got new \r\nphotos in the <a href=http://thunt.net/photo>photo section</a>.  Lots of \r\nem.  Highlights include Devil\'s Tower & Mt. Rushmore, featuring Thunt \r\nriding a gas station dinosaur and much much more.  Also included is a cute \r\ntour of Downtown Ft. Collins, which has a place that sells "swell food".  \r\nI kid you not.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\n<a href=http://thomashunt.com>NEW: Thomashunt.com</a> – A whole new \r\nwebsite is up at our sister site <a \r\nhref=http://thomashunt.com>Thomashunt.com</a>.  I think it\'s nice looking \r\nand I just implemented the database last night so now it will be easy to \r\nupdate.  Check it out.\r\n<BR><BR>\r\nNEW: Story – Man, what is it with cops anyway.  Ben and I were driving \r\nback from South Dakota when a cop pulls us over.  He starts with the \r\ntypical cop question "you boys know why I pulled you over?"  "Was it the \r\nfive pounds of uncut black tar heroin in the trunk?"  "Nope, u was going \r\n39 in a 25."  "Well no shit.  Imagine people coming off a highway into \r\nyour redneck town and still going highway speed.  Amazing what can happen \r\nwhen you don\'t put any signs up you cocksucking sob."  "Can I see your \r\ndriver\'s license?"  "Why, never seen one before?"  "You boys been \r\ndrinking?"  "Yeah, it\'s nine o\'clock so we decided to get drunk and do \r\nLusk, Wyoming.  That\'s what all the kids are doing these days."  "Well, \r\nI\'m going to let you go.  Go a bit slower next time."  "Oh, thanks \r\nofficer, you\'re so great, Shakespeare must have been writing about you \r\nwhen he wrote \'with form and moving how express and admirable, with action \r\nhow like an angel, with apprehension how like a God.\'   You really are \r\nthat great.  Of course why did you pull us over if you weren\'t going to \r\ngive us a ticket, having trouble getting it up with the wife and needed to \r\nfeel powerful again?  I see.  Totally understandable.  Have a nice day \r\nofficer."  \r\n<BR><BR>\r\nWe sure were lucky; if we were driving my car (california plates) or I was \r\ndriving (california license) he would have thrown the book at us for \r\nsure.  Stupid redneck back country cops.  Can\'t wait till they\'re all \r\nreplaced with robocops.  Robocop may have had a Frankenstein complex, but \r\nat least he was polite.  "Thank you for your cooperation."\r\n\r\n\r\n', '', 20010807081136, 'normal', '');
